<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0716 12-09 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,0729</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Snow In The Central Appalachians</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Tennessee plane crash,
traffic deaths in Virginia; picks up 4th graf pvs: ``There's just .
..</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy snow fell on the central Appalachians during the morning
Friday, and high wind blowing out of the desert over southern
California fanned brush fires that destroyed homes.
   Up to 10 inches of snow fell in West Virginia, over the Mountain
State's southern mountains and over the coal fields near the
Virginia border. Up to 10 inches also fell across the mountains of
southwestern Virginia.
   In Tennessee, a twin-engine airplane carrying 40 pounds of
cocaine and $7,000 cash crashed into a snowy field outside
Knoxville, killing its pilot and its sole passenger. Police said the
cocaine was valued at $450,000.
   Authorities said heavy wet snow was falling and the ceiling was
down to 400 feet at the time of the crash that killed pilot John
Chestnut, 47, of Trotwood, Ohio; and Jeffery L. Hicks, 23, of
Cincinnati, officials said.
   The plane was en route from Fort Lauderdale, Fla., to Dayton,
Ohio, with a fuel stop in Knoxville when it apparently lost an
engine, said Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Jack Barker
of Atlanta.
   At least three traffic deaths in Virginia were blamed on slippery
roads. Numerous schools were closed in Virginia and power was out to
thousands of customers in the state's Pulaski, Radford and Giles
counties.
   ``There's just no way we can count the number of accidents
without polling each trooper and seeing how many he investigated,''
said Virginia state police Sgt. G.A. Farthing. ``I'd be hesitant to
even give a number.''
   Rob Yates, a Shenandoah National Park spokesman, said the Skyline
Drive near Winchester, Va., was closed because of heavy snowfall,
and some visitors were stranded at visitor centers along the drive.
   Advisories warned of a chance of snow elsewhere in Virginia,
Maryland, Delaware, eastern Tennessee and West Virginia's Eastern
Panhandle.
   Squalls produced locally heavy snow around the lower Great Lakes
and heavy snow warnings were issued for northeastern Ohio and for
the eastern Lake Ontario counties of New York state.
   Light snow fell around the southern shore of Lake Michigan and
over North Dakota.
   A storm slowly tracking across northern Mexico threatened to
produce heavy snow over parts of New Mexico. A winter storm watch
was posted into Saturday for the state's central highlands,
south-central mountains, and east-central and southeastern plains.
   A snow advisory was issued for parts of western Texas.
   Strong, gusty Santa Ana wind continued to blow across southern
California for a third day with gusts to 60 mph reported at Rialto
and Laguna Peak. More than 20 homes were damaged, some of them
destroyed, northwest of downtown Los Angeles and thousands of people
were evacuated.
   Elsewhere, showers were scattered from northern Florida across
the Carolina coast, with light rain and drizzle over the northern
Rockies.
   Afternoon temperatures remained below freezing from northeastern
Montana through the Great Lakes region and much of the Ohio Valley
to the northern Atlantic Coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from zero
degrees at International Falls, Minn., to 83 at Fort Myers, Fla.
Friday morning's official low was 22 degrees below zero at Hibbing,
Minn.
   For Saturday, snow was forecast from the Great Lakes region and
the northern half of the Ohio Valley to northern New England. Rain
was forecast from southeastern Arizona through the southern Plains
and the lower Mississippi Valley to southern Georgia and northern
and central Florida. Snow also was forecast over parts of New Mexico
and northwestern Texas. Scattered showers were forecast from the
coast of Washington to Montana and western Wyoming, with snow at
higher elevations.
   Highs only in the teens or single digits were predicted from the
Dakotas through the Great Lakes to northern New England; in the 20s
in the rest of the region from eastern Montana through the upper
half of the Mississippi Valley to the northern Atlantic Coast; above
50 from coastal Texas to the southern Atlantic Coast and from the
California coast to southern Arizona; above 60 from the central
coast of California to southwestern Arizona; in the 60s and 70s
across the Florida Peninsula; and in the 70s in southwestern
California.
</TEXT>
