<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RideauClemency     12-09 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rideau Clemency,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Killer At A Loss Over Governor's Decision</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANGOLA, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the urging of parole officials,
Governor Buddy Roemer has refused to grant clemency to Wilbert
Rideau, a convicted murderer who became a nationally recognized
prison editor.
   ``I wish somebody would tell me what to do, and I'd do it,''
Rideau said in a telephone interview Thursday, a day after Roemer
rejected the state Pardon Board's recommendation for a reduction of
sentence.
   Rideau, 47, is serving life in the state prison for a 1961 Lake
Charles bank robbery during which he kidnapped three employees, shot
and wounded two of them and killed the third by cutting her throat.
   Rideau was arrested shortly afterwards and confessed in front of
television cameras. He spent 10 years on death row until the U.S.
Supreme Court struck down the state's capital punishment law in 1972.
   The board's second recommendation of reduced sentence would have
made Rideau eligible for parole. In rejecting it, Roemer cited the
strenuous objections of Rideau's prosecutors and victims.
   Rideau, who has won numerous national prizes as editor of the
prison news magazine The Angolite, said he thinks he was turned down
because his success with the magazine has kept him in the limelight.
   ``We've got a system that encourages anonymity. It encourages
prisoners to do nothing, not to distinguish themselves,'' he said.
``If you want to get out of prison, you're supposed to keep your
mouth shut and let everybody forget about you,'' he said.
   Rideau said he is not sure what to do next. Since the pardon
board agreed with him, it would add nothing to get another hearing.
Rideau said he can only hope that Roemer will change his mind.
   ``I would love to meet the man,'' Rideau said. ``I wish I could
sit down with him. Anything he wants to know, let me present my
side.''
   Although serving life, Rideau is frequently on the road,
traveling under guard to lecture at state universities, appear on
national television shows and cover state board meetings for the
magazine.
   He and other editors have been singled out for national
recognition by the American Bar Association, private foundations and
other organizations.
</TEXT>
