<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Lewis     12-09 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Lewis,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jerry Lee Lewis Has Little Left, Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock 'n' roller Jerry Lee Lewis, facing a
$2 million tax debt and other bills, has few personal possessions he
could use to pay off creditors, a bankruptcy lawyer says.
   ``There's not much left,'' Norman Hagemeyer, an attorney
representing Lewis in federal Bankruptcy Court here, said Thursday.
   Lewis, 53, filed for bankruptcy Nov. 8, citing debts of more than
$3 million and income of about $5,000 a month, Hagemeyer said.
   The Internal Revenue Service has been squabbling with Lewis since
1975, and tax agents have seized cars, furniture and other property
from him several times over the years.
   ``There have been at least two sales by the IRS that I know of,''
Hagemeyer said.
   Lewis' bankruptcy petition lists a residence valued at $30,000
near Nesbit, Miss., and other personal property worth about $6,000.
   In a hearing Wednesday, Lewis said the income from an upcoming
movie based on his life would fall well short of his debts.
   Responding to inquiries from bankruptcy trustee George Emerson,
Lewis said a contract he signed eight years ago puts his income from
the movie at $200,000 to $250,000.
   Emerson asked if Lewis expected to perform any consulting work or
other moneymaking activities for the producers of ``Great Balls of
Fire'' starring Dennis Quaid.
   ``No sir,'' Lewis said. ``I've suggested some things. We don't
see eye to eye on some things. They're pretty well set on what they
want to do.''
   The movie about Lewis' tumultuous personal life and the early
years of his rock 'n' roll career is being shot in Memphis.
   In is petition, Lewis listed 22 creditors, but his major debts
are to the IRS and Oklahoma concert promoter who sued in 1978 after
the rocker failed to show up for a scheduled performance, Hagemeyer
said.
   Lewis failed to show up to oppose the lawsuit and a judgment was
filed against him for more than $450,000. With interest, he now owes
about $950,000, the attorney said.
   Lewis went to trial on tax evasion charges in 1984, but was
acquitted of charges he intentionally hid money from the IRS. At the
time, the IRS said he owed the government more than $650,000.
   The singer's income comes primarily from performances, said Jim
Bingham, an attorney representing Lewis on matters other than the
bankruptcy petition.
   Lewis, who recorded such early rock 'n' roll classics as ``Whole
Lotta Shakin' Going On'' and ``Great Balls of Fire,'' told the
bankruptcy trustee he has not received any record royalties in the
last few years.
</TEXT>
