<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChinookCrashes     12-09 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chinook Crashes,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinook Accidents in Recent Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Honduras-US Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of some accidents in recent years involving the
twin-rotor Boeing CH-47 Chinook helicopter.
   _ Feb. 25, 1988, an Army CH-47D crashed in a cow pasture near
Chico, Texas, killing 10 soldiers and seriously burning eight.
   _ Nov. 20, 1987, an Army CH-47 crashed and burned in Colombia,
injuring two soldiers.
   _ May 15, 1987, an Army CH-47 caught fire and made a forced
landing in dense woods near Monticello, Ark., killing one soldier
and injuring three.
   _ Feb. 27, 1987, a Chinook helicopter belonging to the Royal Air
Force crashed near Port Stanley in the Falkland Islands, killing all
seven aboard.
   _ Nov. 6, 1986, a Chinook 234, a civilian version of the
helicopter, crashed in the North Sea, killing 45 people. The company
that operated the helicopter said gearbox fatigue probably caused
the crash.
   _ May 13, 1986, a British Army Chinook crashed into a mountain on
West Falkland Island, killing three crewmen. Officials said
visibility was poor at the time.
   _ April 9, 1986, an Army CH-47D collided with an AH-1S Cobra
helicopter over Fort Stewart, Ga., killing eight soldiers.
   _ July 11, 1985, a CH-47D being tested before delivery to the
Army crashed in a marshy area in southern New Jersey, killing two
crew members.
   _ April 21, 1985, a CH-47D taxiing on the ground in Honduras was
destroyed when one rotor stopped turning and was struck by the
other. Eight soldiers were injured, and the Army grounded its fleet
of Chinooks for a month and a half to replace rotor transmission
bearings.
</TEXT>
