<DOCNO> AP881209-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 0107EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HolidayGrieving     12-09 0590</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Holiday Grieving,0617</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Holidays Are Tough Times To Deal With Loss Of Child</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holiday chimes may sound a somber note for
families grieving over the loss of a child, but a psychiatrist
suggests survivors start new traditions in memory of the departed.
   ``Families in mourning have to be told it is all right to have
fun,'' says Abby L. Wasserman, writing in the December issue of
American Journal of Diseases of Children.
   ``Laughter is the best medicine for helping the bereaved cope
with their loss. Having a good time does not mean that the parents
loved their child any less,'' she said.
   ``In fact, they may be showing more love because by enjoying
themselves, they are bringing their family closer together.''
   In getting through the holidays, families must decide what is
comfortable, Ms. Wasserman said.
   ``Changes can make things less painful,'' she said. ``A different
tree with different decorations. Opening the presents at a different
time. A different menu for dinner.''
   Some families put a small Christmas tree on the child's grave,
Ms. Wasserman said. Others light a candle or order special plants or
flowers.
   Accompanying her article are some ``do's'' and ``don't's'' for
those spending time with bereaved parents during the holidays.
   Do:
   _ Talk about special qualities of the child they have lost.
   _ Allow them to express as much grief as they are feeling.
   _ Reassure them that they did everything they could.
   _ Pay attention to surviving siblings.
   But don't:
   _ Say you know how they feel unless you have lost a child.
   _ Say the parents should be over the loss.
   _ Change the subject when they mention their dead child.
   _ Say they can always have other children.
   _ Point out that at least they have other children.
   Ms. Wasserman, a child psychiatrist at Washington University
School of Medicine in St. Louis, says religion can be a source of
comfort, but she cautions that surviving children might misinterpret
some explanations.
   In one case, she said, the behavior of a 4-year-old boy was poor
after his brother's death.
   ``When asked about this behavior change for the worse, he replied
that he was not going to be so good that Jesus would want him. This
child had been told that his brother was so wonderful that Jesus
wanted him to live with him in heaven,'' Ms. Wasserman said.
   The Compassionate Friends, an international organization
dedicated to helping parents overcome the loss of a child, recently
sent out holiday suggestions to its 600 U.S. chapters.
   ``Sometimes the toughest part of all is the anticipation,'' said
Therese Goodrich, director of group's national office in suburban
Oak Brook.
   ``You turn on the television and people are telling you to get
the shopping done. It's all around us,'' she said in a telephone
interview Thursday.
   ``Some people like to buy a gift that their child would have
liked, and then give it to the Salvation Army or a church group.''
   Other suggestions include urging families to change their holiday
routines, mention the loss of their children in Christmas cards and
discuss them when they feel comfortable with the subject.
   Mrs. Goodrich, whose 14-year-old daughter was killed by a car in
1971, says the first holiday without a child is the hardest.
   ``When a child dies, our priorities get shook up. We want to show
a little more love,'' she said. ``I think people just need to be
gentle with themselves. That's the main thing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
