<HEAD>With PM-Reagan Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of President
Reagan's news conference Thursday night.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOVIET UNION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Reagan said ``extraordinary things'' have occurred in recent
years to improve U.S.-Soviet relations. But he added that the
Soviets would retain conventional troop superiority even if Mikhail
S. Gorbachev makes planned troop reductions.
   The president said he believed Gorbachev was trying to make the
Soviet Union less threatening. Asked whether he trusted the Kremlin
leader, he replied, ``He hasn't shown me any reason yet that I
shouldn't.'' But he quickly reasserted his policy of ``trust but
verify.''
   He said he would someday like to see the United States and Soviet
Union as allies ``if it can be definitely established they no longer
follow expansionist policy.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEFICIT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Reagan rejected an assertion that tax cuts he sponsored had
contributed to the federal budget deficit. He blamed anew
congressional spending habits, specifically those of the Democrats,
for the red ink.
   ``We came in inheriting literally deficit spending built into the
structure of government,'' the president.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TAXES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Reagan said he would be ``deeply disappointed'' if
President-elect Bush sought to raise taxes after taking office,
adding ``I don't think it's going to happen. Reagan said he believed
Bush could trim the deficit without raising taxes or cutting Social
Security.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>A LOOK BACK</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   His hardest job as president: ``I don't think there is anything
tougher than to have to order the young men and women in our
military today ... to have to send them into danger, order them into
some place where their lives are threatened, where their lives can
be taken.''
   He said the economic recovery was the best part of his presidency.

</TEXT>
<HEAD>AFGHANISTAN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Reagan said the United States would not unilaterally halt aid to
the U.S.-backed rebels seeking to overthrow the Soviet-sponsored
Kabul regime. He called Gorbachev's proposal for a U.N. peacekeeping
force in Afghanistan an ``exceptional'' proposal but said he was not
certain the U.N. would endorse it.
   The president said the ``puppet government'' would have to step
down for lasting resolution of civil strife.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MIDDLE EAST</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The president said PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat ``left openings for
himself'' to back away from his statement this week of support of
Israel's right to exist. Reagan reiterated that the Unted States
would enter into dialogue with the PLO chief only ``once it is
clear-cut that he's ready to recognize Israel as a nation.''
