<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Reflections     12-09 0345</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Reflections,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Discusses Ups and Downs of Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reflecting on the peaks and valleys of his
presidency, Ronald Reagan said his toughest burden has been sending
young Americans into battle and laboring to win the release of
others held hostage.
   At two different points in his nationally broadcast news
conference Thursday night, Reagan talked of difficult moments in the
Oval Office.
   Asked what task he had found most difficult, the president
quickly cited the sending of troops into combat.
   Saying that ``I think I am prouder of them than of anything that
has happened'' during his nearly eight years in office, Reagan
added: ``I don't think there's anything tougher than to have to
order these magnificent young men and women in our military ... into
danger.''
   ``That's got to be something that any president would hesitate on
and have to say was the greatest burden,'' he said.
   At another point, Reagan cited the continuing captivity of nine
Americans held by pro-Iranian elements in Lebanon, saying it was
``one of those things ... you go to bed with every night.''
   During Reagan's presidency, more than 200 U.S. military personnel
were killed during a bombing of a Marine barracks in Beirut,
Lebanon, several thousand troops were sent into combat during the
invasion of Grenada, in which 19 American soldiers were killed, and
37 crewmen aboard the USS Stark were killed in the Persian Gulf when
their ship was struck by missiles fired by an Iraqi fighter.
   When asked what he most enjoyed about the presidency, Reagan
replied that ``there are a number of things to miss.''
   But Reagan said ``let me simply say one I enjoyed the most is the
economic recovery.''
   ``When I came here, for almost half a century, the debate on the
(Capitol) Hill in the Congress had always been between more big
spending programs, more power for the federal government, more
intervention in private affairs by the federal government, as
against those who were preaching less,'' he said.
</TEXT>
