<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mitchell-HoldoutPrecinct Bjt   12-09 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mitchell-Holdout Precinct, Bjt,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Democratic Leader Visits Election Foe's Only Precinct</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALMADGE, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a return to his home state, Senate
Majority Leader George J. Mitchell visited the only precinct that he
didn't carry in November's election. Judging by the reception, he
might win even its votes the next time around.
   The tiny Bethel Chapel in Talmadge was filled with half again as
many adults as voted in the race. Mitchell lost there, 18-12, but
won in the other 672 precincts, capturing 81 percent of the
statewide vote.
   ``I wanted to head up here and find out what I was doing wrong,''
Mitchell told the gathering in this outpost of rural eastern Maine.
   Mitchell, who followed up his election victory by winning the
three-way majority leader's race last week, had written letters to
Talmadge residents inviting them to the meeting. He was applauded
repeatedly inside the church, a white wooden building surrounded by
a mustard-seed farm, and several people told him they looked forward
to seeing him running for president.
   ``Boy, you'd never know I only got 12 votes, for all that told me
they voted for me,'' Mitchell said.
   Local citizens said they held nothing against the senator, a
Democrat, but that his challenger, Republican Jasper S. Wyman, was
more in tune with the Pentecostal community's beliefs, especially on
abortion. Wyman is the director of the conservative Christian Civic
League of Maine.
   ``Abortion was the issue here,'' said Dawn Coffin, the pastor who
welcomed Mitchell.
   Rev. Coffin, in her introduction, reminded Mitchell that the
success of majority rule in the United States is the ability to
listen to the minority. ``Thank you for listening to a very small
minority here,'' she told him.
   The toughest questions for Mitchell came from Talmadge resident
Walter Heim. He attacked Mitchell, President-elect Bush and others
who don't oppose abortion in all instances as being in the same
league as ``pimps, prostitutes and witches.''
   Mitchell said he opposes federal funding for abortion but was not
against the Supreme Court's ruling which gives women the choice. He
told Heim it was ``regrettable'' that he was associating people of
different viewpoints with scurrilous characters.
   The senator explained that he is a Roman Catholic but, ``I don't
know when life begins.''
   Mitchell fielded questions on local issues and the U.S.-Canada
free-trade pact, which he opposed in the Senate, and afterward
joined the congregation for sandwiches and sweets in a basement
social hall.
   Some of the people apologized for Heim's attack, explaining that
he was not a native of Maine. Heim himself allowed that he was
impressed by Mitchell's visit.
   ``He comes here, exposing his flank,'' said Heim, ``He's quite a
guy.''
   Mitchell chatted with Heim, reporting afterward that another
facet of the encounter had been revealed.
   ``He said, `I was a private and I always wanted to get an
officer. This was my chance','' Mitchell, who was an officer in the
Army Counterintelligence Corps in the mid-1950s, said with a laugh.
   Mitchell said another, older man came up and said, ``Boy, I've
had a lot of politicians come around before the election, but you're
the first one to come around after the election.''
</TEXT>
