<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ReaganRelics     12-09 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan Relics,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Sending Relics of Presidency to Eureka College</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VOGRIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EUREKA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald Reagan's alma mater, tiny Eureka
College, is sifting through a bonanza of presidential baubles,
including the trademark jellybean jar and a cowboy belt buckle
proclaiming ``the buckaroo stops here.''
   ``President Reagan has a deep affection for Eureka College and
remains consistently in touch with us,'' said George Hearne, the
college's president.
   The school of 460 students about 20 miles east of Peoriairport news
conference, saying the quake, which registered 6.9 on the Richter
scale, ``had extremely grave consequences, devastation and grave
loss of life.''
   Armenian church officials in New York who are in contact with
people in the region said the death toll may be as high as 70,000.
   Although he had only ``one working day'' in New York, Gorbachev
said, ``I and my delegation believe that this was a very important
day.''
   The highlights of the visit were Gorbachev's announcement before
the U.N. General Assembly that he planned a major reduction in
Soviet troop strength over the next three years, and his superpower
luncheon with President Reagan and President-elect Bush.
   Gorbachev, the first Soviet chief to visit New York in 28 years,
said his U.N. speech and a later reception gave him the opportunity
to ``set out our views ... on the world today, and on the prospects
of the world's development.''
   Gorbachev called the Governors Island session with Reagan and
Bush ``a good meeting, held in ... an open and trusting atmosphere.''
   He said the one word he would use to characterize it was
``continuity'' and said all parties walked away, ``confident that
our relations will expand and improve on the basis of cooperation,
on the basis of mutual respect for each other's interests.''
   Gorbachev later added, ``I think I would be remiss in my duty if
I went home without saying how much we are grateful to New Yorkers,
for the hospitality and feelings of friendship that they have been
expressing over these days. So to all New Yorkers, our very warm
gratitude. We value that very much.''
   He had planned to visit the first Soviet trade show in the United
States, Central Park and the Metropolitan Museum on Thursday.
Gorbachev's wife, Raisa, canceled a visit with children at an Upper
East Side elementary school.
</TEXT>
