<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 0150EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Opera     12-09 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Opera,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attractive New `Aida' At Met</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will stand for PMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attractive new production of ``Aida'' at the
Metropolitan Opera avoids the visual silliness of the two
productions that arrived before it. This one makes dramatic use of
the stage elevator to change sets.
   The opening night of the new ``Aida,'' a Met Opera Guild benefit,
was tastefully conducted by James Levine and gloriously sung by
Leona Mitchell as Aida, Placido Domingo as Radames, Fiorenza
Cossotto as Amneris, Sherrill Milnes as Aida's father, Amonasro, and
Paul Plishka as the high priest.
   Domingo sounded sterling throughout. He surprised this listener
by taking the optional lower ending, not the high C, at the end of
``Celeste Aida.''
   Miss Mitchell, singing her first Aida at the Met, bloomed into
full vocal glory in the third act. She had longing in her voice in
``O patria mia'' and some beautiful pianissimos. Her voice has
matured marvelously and still has youthful freshness.
   In many operas, the love music is in the first act, before things
start to go wrong. In ``Aida'' the love music is in Act 4, after
things have gone so wrong that Aida and Radames are sealed in a
vault to die. Their duet was so beautiful that the audience didn't
immediately break the spell with huge applause at the end of it.
   Miss Cossotto, who made her Met debut as Amneris in 1968, is a
fine musician, using her voice to brilliant advantage. Her stage
personality, while not flamboyant, is striking, placing Amneris'
royal but hopeless love for Radames in the foreground in the first
two acts. Miss Mitchell's more retiring demeanor put Aida in the
background.
   Milnes was in brilliant voice and form. Amonasro may be a captive
but he's full of vitality and vibrant with plans. Plishka sang with
admirable authority.
   The costumes, by Dada Saligeri, were mostly white trimmed with
gold. Domingo began, a hero, in all gold, and ended, disgraced, in a
dark striped tunic.
   Some scenes were played near the front of the stage, in front of
a wall with huge bas reliefs of two seated Egyptians. Then this
would lift for a scene using more of the stage.
   The most dramatic theatrical stroke is having Amneris' room in
Act 2 sink out of sight. First, soldiers are seen standing on top of
the set that's descending, then a platform for the king and Amneris
is revealed, then all the citizenry _ now joined at ground level by
the soldiers _ wait for the triumphal entry scene.
   In the final scene, the elevator is used again, so the audience
sees Aida and Radames in the vault and Amneris in a temple above
them.
   There is no silly dance in Act 1 while Radames receives his armor
and no fight to the death during the triumphal entry scene. There is
a dance there, by choreographer Rodney Griffin of Philadelphia,
making his Met debut, but it isn't silly.
   Gianni Quaranta, who is Italian and won an Academy Award in 1987
for art direction for ``A Room with a View,'' designed the sets.
Sonja Frisell, a native of Great Britain who was on the staff of La
Scala for 15 years, did stage direction.
   Both, making Met debuts, proved to be stars of the show.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881209-0019 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 0211EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AirForceSafety     12-09 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Air Force Safety,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A-10 Warplane Has One of Best Safety Records In Air Force Fleet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Germany Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. warplane that crashed into an
apartment building in West Germany, killing four people, has one of
the best safety records in the Air Force inventory.
   The A-10 Thunderbolt II is an older model ground-attack plane
designed to be highly maneuverable at low speeds and low altitude
and to carry a lot of bombs and ammunition.
   The Air Force said the crash was the 14th serious, so-called
Class A accident since Oct. 1, when the current fiscal year began,
although it was the first involving an A-10.
   At the same point in the last fiscal year, the service had
experienced nine Class A accidents.
   Among the 14 accidents recorded since Oct. 1 have been two
involving the new B-1B bomber; one involving a B-52 bomber, and one
involving an F-16 fighter in Spain last Monday that killed the
general in charge of Air Force personnel in the Mediterranean.
   The Air Force says it is impossible to predict what type of
safety record it will post for the year based on little more than
one month's passage. During fiscal 1988, for example, the service
experienced a grim record for its F-16 jet fighter, and yet finished
the year by posting one of its best overall safety records in
history.
   ``Nonetheless, it is true that our mishap rate has suddenly
spiked up and we don't know why,'' said one Air Force official who
asked not to be identified.
   ``We continue to examine our training procedures, maintenance and
everything else.''
   Wednesday's crash involved an A-10 on a training flight that
inexplicably slammed into an apartment building in Remscheid, West
Germany, killing at least four people, injuring dozens of others and
destroying homes for more than a block.
   The A-10 is designed to support soldiers on the ground by
attacking enemy tanks and other high-priority targets. The
Thunderbolt first flew in 1975 and became operational with the Air
Force in 1977. The plane is no longer in production, but the Air
Force has more than 700 of them in its inventory.
   Statistically, the A-10 over time has been the safest fighter or
attack plane currently in the inventory. The aircraft has chalked up
a major accident rate of less than 4 Class A mishaps per 100,000
flying hours over its lifetime _ which now consists of more than
1.75 million flight hours.
   A Class A mishap is one in which there is either a fatality or
damage exceeding $500,000 to an aircraft.
   In the fiscal year ended Sept. 30, the Air Force lost three
A-10's, for a mishap rate of 1.37 per 100,000 flight hours. By
comparison, the A-7 had a mishap rate of 6.04 per 100,000 flight
hours; the F-16 a rate of 6.80 per 100,000 flight hours, and the
B-52 a rate of 2.04 per 100,000 flight hours.
   The overall Air Force rate for the last fiscal year was 1.63
serious mishaps per 100,000 flying hours _ representing 55 total
accidents _ just slightly worse than the service's all-time best of
1.53 set in fiscal 1986.
   The surge in Air Force accidents over the past month comes at a
time when the other military services continue to report stable
rates.
   The Navy, for example, which enjoyed its safest year ever in
fiscal 1988, is on track toward an even safer year. Since Oct. 1,
the Navy has experienced only four Class A accidents. It recorded 37
in all of fiscal 1988, or more than three per month on average.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
