<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 0212EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CorporateTaxes     12-09 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Corporate Taxes,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey: Tax Changes Taking Bigger Corporate Bite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new survey shows that overhaul of the federal
income tax is increasing the bite on corporations _ which is just
what Congress intended.
   One thousand corporations surveyed by Tax Analysts paid about $7
billion more into the federal treasury last year than they did in
1986, when the tax laws underwent major revisions.
   The 1,000 companies, spread out among 49 industries, paid an
average of 24.72 percent of their earnings in federal income tax in
1987, the study found. That compares with 21.54 percent in 1986 and
20.94 percent the previous year.
   Three out of four corporations paid a higher rate last year than
the year before. While a portion of the increase is due to higher
earnings in 1987, most is attributable to the new tax law, said Tax
Analysts, a Virginia-based research and publishing organization.
   ``Tax reform is working,'' said Forrest D. Marovelli of Tax
Analysts. ``More corporations are paying higher taxes. Fewer are
avoiding taxes.''
   A major goal of the 1986 tax overhaul was to shift a greater
portion of the tax burden from individuals to corporations. Over
five years, the total shift is expected to be about $125 billion.
   The most significant corporate changes enacted were repeal of the
special treatment of capital gains, toughening of the alternative
minimum tax, repeal of the investment tax credit and restructuring
of depreciation allowances. The general corporate tax rate was cut,
from 46 percent to 33 percent, which benefited all companies.
   However, because different types of corporations took advantage
of different provisions under the old tax law, there are significant
variations in how they are faring under the new law, said Mark
Starcher of Tax Analysts.
   For example, a reduction in long-term accounting provisions more
than doubled the average tax rate paid by aerospace companies, from
15.6 percent of earnings to 36.7 percent, the study found. On the
other hand, apparel and furniture companies are paying generally
lower taxes because they have the lower tax rates but lost
relatively little in the other tax changes.
   According to the Tax Analysts calculations, the automobile
industry paid the lowest tax rate last year _ a negative 6.93
percent _ while construction was highest at 58.9 percent. Both
situations were exaggerated by special circumstancs, Marovelli said.
   General Motors Corp., the largest U.S. automaker, had a one-time
tax writeoff that made the entire industry's situation look worse
than it was; without GM, Marovelli said, the industry would have
paid 17 percent.
   The high rate on the construction industry reflected the same
accounting changes that affected the aerospace industry, as well as
a curtailment in use of installment sales, which in the past had
produced a tax savings for that industry.
   Other industry figures from 1987 included: insurance, 14 percent;
paper, 19 percent; drugs, 22.1 percent; banking, 23.6 percent;
railroads, 23.9 percent; petroleum refining, 24.9 percent; lumber,
29.2 percent; textiles, 29.4 percent; services, 31.7 percent;
tobacco, 33.1 percent; apparel, 34.9 percent; commercial printing,
35 percent; newspapers, 36.7 percent; and retail groceries, 37.1
percent.
   Tax Analysts bases its calculations on corporate filings with the
Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Citizens for Tax Justice, a labor-financed tax research group,
reached similar conclusions in a study of profitable corporations
released in September. That study concluded the number of profitable
companies that paid no federal tax was cut by more than half last
year _ to 16 _ and that the 250 companies surveyed paid an average
of 22.1 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
