<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Arafat     12-09 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Arafat,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says Arafat Not Clear On Israel Question</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, defending the U.S. refusal to
allow PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat to speak to the United Nations in
New York, says the Arab leader hasn't yet clearly recognized Israel.
   ``We are willing to meet with him, and talk with him, and I'm
sure the Israelis would be, when once and for all it is clear-cut
that he is ready to recognize Israel's right to be a nation,''
Reagan said Thursday in a nationally televised news conference.
   The president said Arafat's statement Wednesday in Stockholm _
that the Palestine Liberation Organization accepts Israel and
rejects terrorism ``in all its forms'' _ was ambiguous.
   ``He has left openings for himself where he can deny that he
meant this or meant that, that sounded so clean-cut,'' Reagan said.
``... You could quote to him, `Oh you said this,' but he's still in
a position to say, `Well yes, but wait a minute. I also said this.'
And then you find that the second `this' kind of reduces or
nullifies the first `this.'''
   The United States has said it will not deal directly with the PLO
until it explicitly recognizes Israel's right to exist and renounces
terrorism.
   In a Nov. 15 declaration in Algeria, the PLO's parliament did not
specifically recognize Israel's right to exist, although it accepted
three U.N. resolutions that do so.
   And, it did not directly renounce terrorism, although it commited
the PLO to the ``Cairo declaration'' of 1985, which limits attacks
to ``military targets'' in Israel.
   Israel has rejected the Nov. 15 declaration by the Palestine
National Council as ``doubletalk.''
</TEXT>
