<DOCNO> AP881209-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 0242EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Hostages     12-09 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Hostages,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says US Eventually Must Negotiate With Iran On Hostages</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan says the United States
eventually will have to negotiate with Iran to gain the release of
American hostages held in Lebanon, but insisted the U.S. government
would not consider paying any kind of ransom.
   ``We're looking at every channel that we can find to try and get
them, and I imagine that the ultimate is going to have to be somehow
a negotiation with Iran, because they have control of those
people,'' he told a news conference Thursday.
   ``We are hopeful that there can be avenues that would open'' for
the release of the hostages, he said. ``We cannot enter into
negotiating in the sense of what kind of ransom to pay, or you are
just encouraging more hostage-taking.''
   And in perhaps his last White House news conference, Reagan
repeated that he did not believe his administration was bargaining
with terrorists when it entered into the Iran-Contra affair.
   ``We were not negotiating with them in the so-called Iran-Contra
affair at all. We were heeding a plea from some individuals ... And
these people were among those who were planning ahead to have a
government'' after the death of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
Khomeini remains the spiritual head of Iran.
   Reagan said he would be willing to negotiate with Tehran, with
which Washington has had no formal diplomatic ties since the 1979-81
hostage crisis.
   ``There are conditions that have to be met also there. Anytime
that they are ready to come forward on an open basis, we would be
ready to talk to them,'' Reagan said.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, speaking to reporters
immediately after the news conference, said Reagan was not referring
to any new circumstances under which the United States would
negotiate with Iran, saying the terms that Reagan alluded to ``are
the same conditions that we've been talking about all along.''
   ``We have said that there would have to be authoritative
representatives of the government of Iran'' to negotiate with and
that ``they would have to acknowledge this publicly,'' Fitzwater
said.
   ``We'll be glad to talk, but we've never been able to get them to
do that,'' the spokesman said.
   Fitzwater said that releasing U.S. hostages held captive in
Lebanon by pro-Iranian elements was not a precondition to
discussions with Tehran.
   Anita Stockman, a State Department spokeswoman, also said that
the administration ``has always maintained that we are prepared to
talk with the Iranians if it is somebody that is serious and
somebody in authority.''
   ``We have extended an invitation to meet in a serious setting,
and have not gotten any response to that,'' she said. ``We have
maintained all along that any one with influence with the
kidnappers, and that includes the Iranians, should use it to win
their freedom.''
   The State Department's Office for Counter-Terrorism says that as
of Oct. 5, 1988, 15 foreign hostages remain in Lebanon _ nine
Americans, three Britons, an Irishman, an Italian and a Belgian.
</TEXT>
