<HEAD>Dollar Off Against Yen, Shares Up Marginally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar dropped Friday against the Japanese
yen, while share prices edged up on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed the week at 122.43 yen, down 0.59 yen from
Thursday's closing of 123.02 yen. After opening at 122.20 yen, the
U.S. currency ranged between 122.10 and 122.47 yen.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues finished the day's trading at 29,793.42, gaining 34.52 points
or 0.12 percent. The index lost ground shortly after the market
opened but then reversed directions.
   The dollar surged against other major currencies earlier this
week on speculation that talks between U.S. and Soviet leaders might
lead to bilateral arms reductions which could help reduce the U.S.
budget deficit.
   The dollar fell Friday mainly because investors were disappointed
by the still unclear U.S. reaction to Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev's pledge to unilaterally reduce Soviet troops by 500,000,
said a Bank of Tokyo dealer.
   On the stock exchange, share prices were slightly lower following
a 11.92-point drop in the Dow Jones industrial average on Wall
Street overnight, equity dealers said.
   Investors withdrew to the sidelines to follow the case involving
Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa and his alleged involvement in a
stock dealing scandal.
</TEXT>
