<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cy Young Award winner LaMarr Hoyt wasted
little time getting married after being released from a halfway
house where he finished the remainder of a one-year sentence for
violating parole on a drug conviction.
   The former major league baseball pitcher was released late last
month after five months at the halfway house in his hometown, Alston
Wilkes Society spokeswoman Sharon Driggers said Thursday. The
society runs the halfway house and others in the state.
   ``He completed the program successfully,'' Ms. Driggers said.
   On Saturday, the 33-year-old former Chicago White Sox star
married Leslie Miller of Irmo, a suburb of Columbia. Hoyt has an
apartment in Columbia, but there is no telephone listing for him.
   Hoyt been at the Allenwood Federal Prison Camp in Montgomery,
Pa., before being transferred to the halfway house in his hometown.
   The sentence was imposed after Hoyt, who pleaded guilty in 1986
to two federal misdemeanor drug charges, tested positive for cocaine
in October 1987.
   Hoyt also pleaded guilty to possession of cocaine and marijuana
in February after a Dec. 15 drug arrest at his Columbia apartment.
He was sentenced to seven months, to be served concurrently with the
other term.
   Baseball Commissioner Peter Uberroth banned him from baseball for
1987 for his involvement in drug incidents the year before.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OGDEN, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito of Japan honored a local man
with the Order of the Sacred Treasure in honor of his years of
community service.
   ``Of course I didn't expect to be selected, because this is quite
an honor,'' Roy Y. Nakatani, 72, of Ogden said recently.
   The award is one of four given to people of Japanese ancestry in
the western United States and one of 4,000 awarded worldwide this
year to those who have worked to promote understanding between their
countries and Japan.
   Nakatani traveled to Japan to receive the award last month. Crown
Prince Akhito was host of the ceremonies because of the emperor's
illness, Nakatani said.
   Nakatani has been active in Utah community affairs since moving
here after World War II. He has served on a variety of boards and
fraternal organizations, including the American Red Cross, United
Way and the Boy Scouts.
