<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0466 12-09 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0466,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Warplanes Blast Guerrilla Posts In Effort To Rescue Trapped
Paratroopers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with seven grafs on helicopters hovering overhead,
quote. Picks up graf 6 pvs, `The assault ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAAMEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes blasted guerrilla
positions Friday in hills overlooking this coastal town near Beirut
as they tried to rescue trapped paratroopers who landed by
helicopter before dawn, police said.
   They said at least one Israeli soldier was killed and two others
wounded in a clash between the Israeli landing party and guerrillas
of a pro-Syrian Palestinian faction and a leftist Lebanese group.
   ``Other Israeli troops have been captured, but we do not know
their number yet. It seems the Israelis are surrounded,'' said a
police officer in Naameh. He cannot be named under standing rules.
   There was no immediate confirmation from Israel's military
command, which usually issues its communiques only after its
operation has been completed.
   Gunboats cruised off Naameh as five helicopter gunships hovered
overhead, apparently waiting to evacuate the Israeli commandos who
landed on Naameh's bluffs at 2:10 a.m., the spokesman said.
   Eight fighter-bombers thundered in from the clear Mediterranean
sky at dayrteak to blast hilltop targets east of Naameh in 15
bombing sorties, police said.
   ``They are attacking roughly at 15-minute intervals, obviously
trying to help break the noose around their trapped paratroopers in
the Naameh hills,'' the spokesman said.
   The assault began at 6:40 a.m. Black smoke billowed from stricken
targets perched in olive groves above Naameh, police said.
   Naameh is nine miles south of Beirut and 16 miles north of Sidon,
provincial capital of south Lebanon. Ambulances were dispatched from
both cities after the attack.
   The area is controlled by the Syrian-backed Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine-General Command and leftist militiamen of
Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party.
   Many cars were seen speeding out with honking horns from the
stricken bluffs to the coastal highway linking Beirut and Sidon.
They were believed rushing casualties to hospitals in both cities.
   Distant thuds of explosions could be heard in Beirut as the
planes staged Israel's 24th air raid on Lebanon this year.
   Fighters of the Popular Front and their Druse allies unleashed a
screen of shoulder-fired SAM-7 missiles, known as Strellas, against
the raiding jets, but no hits were scored, police said.
   They said Israeli pilots released hot air balloons to deflect the
heat-seeking missiles.
   The Popular Front, headed by former Syrian Army Capt. Ahmed
Jibril, is armed by Syria and funded by Libya. It is at odds with
Yasser Arafat's mainstream Palestine Liberation Organiztion.
   Dozens of guerrillas and militiamen, all toting shoulder-fired
rocket- propelled grenades were seen running to positions along
Naameh's beach as five Israeli helicopter gunships hovered opposite
the coastal town at 8:15 a.m.
   ``They're going to land troops,'' one guerrilla was heard
shouting as he raced to the beachstrip.
   Panicky shopkeepers hurriedly lowered their shutters as hundreds
of Naameh residents scurried to take shelter in basements.
   At least 119 people were killed and 333 wounded in Israel's 23
previous air raids on Lebanon since Jan. 3.
</TEXT>
