<DOCNO> AP881209-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 0331EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cuba-Gorbachev     12-09 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-Gorbachev,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cubans Won't Get to Meet the Great Reformer Himself</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The writer traveled to Cuba to cover the visit of
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev, which was canceled.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At a small park near the seashore, Ofelia Espinosa
says sales at her newsstand of Soviet magazines were negligible two
years ago.
   Now, she says, she prepares for a stampede whenever certain
Soviet publications translated into Spanish arrive, particularly the
monthly ``Sputnik'' and the weekly ``News of Moscow.''
   The difference between now and two years ago is ``glasnost,''
President Mikhail Gorbachev's experiment with allowing open debate
on issues once rarely discussed outside Kremlin walls.
   Glasnost has helped boost sales for Ms. Espinosa. She says she
gets about 60 copies each of the two magazines per delivery.
``They're gone in about five minutes,'' she says, recalling the time
not long ago when the same publications were discarded for lack of
buyers.
   Today was to have been the day Gorbachev began a three-day visit
to Cuba, offering an opportunity to measure his appeal among
ordinary Cubans. But he cut short his three-nation trip Thursday and
rushed back to the Soviet Union from New York to supervise relief
efforts in earthquake-stricken Armenia.
   For Cubans who sense that Marxism is here to stay but who are
eager for a more flexible system, the Soviet leader is the most
promising development in years.
   Several Cubans privately confess their admiration for Gorbachev.
They hope for Soviet-style reforms in Cuba, where outspokenness is
discouraged and the economy has stagnated for years.
   However, millions of other Cubans appear to have retained their
allegiance to Cuban leader Fidel Castro, who has made no secret of
his disdain for Gorbachev's reforms.
   He has left the impression that he is worried the system in place
for 70 years in the Soviet Union could unravel under Gorbachev's
leadership.
   Castro has insisted Cuba will never accept any reform that
``reeks of capitalism.'' His inflexible stand has led to speculation
about a possibly serious Soviet-Cuban rift.
   Despite the tension, Cuban authorities had planned for Gorbachev
the grandest reception ever staged for a visiting luminary, with a
projected 500,000 lining the parade route.
   U.S. and Cuban analysts agree that the foundation of Soviet-Cuban
friendship remains solid. Castro helps the Soviets collect political
support worldwide, and the Soviets lavish an estimated $5 billion in
annual economic aid on Cuba.
   Some Westerners, however, believe the Soviet Union has been
dissatisfied with Cuban economic performance for years. It is not
known if Gorbachev has pressured Cuba to impose capitalist-style
reforms to revive the Cuban economy.
   With the postponement of Gorbachev's visit, the answer probably
will not be forthcoming for now.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881209-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 0347EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-MoneyCrisis     12-09 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Money Crisis,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Peacekeeping Mission Could Break United Nations, Says U.N.
Chief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demands for new peacekeeping missions could
force the financially strapped United Nations into insolvency in
1989, according to a report by U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar.
   The U.N. chief's pessimistic assessment was released Thursday
before he left for Oslo, Norway, to accept the 1988 Nobel Peace
Prize on behalf of U.N. peacekeepers worldwide.
   The Nobel includes a cash prize worth about $390,000, but that
won't make much of a dent in the $450.1 million in unpaid dues that
U.N. members owe. The United States owes $337.3 million.
   U.N. officials haven't announced how the award money being
collected Saturday will be used.
   On Wednesday, Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev spoke to the
General Assembly and called for a new U.N. peacekeeping force in
Afghanistan to oversee establishment of a broad-based government.
   U.N. officials already are drafting plans for a 7,500-member
peacekeeping force to monitor South-West Africa's transition to
independence. Plans also are under way to send 2,000 peacekeeping
troops to monitor an independence referendum in Western Sahara.
   Perez de Cuellar predicted that in 1989, the United Nations will
collect $779.3 million but will spend $803.9 million, ending the
year with a loss of $24.6 million.
   He based his projections on current payment patterns.
   ``The United Nations has yet to leave behind the spectre of the
financial crisis. Throughout 1988, the organization has confronted
the possibility of imminent bankruptcy, which it has narrowly
managed to avoid so far,'' Perez de Cuellar wrote in the report.
   Only 79 of the 159 member states had paid all their dues as of
Nov. 30, he said. ``Of the 80 member states still in arrears, 40
owed more than their 1988 assessments,'' he added.
   Assuming next year's payment patterns are like 1988, the U.N.
chief said ``the organization would manage to avoid insolvency, but
only by once again utilizing its reserves to meet cash requirements
at many points during the year.''
   The United Nations has a contingency reserve fund of about $210
million that must be replenished as soon as new dues are paid. The
United Nations often dips into this fund to start new peacekeeping
operations or to meet operating costs.
   ``The financial situation of the United Nations could rapidly and
dramatically deteriorate should any additional demands be placed
upon these depleted reserves to meet the cash requirements for
existing or new peacekeeping operations,'' the report says.
   President Reagan said in September that the United States would
gradually repay all its dues. It has withheld money in recent years
to protest what the Reagan administration saw as mismanagement,
overstaffing, and an anti-Western bias at the United Nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881209-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 0430EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArmenianTreasures     12-09 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Armenian Treasures,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armenian Earthquake May Have Destroyed Priceless Art Treasures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The earthquake that devastated several cities and
wiped out villages in Soviet Armenia may have also doomed priceless
medieval art and early Christian churches in the region, an art
historian said.
   ``That area is full of medieval monuments and churches,'' said
Lucy Der Manuelian, professor of Armenian art and architecture at
Tufts University. ``Some are over a thousand years old.''
   Wednesday's earthquake destroyed two-thirds of Leninakan, a city
of 250,000 people 30 miles from the epicenter, and wiped out the
nearby village of Spitak, a Soviet TV correspondent said. Early
estimates put the death toll at 50,000 to 70,000.
   Atop a mountain less than a mile from Leninakan is a 7th century
church called St. Stepanos, which contains rare wall paintings. A
domed church made of rose and brown-colored volcanic stone, St.
Stepanos is a ``priceless treasure,'' Manuelian said.
   She fears it may have been destroyed becaues it is so close to
the quake's center, but she said she has not been able to find out.
   Also within a few miles of Leninakan is an 11th century Marmashen
church and a 13th century monastery called Harich, which has a
museum that may contain priceless medieval gospel manuscripts,
Manuelian said.
   Across the border from Armenia in Eastern Turkey are the ruins of
the 9th century capital city of Armenia, called Ani. Scholars
believe that city's 10th century cathedral may have been the
inspiration for Romanesque and Gothic architecture in Western
Europe, she said.
   Armenia was the first country to make Christianity its official
religion in the year 314, Manuelian said. Its early stone churches
are of special interest because some scholars believe that Europeans
learned the building techniques used on their towering cathedrals
from the Armenians.
   ``The Soviets have been spending million of rubles to restore
these Armenian churches,'' Manuelian said. ``Whatever is destroyed
of medieval Armenian architecture is a terrific loss, because the
ones in Turkey aren't being taken care of.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881209-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 0356EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     12-09 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Against Yen, Stocks Up Moderately</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell against the Japanese yen today
in Tokyo, while stock prices rose moderately as participants weighed
the impact of the resignation of Japan's finance minister.
   The dollar ended the week at 122.43 yen, down 0.59 yen from
Thursday's closing of 123.02 yen. After opening sharply lower at
122.20 yen, the U.S. currency edged up, ranging between 122.10 and
122.47 yen during the day.
   The dollar's decline in Tokyo followed a drop in New York, where
it closed Thursday at 122.28 yen.
   In Tokyo, many participants began selling the dollar after
Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa announced his resignation, said
Mitsuhiko Kinugasa of Daiwa Bank.
   Many traders feared the departure of Miyazawa, who had opposed a
weaker dollar, could damage current international monetary
coordination, he said.
   Miyazawa announced his resignation near midday, saying he wished
to clear the way for the passage of tax reform bills now being
discussed in the upper house of parliament.
   Opposition parties had opposed a continuation of debate on the
bills until Miyazawa resigned because of inconsistencies in his
accounts of his involvement in a stock trading scandal.
   Dozens of politicians and other influential people have been
linked to the scandal, involving the purchase of unlisted shares in
Recruit-Cosmos, a real-estate company, at bargain prices, and their
subsequent resale when the stock began being traded publicly.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita accepted Miyazawa's resignation
and appointed himself finance minister. He told reporters today that
Miyazawa's departure from the Cabinet would not have a strong impact
on exchange markets.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
which plunged 291.92 points Thursday, regained 34.52 points or 0.11
percent, closing the week at 29,793.42.
   Many traders stayed on the sidelines because of caution over the
possible impact of Miyazawa's resignation on the currency and stock
markets, dealers said.
   Toshiaki Yui of Nomura Securities said the Nikkei rose in spite
of the wait-and-see mood because of lingering bullishness from the
Nikkei index having achieved the 30,000-point level for the first
time on Wednesday and the rise of the dollar after the Soviet
Union's announcement of an arms reduction.
   ``Minor stocks have been attracting participants recently, which
is likely to help the market accumulate strength,'' he said.
   Yui said the Nikkei index has been strong because the Japanese
economy is expanding, whereas the United States continues to run
large trade and budget deficits.
   Volume traded on the market's first section was estimated at 1
billion shares.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
