<DOCNO> AP881209-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 0448EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Soldiers     12-09 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Soldiers,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Weapons Deter Crowds, Help Soldiers Feel More In Control</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JEBALIYA, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year after the Palestinian
uprising began, Israeli soldiers believe they are gradually
regaining control of the streets despite ongoing clashes.
   Talks with soldiers in both the Gaza Strip and the West Bank
indicate morale is much improved since the chaotic early days of the
uprising, when thousands of Palestinians joined demonstrations
against Israel's 21-year occupation.
   Today, the best evidence things have changed is that
confrontations are usually limited to skirmishes with small groups
of Arab youths who appear only long enough to hurl a stone before
vanishing into the narrow alleyways.
   ``In the beginning we used to face crowds of 5,000 people. Now we
are dealing with at most about 100,'' said Lt. Col. Micha, whose
infantry unit recently returned to this squalid refugee camp of
70,000.
   Micha recalls that in December 1987 his unit was transferred from
Lebanon and thrust into the riots without training or the necessary
tools.
   ``We got here and we suddenly had no weapons to use, no
artillery, no tanks,'' said Micha, whose full name was not disclosed
in keeping with army policy.
   ``We had clubs, and they had sticks, and we battled like gangs.
Officers were simply told to make the situation quiet, and there was
a lot of gray in the orders so every soldier had his own method for
dealing with the population.''
   At least 320 Palestinians have been killed in the rebellion since
it began Dec. 8, 1987, in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Eleven
Israelis also have been slain and 7,000 Palestinians wounded during
the same period.
   In recent interviews, army commanders attributed the drop in
large protests to improved crowd control devices such as plastic
bullets, which are less lethal than live ammunition and allow
soldiers to use rifles more freely.
   The army also has developed fender-mounted tear-gas launchers,
rooftop guns that fire rubber bullets, hot marbles or gravel, and a
wagon equipped with a scoop to remove roadblocks.
   ``Soldiers feel they have an answer. There is no longer such
frustration and feelings of impotence. The soldiers feel they
control the situation,'' said Col. Segev, who commands troops in
Nablus, the West Bank's largest town.
   Taunted by demonstrators who hurled provocative insults as well
as stones and bottles, soldiers sometimes lost control, beating
detainees or smashing houses and cars.
   In one case last spring in Kfar Salem village, soldiers used a
bulldozer to bury alive four Palestinians. The four were rescued by
witnesses minutes later.
   The army said 45 soldiers have been court-martialed since last
December for using excessive force. More soldiers have been
disciplined through less formal trials. The army will not say how
many.
   Brig. Gen. Ehud Gross, the chief army education officer,
described the number of violations as ``minor'' when compared to the
thousands of soldiers who have been sent to the occupied areas.
   Israeli newspapers say the army has an average of 10,000 troops
deployed each day in the occupied territories _ several times the
pre-uprising level.
   In an interview, Gross emphasized repeatedly that the army
believed excessive force would have a boomerang effect.
   ``If we want to bring some tranquility, some peace to the area,
the less we create polarization and hatred by revenge the more
chances there are for better future understanding,'' he said.
   The new emphasis on restraint is contained in a two-day course
instituted recently to prepare soldiers for duty in the occupied
areas and in a new briefing kit prepared for commanders.
   Gross said the army's mission was to restore enough order to
``enable the government to make its decisions free from pressure, or
under the least amount of pressure possible.''
   He claimed the army ``can cope with the mission, and we can
fulfill it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
