<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GorbachevAftershock     12-09 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gorbachev Aftershock,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Early Departure Elicits Sympathy, Sorrow and Savings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The abrupt departure of Mikhail Gorbachev
elicited sympathy and sadness from those who were dropped from his
itinerary, but others fed up with two days of ``Gorby-lock'' had few
regrets.
   ``The mood is very sad,'' said Elaine Fink, principal of P.S. 6,
the Manhattan grammar school that had hoped to host the Soviet
leader's wife, Raisa, Thursday afternoon. ``It's a lesson in
disappointment for us all.''
   The lesson was echoed at each planned stop by the Gorbachevs on
their final day in Manhattan. The Soviet leader returned home a day
early to lead relief efforts for victims of a massive earthquake
that ravaged Armenia.
   ``I think the only thing we can say is to express sympathy for
the earthquake victims,'' said John Ross, head of public relations
at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, another Big Apple tourist sight
missed by Gorbachev.
   The Soviet President's admiring American hosts managed to squeeze
in one last event just before he boarded his plane at Kennedy
International Airport just after noon Thursday. Former astronaut
James B. Irwin presented Gorbachev with a Soviet flag that went to
the moon in 1971 with the Apollo 15 mission.
   Irwin said he and his crewmates, David R. Scott and Alfred
Worden, signed the flag, which was one of a number of foreign flags
carried by the moonwalkers.
   Gorbachev and his wife also had planned a short stroll through
Central Park before their museum visit and a morning stop at the
Javits Convention Center for a Soviet trade show.
   ``I guess I'll just go do some Christmas shopping and go home,''
said John Chrystal, chief operating officer of Bankers Trust Co. of
Des Moines, Iowa, who was invited by Gorbachev to attend the trade
event.
   Chrystal's uncle, Roswell Garst, owned the Iowa farm that Nikita
Khrushchev visited in one of the high points of his 1959 American
tour.
   ``Yes, we are disappointed, but who can argue with an
earthquake?'' asked Parks Commissioner Henry Stern, who was to be
Gorbachev's host in the park. ``We hope he can come back another
time.''
   For the New York City Police Department, sympathy and sorrow gave
way to relief over savings. Officials figured the visit cost
$613,000 in overtime; the extra day would have put that figure at $1
million.
   The sighs of relief also came from the Transportation Department,
which battled mild ``Gorby-lock'' caused by Gorbachev's motorcade
and stifled traffic in midtown Manhattan Wednesday.
   ``We're doing better now,'' said Joe O'Brien, a spokesman for the
department.
   Also bumped by the change in plans was billionaire developer
Donald Trump, whose invitation to have Gorbachev visit the opulent
Trump Tower was rejected. Trump was among a group scheduled for
dinner Thursday night at the Soviet Mission; instead, the closest he
came to the Soviet leader was a glimpse of a Gorby look-alike on
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
