<1ST_LINE>u i PM-QuakeScene     12-09 0744</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quake Scene,0769</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Quake Coverage Unprecedented, Aimed At Healing Ethnic Rift</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Quake, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With Pravda headlining ``Our pain and tragedy'' on
its front page and television showing soldiers digging for
schoolchildren in piles of rubble, Soviet media have covered the
devastating earthquake in Armenia with unprecedented detail and
urgency.
   ``Helpless, sobbing people are climbing on the wreckage of an
apartment house, from which can be heard heart-rending cries for
help,'' Pravda reported today in a dramatic departure from its
typical dry reports of Communist Party decrees and speeches.
   ``Powerless, without anything they can do, the living
superstitiously run back and forth,'' the story said.
   Driven by destruction that has killed tens of thousands of
people, Soviet authorities are using the media to broadcast urgent
appeals for everything from heavy-duty cranes to blood.
   Officials also are emphasizing the need for national cooperation
in coping with the tragedy, in an attempt to use the disaster to
stop the ethnic strife that has killed at least 60 people in Armenia
and neighboring Azerbaijan this year and sent 180,000 fleeing their
homes in fear of mobs.
   Parts of both republics were being patrolled by soldiers and
tanks when the quake hit.
   ``Reproaches and mutual offenses are thrown away'' in the
aftermath of such a tragedy, Azerbaijani health minister T.A.
Kasumov said on national television Thursday. ``There is a saying
among the Azerbaijani people: `The pain unites,''' he said.
   ``Our hospitals are ready to take patients and wounded from
Armenia, and they will be surrounded by special care and
attention,'' Kasumov promised. That would be a stark contrast to
recent weeks, when medical care and food supplies had been denied to
whole neighborhoods of Armenians in Azerbaijan.
   The focus of much of the Soviet reporting has been on the
rescuers rather than victims.
   Television journalists spoke sadly of tens of thousands of dead
Thursday, but their film showed crunched and crushed buildings
rather than children's mangled bodies. Reporters interviewed
officials about the rescue effort instead of grieving parents.
   Broadcasters spoke of half the city of Kirovakan being leveled,
but they showed no aerial photos indicating the extent of the
damage. Nor were there pictures of tent cities being erected to
shelter families left homeless by the quake.
   Most Soviet photographers aimed their cameras at the relief
effort: evacuation of victims by military helicopters, cranes
clearing away destruction and volunteers rushing to donate blood.
   A few of the photographs published in Moscow and sent abroad by
the official news agency Tass show grieving women in Spitak, and
mothers and their bundled children huddling around campfires in the
remnants of downtown Leninakan.
   Tass photographer Sergei Chistyakov said his agency sold one such
dramatic photo to the French photo agency SIPA for $2,500 for its
exclusive use outside the Soviet Union. ``I hate to sell pictures of
the tragedy,'' he said. ``But we are on `self-accounting' now, and
they say we must.''
   Soviet enterprises are switching to a new economic regime where
they must turn a profit.
   Today's reports in the national newspapers were the first to
detail the suffering of the victims. The story was given remarkable
prominence.
   Pravda ran a photo of a partially collapsed building on its front
page, a spot normally reserved for pictures of happy workers and
politicians.
   The relative speed of the coverage is also remarkable in a nation
that until recently ignored natural disasters.
   Just last week, it left unreported the hijacking of a bus full of
30 schoolchildren until foreign news agencies learned of it through
air traffic control communications on the hijackers' plans to fly to
Israel.
   The earthquake was first reported in one of the most unlikely
sources of news on the Soviet Union, the Islamic Republic News
Agency of Iran.
   But shortly thereafter, Soviet seismologists confirmed it to
questioning reporters. Still, it was not until eight hours after the
quake hit that Tass called it a disaster.
   And it was not until Thursday, when President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev cut short his trip to New York to oversee relief efforts,
that officials began to speak of thousands of dead.
   Part of the delay can be explained by the destruction itself.
   Chistyakov said Tass photographers based in Yerevan reached the
damaged area via military helicopter while the Tass correspondents
were stuck on the blocked highway. As a result, he said, Tass had
pictures ready to transmit before it had a story.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
