<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-France     12-09 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Czechoslovakia-France,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mitterrand Meets With Czech Dissidents At Embassy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   French President Francois
Mitterrand met today with eight leading Czechoslovak dissidents, the
first such meeting by a Western leader on an official visit to
Prague.
   Leading human rights activists had voiced fears before
Mitterrand's two-day visit started Thursday that it would be
exploited by the Communist authorities to mute recent Western
criticism of the jailing and repression of independent activists.
   But banned playwright Vaclav Havel, who wrote an open letter to
Mitterrand last week regarding those fears, said after the 75-minute
breakfast at the French embassy that the president was ``very
well-informed about the situation'' in Czechoslovakia.
   ``I am very satisfied with this conversation,'' Havel said. ``It
is the first time a head of a state officially met independent
activists. It is a new phenomenon which is very important for us.''
   Havel, a leading signatory of the Charter 77 human rights
document, also expressed satisfaction that Mitterrand lauded the
1968 ``Prague Spring'' reforms in a dinner speech Wednesday.
   The speech was printed in full this morning in the Communist
Party daily Rude Pravo.
   ``It's the first positive mention of the Prague Spring in Rude
Pravo in 20 years,'' Havel said, smiling.
   Charter 77 spokesman Milos Hajek, another dissident present at
the meeting, called Mitterrand's mention of the Prague Spring
``excellent.''
   Others attending the meeting at the French embassy were Charter
77 signatories Jiri Dienstbier, Petr Uhl, Ladislav Lis, Rudolf
Battek and Vaclav Maly, a banned Roman Catholic priest.
   Karel Srp, leader of the independent cultural group the Jazz
Section, was the eighth man present.
   The meeting took place a day before Communist authorities permit
a demonstration called by Charter 77 and four other independent
groups to mark the 40th anniversary of International Human Rights
Day.
   For the first time since 1969, authorities have given permission
for the independent gathering.
   Havel said he was sure this was connected with Mitterrand's visit.
   ``The day after he leaves, they could not do what they did with
other independent demonstrations,'' Havel said.
   In October, hundreds of police with water cannon, tear gas,
batons and dogs broke up a crowd of about 5,000 who defied a ban on
a rally called by the same five groups to mark 70 years of
Czechoslovak independence.
   Another demonstration protesting the 1968 invasion that crushed
reform in Czechoslovakia was also broken up by police in August.
</TEXT>
