<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HongKong-China     12-09 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hong Kong-China,0208</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain, China Reach Agreement On Post-1997 Extradition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British-Chinese negotiators working out
details of turning Hong Kong over to Chinese rule ended their 11th
meeting today with an agreement over the territory's future
extradition arrangements.
   The British colony reverts to Chinese sovereignty in 1997 under
an agreement reached four years ago by London and Beijing. The
Sino-British Joint Liaison Group was formed to help implement the
accord.
   A statement from the group said the two sides ``reached agreement
on the basic principles'' by which Hong Kong will make its own
arrangements for extradition after 1997, but provided no details.
The territory now relies on Britain's network of extradition
treaties.
   ``As a major financial and commercial center, Hong Kong should be
able to maintain its own network of extradition agreements,'' said
Robin McLaren, spokesman for the British team. ``Nobody wants Hong
Kong to become a sort of haven for criminals which people could go
to and couldn't be extradited from.''
   The group also discussed the withdrawal of British armed forces
from the colony and arrangements for Chinese troops to be based
here, but again no details were provided.
   The liaison group will meet next March in Beijing.
</TEXT>
