<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     12-09 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOVELAND, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How do you make a nude statue respectable?
Stand it against a wall, according to the Loveland Visual Arts
Commission.
   The commission was caught in a controversy that broke out over
``Moulding Our Future,'' a proposed 7-foot-tall bronze monument
meant to celebrate love, the town's namesake.
   On Thursday, the commission wriggled out of the problem,
tentatively approving the statue of a mother with a child at her
breast for a new park, but ordering the sculpture to be turned
toward a wig shop wall so it won't offend passers-by.
   The woman's breasts will also be covered by trees, hiding them
from unsuspecting strollers.
   About 600 residents signed a petition against the statue, saying
they like love and Loveland but wanted the statue to have another
home. Customers at the wig shop also protested.
   The commission is scheduled to take a final vote on the statue
Dec. 16.
   Artist Denny Hasken was happy with the compromise because the
child in his work will be facing park visitors.
   ``This is not a nude,'' Hasken said. ``This is a mother and
child.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PINE MOUNTAIN, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hansels and Gretels beware: Peter
Brochu's gingerbread house may be the world's largest.
   Brochu, executive chef at the Callaway Gardens Inn, had the help
of seven chefs, 13 cooks and the entire maintenance department of
the west Georgia resort to build the gingerbread house _ complete
with lights, chimney, picket fence lined with poinsettias and
icicles hanging from the roof.
   There are 450 pounds of candies and cookies in the decorations.
   Modeled after the structure that almost led to the downfall of
Hansel and Gretel in the fairy tale, the house on display in the
lobby of Callaway Gardens through New Year's Day.
   The structure, 14 feet long, 6{ feet high and 4 feet wide, is
built from, among other things, 1,200 pounds of powdered sugar, 175
sheet pans of gingerbread, 1,080 egg whites, 120 pounds of honey,
550 pounds of all-purpose flour and 1,200 assorted Christmas lights.
   ``It might be a record, we don't know,'' Brochu said. ``But it's
just beautiful, especially at night with all the lights.''
   Working night and day for three days over Thanksgiving weekend,
it took Brochu and his crew 315 hours to complete the confectionary
castle.
</TEXT>
