<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell today against most major currencies
in modest late-morning European trading but traders said they
expected little movement during the session.
   Gold prices fell.
   Traders said the exchange market was coming off a dollar rally
that followed Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev's announcement
earlier in the week of troop reductions.
   In Germany, they said official dollar sales by the Deutsche
Bundesbank Thursday added to the currency's weakness.
   Dealers said they expected the dollar to move in a reasonably
narrow range through today's session.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.59 yen to a closing 122.43 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 122.65 yen.
   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound. It cost
$1.8435 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.8510 Thursday.
   Other mid-morning dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Thursday:
   _1.7375 West German marks, down from 1.7420
   _1.4625 Swiss francs, down from 1.4665
   _5.9375 French francs, down from 5.9450
   _1.9607 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9645
   _1,283.00 Italian lire, down from 1,285.00
   _1.1945 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1933
   Gold opened at a bid price of $422.10 a troy ounce, down from
$423.50 late Thursday. At mid-morning, London's major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $422.20.
   In Zurich, gold fell to close at a bid $422.65 from $423 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.24 to close at a bid $423.64.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at a bid price of $6.12 a troy ounce, compared with
Thursday's $6.16.
