<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CondomCaper     12-09 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Condom Caper,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>16,000 Condoms Stolen From Family Planning Clinic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A downtown hospital is investigating the theft of
16,000 prophylactics that has officials puzzled since the condoms
are given away free in the first place.
   The missing condoms, discovered Wednesday by officials at Grady
Memorial Hospital's family planning clinic, temporarily crippled a
program that distributes about 500,000 condoms a year.
   ``It's amazing. They did clean us out,'' said Grady clinic's
director, Dr. Robert Hatcher, on Thursday. ``Maybe those condoms are
in the right hands now.''
   Police believe the theft occurred Tuesday night. Hatcher said he
found his offices trashed and telephones missing when he arrived at
work Wednesday morning.
   ``Then we found out that in our supply room, 16,000 condoms had
been stolen. We ended up with no condoms,'' Hatcher said. ``But most
of our patients maintain a supply at home. We're just telling them
to be careful.''
   News of the theft prompted an Eatontown, N.J. condom
manufacturer, Ansell-Americas Inc., to replace the clinic's supply
free of charge.
   Hatcher said each day his clinic dispenses about 2,000 condoms _
roughly 40 to 160 per patient _ and encourages clients to pass the
condoms on to family members and friends.
   ``Our hope is that those stolen condoms are used so they help
prevent unplanned pregnancies and unwanted infections,'' he said.
   Hatcher, who has served at the Grady clinic for 25 years, said
the condom theft was a first. He urged the bandits to ``come back
and see us again and we'll be glad to help.''
</TEXT>
