<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 0654EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Sakharov     12-09 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sakharov,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sakharov Ends U.S. Trip, Heads To Paris</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bidding goodbye after a four-week visit, Soviet
human rights activist Andrei Sakharov called the United States a
wonderful country but said he had no desire to move here.
   ``I think that my fate is completely bound up with the country
where I was born, and I want to live there,'' Sakharov said Thursday
night before boarding a jet to Paris and a possible meeting with
Polish Solidarity leader Lech Walesa.
   The 67-year-old Nobel laureate also called for an international
effort to aid victims of the massive earthquake that struck Soviet
Armenia, killing tens of thousands of people.
   Sakharov arrived in the United States Nov. 4 as a Soviet delegate
to the International Foundation for the Survival and Development of
Humanity, an organization formed this year by Soviet and American
scientists to foster cooperation on arms control, hunger, pollution
and other issues.
   During his stay, he visited relatives in the Boston area,
attended a private dinner in New York and met with President Reagan
in Washington. He also underwent tests at Massachusetts General
Hospital, where doctors determined he did not need a heart pacemaker.
   It was Sakharov's first visit to the West, and he and others
hailed it as a symbol of change in the Soviet Union.
   ``Just by being able to make the trip he achieved a lot,'' said
Joshua Rubenstein, Northeast regional director for Amnesty
International. ``He showed he could come and that Soviet security
was not threatened as has always been argued.''
   ``Sakharov is a symbol for people who were persecuted from the
late 1960s until the 1980s,'' said Stephen F. Cohen, professor of
Soviet studies at Princeton University. ``It's a sign to people in
the Soviet Union that it's now possible to protest official policies
and still travel freely and move in high circles.''
   Sakharov, who helped develop the Soviet hydrogen bomb, previously
was barred from traveling abroad because of his past scientific
work. He was also restricted to the industrial city of Gorky for
seven years because of his outspoken opposition to Soviet
intervention in Afghanistan.
   In 1986, Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev personally called him
back to Moscow. Since then, Sakharov has generally supported
Gorbachev's perestroika, or political and economic restructuring,
while speaking out against some trends, including the growing
concentration of power in Gorbachev's hands.
   Using his stepdaughter, Tatiana Yankelevich, as a translator,
Sakharov said before his departure at Logan International Airport
that ``support for perestroika should be very strong but by no means
unconditional.''
   He warned that perestroika still faces many obstacles and that
the reforms ``cannot yet be called irreversible.''
   He praised Gorbachev's announcement Wednesday of unilateral troop
cuts, saying the Soviet leader ``has taken a very important
initiative ... that will broaden international support for him and
therefore strengthen his position in the Soviet Union.''
   Sakharov, who received the Nobel Peace Prize in 1975 for his
human rights activities, plans to attend a celebration in Paris of
the 40th anniversary of the United Nations' Universal Declaration of
Human Rights. He said he may also meet with Walesa in France before
returning to Moscow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881209-0067 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 0656EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Summit-Gorbachev     12-09 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Gorbachev,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Visit, Though Short, Was Fruitful</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amid a hasty departure, Mikhail S. Gorbachev
paused to thank New York for its friendliness and speak
optimistically of the prospects for world peace.
   ``The road ahead will be tough but we will go ahead, and we will
_ I believe _ be building on what has been achieved if we act as we
have been acting, and also maybe add something new,'' the Soviet
leader said Thursday as he headed back to Moscow after a disastrous
earthquake in the Soviet south.
   He flew out of New York a day earlier than scheduled and canceled
planned visits to Havana and London because of the massive quake
centered in Armenia that killed tens of thousands of people.
   Although his stay was brief _ 45 hours _ the communist leader
dazzled world leaders with a dramatic troop reduction proposal and
captured the hearts of New Yorkers, who gathered by the thousands
along Manhattan streets to wave and cheer his speeding motorcade.
   The warm feelings were not lost on Gorbachev, who said the kind
of hospitality he experienced showed an ``increasing friendliness
and willingness to cooperate on the part of the Soviet people and
the American people.''
   ``We believe that this may have been one of the most important
things that happened on this day of our stay in America,'' Gorbachev
said before leaving from Kennedy International Airport.
   Gorbachev explained his abrupt departure at an airport news
conference, saying the quake, which registered 6.9 on the Richter
scale, ``had extremely grave consequences, devastation and grave
loss of life.''
   Although he had only ``one working day'' in New York, Gorbachev
said, ``I and my delegation believe that this was a very important
day.''
   The highlights of the visit were Gorbachev's announcement before
the U.N. General Assembly that he planned a major reduction in
Soviet troop strength over the next three years, and his superpower
luncheon with President Reagan and President-elect Bush.
   Gorbachev, the first Soviet chief to visit New York in 28 years,
said his U.N. speech and a later reception gave him the opportunity
to ``set out our views ... on the world today, and on the prospects
of the world's development.''
   Gorbachev called the Governors Island session with Reagan and
Bush ``a good meeting, held in ... an open and trusting atmosphere.''
   He said the one word he would use to characterize it was
``continuity'' and all parties walked away ``confident that our
relations will expand and improve on the basis of cooperation, on
the basis of mutual respect for each other's interests.''
   Gorbachev later added, ``I think I would be remiss in my duty if
I went home without saying how much we are grateful to New Yorkers,
for the hospitality and feelings of friendship that they have been
expressing over these days. ... We value that very much.''
   He had planned to visit the first Soviet trade show in the United
States, Central Park and the Metropolitan Museum on Thursday.
Gorbachev's wife, Raisa, canceled a visit with children at an Upper
East Side elementary school.
</TEXT>
