<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DoctorCharged     12-09 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Doctor Charged,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctor Charged With `Gross Immorality' For Secretly Performing
Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gynecologist charged by the State Medical
Board with gross immorality for allegedly performing
sexual-enhancement surgery on women without their knowledge says
he's eager to answer the charges.
   Dr. James C. Burt of Dayton was cited Thursday with violating
several provisions of the Medical Practices Act in 78 instances
involving 33 patients dating to March 1966, said Lauren Lubow, a
spokeswoman for the 12-member board.
   Burt, 67, also is being sued by two former patients who claim he
performed sexual-enhancement surgery on them without their knowledge.
   In an interview with a Dayton television station Thursday, Burt
said he had not been notified by the medical board of the charges
against him.
   ``I'm looking forward to answering whatever charges,'' Burt told
WDTN-TV. ``I feel that when the truth comes out that I will be
totally vindicated.''
   Ms. Lubow said Burt, who was banned by the board from surgical
practice in November, has 30 days to seek a public hearing on the
charges. Failing to do so ``would permit the board to construe those
allegations as having been proven,'' she said.
   Burt faces possible penalties ranging from reprimand to
revocation of his license.
   Burt's techniques came under fire in October after CBS' ``West
57th Street'' program investigated his surgical procedures.
   That report and the medical board's citation also referred to
Burt's 1975 book, ``Surgery of Love,'' in which he admitted he had
performed reconstructive surgery aimed at enhancing sexual pleasure
without his patients' knowledge.
   In his book, Burt wrote, ``One doesn't have to go into the
complexity of sexuality with the patient and her partner; one merely
does the operation of coital area reconstruction. ... In many
hundreds of these patients, the patient had not been informed that
anything more had been done to her than delivery and episiotomy and
repair.''
   The board said Burt conducted experimental surgeries that
included rotation of the vagina away from the bladder and internal
genitalia, and extension of the vagina to align it with the
clitoris, an external tissue that responds to sexual stimulation.
   The procedures in many cases resulted in complications,
complaints of sexual dysfunction, infection, a necessity for
corrective surgery and chronic pain, the board said.
</TEXT>
