<HEAD>Hired Killer Called Loving, Warm, Insightful</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor David Soul and a former TV news
anchorwoman testified that an ex-policeman convicted of a contract
murder was warm, insightful and great with kids.
   Soul, who starred in the TV show ``Starsky and Hutch,'' and
Christine Lund, a former anchorwoman at KABC-TV in Los Angeles,
spoke on behalf of Robert Von Villas during the penalty phase of the
former Los Angeles police officer's trial. Von Villas could face the
death penalty.
   Miss Lund called Von Villas an ``insightful human being ... who
has immense good in him.''
   Soul described Von Villas as a ``loving, warm person who is great
with kids.''
   Von Villas, 44, of Simi Valley was convicted last month of murder
and conspiracy to murder. He was charged with killing Thomas Weed,
52, in 1983 in exchange for $20,000 from Weed's former wife. Weed's
body has never been found.
   Jurors can recommend that Von Villas be sentenced to death or
life in prison without possibility of parole.
   Another former police officer, Richard Herman Ford, 48, was
convicted Oct. 11 of the same charges in Weed's slaying, but his
jury was unable to reach a decision on his punishment.
   The district attorney's office hasn't decided whether to retry
the penalty phase of Ford's case to seek the death penalty. Without
a retrial, a judge could sentence Ford to life in prison with or
without the possibility of parole.
   Miss Lund testified Wednesday that she met Von Villas when he was
on patrol near her Chatsworth home. She said they became friends,
mainly because both were interested in the problems of children.
   Miss Lund described Von Villas as a devoted family man who had a
``magic touch with kids.''
   Soul testified that he and Von Villas struck up a friendship
after meeting at a ``Starsky and Hutch'' filming location.
   Soul called Von Villas ``a very responsive human being, the kind
of person I like to know, the type I wish there were more of.''
