<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel     12-09 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arabs Mark Uprising Anniversary with Acts of Defiance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GAZA CITY, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians marked the
first year of their revolt against Israeli rule today by erecting
roadblocks, burning tires and flying balloons with the colors of the
outlawed Palestinian flag.
   Four Palestinians were wounded in clashes with troops in the
occupied West Bank following Moslem noon prayers, Arab doctors said.
   All 650,000 residents of the Gaza Strip were confined to their
homes under a military curfew imposed Thursday night following
scattered daytime clashes.
   In Gaza City, streets were virtually deserted, but the stench of
tires set ablaze in protest permeated the air.
   In the West Bank town of Tulkarem, a prayer leader at the main
mosque interrupted his sermon to announce Israeli casualties today
in Lebanon, where Israeli commandos attacked a pro-Syrian
Palestinian guerrilla base.
   ``I have good news for you,'' the Moslem cleric told worshipers.
``An Israeli soldier has been killed.''
   An Israeli announcement, delayed for several hours until the
fighting ended, said combined naval, air and ground forces attacked
the bases of Ahmed Jibril's Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command.
   Throughout the occupied territories, businesses were shuttered
and transportation was halted for a second straight day in
observance of a PLO-ordered general strike to mark the anniversary
of the revolt, which has claimed the lives of 320 Palestinians and
11 Israelis since Dec. 8, 1987.
   Dozens of Palestinian flags flew in the open-air market of
Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, and residents released
balloons in the colors of the outlawed flag, Palestinian reports
said.
   Slogans painted on the walls of the Tulkarem refugee camp
declared: ``Happy New Year to the Intefadeh,'' which means uprising
in Arabic.
   Palestinian demonstrators clashed with troops in the Balata and
Fara refugee camps near Nablus following noon prayers. Hospital
officials said four Palestinians were wounded, including a
22-year-old man shot in the mouth. The army said it was checking the
reports.
   In Jerusalem, four Israeli cars were burned overnight, and police
discovered a Palestinian flag nearby, a police spokesman said. A
note written in Hebrew in support of the uprising also was found,
Israel radio said.
   Two left-wing legislators said in a report today that the
uprising has become institutionalized and is ``gaining in strength''
contrary to army predictions.
   Yossi Sarid and Dedi Zucker of the Citizens' Rights Movement
charged that the 70,000 Jewish settlers living in the West Bank and
Gaza Strip had become ``a garrison force'' seldom called to answer
for their ``wild deeds.''
   According to the report, published in the English-language
Jerusalem Post, 16 Palestinians have been killed by settler gunfire
during the uprising.
   The report also accused the army of doing little to punish troops
who violated standing orders on the treatment of Palestinians.
   It said 600 cases of alleged violations had been opened, but only
20 soldiers brought to trial. The army recently said it has carried
out 45 courts martial and 15 soldiers were given jail terms up to a
year.
</TEXT>
