<1ST_LINE>r a PM-INFParty     12-09 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-INF Party,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Treaty Inspectors Celebrate INF's First Birthday,</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet and American officials ate rum cake
with frosting missiles in a party marking the first anniversary of
the signing of the Intermediate Nuclear Forces treaty.
   ``Don't let anybody carry that cake outside,'' one partygoer said
Wednesday, joking about Utah's liquor laws. ``We could get busted.''
   In the Soviet city of Votkinsk, American inspectors suspended the
policy prohibiting alcohol after their Soviet escorts brought in
pastries and wine.
   Americans are in the Soviet Union to verify that the Soviets no
longer produce SS-20 missiles at the Votkinsk Machine Building
Plant. The Soviets are here to make sure no more Pershing II
missiles are built at the Hercules Aerospace plant in Magna.
   President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev signed
the INF Treaty in Washington on Dec. 7, 1987. The agreement, which
bans medium-range nuclear missiles, took effect in June. Salt Lake
County and Votkinsk are the only two permanent inspection sites
named in the treaty.
   ``What we're doing today is starting a joint cultural tradition,
with the celebration of the signing of the treaty that brings you
here to Utah,'' James Szatkowski, U.S. site commander, said during
the party.
   As many as 30 Soviet inspectors will serve two- and three-month
duty tours for the next 13 years in Salt Lake County under terms of
the treaty.
   ``There's certainly a sense of history in what we're about here
and a sense of pioneering in the area of peace,'' Szatkowski said.
``I think we're all proud to be a part of this exciting time in
international history.''
</TEXT>
