<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EcclesiaHearing     12-09 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ecclesia Hearing,0471</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fatal Beating At Church Camp Described</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OREGON CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An 8-year-old girl was beaten as many as
500 times, slammed against a wall and dropped on the pavement the
night she died at a church camp, one of four people accused in the
death told authorities.
   The girl, Dayna Lorea Broussard, hid in a corner but the beatings
continued with a hose after a plastic pipe and bamboo cane broke,
Frederick P. Doolittle, 28, told a deputy sheriff.
   The girl was the daughter of Eldridge Broussard Jr., founder of
the Ecclesia Athletic Association that ran the camp at a rural house
southeast of Portland. Broussard also ran the Watts Christian Center
in Los Angeles.
   A tape of an interview Doolittle gave to the deputy the day after
the girl's Oct. 14 death was played Thursday before Clackamas County
Circuit Judge John Lowe, who is considering pre-trial defense
motions to suppress information the defendants provided authorities.
   Charged with manslaughter in the girl's death are Doolittle,
Brian J. Brinson, 30, Constance Jackson, 37, and Willie Chambers, 35.
   Defense lawyers allege in their motion to suppress the
information that the defendants were not properly advised of their
rights.
   Lowe made no decision and said the hearing would continue Monday.
The judge said he was delaying the start of the defendants' trial
until Feb. 6.
   Lowe also released Doolittle and Brinson on their own
recognizance. Jackson and Chambers were released in mid-November.
   On the tape, Doolittle told how he came to Oregon a few days
before the child's death to work at the camp. When he arrived,
Doolittle said Chambers told him Dayna had been a problem and they
would have to discipline her.
   He said Chambers told him the child had stolen some pieces of
chicken she was not supposed to have.
   Doolittle said the beating began Oct. 13 when Jackson pushed the
girl against a wall three to five times, after which the girl said
she was having trouble seeing and was dizzy.
   Doolittle said he and Brinson held the girl down while Chambers
beat her repeatedly with a leather strap, a bamboo cane and a
plastic pipe. Some 250 to 500 blows were delivered, Doolittle said.
   He said the girl also was taken outside and dropped on the
pavement three to five times. At one point she tried to run and hide
in a corner. Jackson then beat her with three extension cords
braided together. Authorities said the beating lasted about 90
minutes.
   The child later was taken to a fire station, where a firefighter
tried to administer first aid.
   After the girl's death, the state took custody of 53 children
living at the camp. Officials said the children were systematically
beaten.
</TEXT>
