<HEAD>Snow Falls From Arkansas to Appalachians; Santa Ana Winds Blow
Through West</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with snow in Virginia, school
closings, snow being welcome at Michigan ski resorts; Picks up 6th
graf, `Some light ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered snow fell today from northern Arkansas to parts of
Kentucky and Tennessee and the southern Appalachians as strong winds
continued blowing through Arizona and Southern California.
   In Virginia, thousands of school children were kept home as up to
6 inches of snow fell from the north to the southwest, slickening
roads and causing power outages.
   Snow, sleet and freezing rain left roads in southwest Texas slick
today, and more precipitation was expected. A winter weather
advisory was in effect.
   A snow advisory was in effect for southern New Mexico after the
state's south-central mountains got up to 13 inches of snow. Snow
advisories also were in effect for the northern mountains of North
Carolina and parts of Tennessee.
   Locally heavy snow was expected in parts of the Great Lakes
region.
   A winter storm warning was in effect for northeast Ohio. And in
New York state, a snow squall warning was out for counties east of
Lake Ontario, where 6 inches of snow were expected.
   In Michigan, snow-making machines have been pumping out
artificial flakes for weeks, but ski resort workers awoke today to
up to 4 inches of natural snow.
   ``It was unnatural, to go so long without much snow. It scared
me,'' said Paula Brown, a receptionist at Sugar Loaf Resort in
Cedar, 15 miles northwest of Traverse City.
   Some light snow fell today in western Montana and parts of Idaho.
   Light rain lingered in eastern Texas, southern Arkansas and parts
of Tennessee, Mississippi and Alabama, as well as the Pacific
Northwest.
   Strong winds in Arizona and Southern California were generated by
a strong high-pressure system over the Rockies and a low-pressure
system in the Gulf of California.
   A high-wind warning remained in effect for the mountains and
coastal areas of Southern California, and a wind advisory for the
deserts of Southern California and extreme western Arizona.
   Today's forecast called for rain from the Middle Atlantic States
to the Carolinas, Georgia, the Gulf Coast states and eastern and
central Texas; snow in western Texas and southeast New Mexico, and
from the Great Lakes to the northern and central Appalachians, as
well as in eastern Montana and western sections of the Dakotas; fog
in the central San Joaquin Valley of California and parts of Nevada.
   High temperatures were predicted in the single digits in
northeast Minnesota; teens and 20s from eastern Montana to the
Dakotas, the upper Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes region and
northern New England; 50s from the Carolinas to the central Gulf
Coast and southern Texas; 60s to the lower 80s in Florida; 50s and
60s across the desert Southwest and much of California with some 70s
along the Southern California coast; and 30s and 40s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 13
degrees below zero in Hibbing, Minn., to 72 in Miami, Key West and
Homestead Air Force Base, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 49 cloudy; Boston 29 fair; Buffalo 22 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 47 foggy; Cincinnati 28 cloudy; Cleveland 24
cloudy; Detroit 20 fair; Miami 72 partly cloudy; New York 35 partly
cloudy; Philadelphia 33 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 23 partly cloudy;
Portland, Maine 22 fair; Washington 40 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 2 cloudy; Chicago 18 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
36 cloudy; Denver 23 partly cloudy; Des Moines 15 fair; Indianapolis
29 cloudy; Kansas City 24 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 6 fair;
Nashville 33 snow; New Orleans 60 foggy; St. Louis 29 partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 20 fair; Anchorage 26 cloudy; Las Vegas 48
fair; Los Angeles 63 fair; Phoenix 56 fair; Salt Lake City 22 fair;
San Diego 62 fair; San Francisco 57 partly cloudy; Seattle 48 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 12 fair; Toronto 25 cloudy.
</TEXT>
