<DOCNO> AP881209-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1050EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pope-Peace     12-09 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope-Peace,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Condemns Terrorists Who Claim To Speak For Minorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II urged today that the rights
of minorities be respected, but he also condemned any recourse to
violence to advance their claims and lashed out at terrorist groups
acting in their name.
   ``May those who follow the inhuman path of terrorism hear my
voice: to strike blindly, kill innocent people or carry out bloody
reprisals does not help a just evaluation of the claims advanced by
the minorites for whom they claim to act,'' the pope said in his
message for the Roman Catholic Church's World Day of Peace.
   The message, sent to world leaders each year, was titled ``To
Build Peace, Respect Minorities.''
   Vatican officials said the message was in general terms and that
John Paul had no specific ethnic, racial, religious or national
group in mind, although his words seemed directed at a number of
situations in the world.
   The pope acknowledged that ``delicate problems arise'' when a
group seeks independence or greater political autonomy.
   ``I wish to state that, in such delicate circumstances, dialogue
and negotiation are the obligatory path to peace,'' he said, adding
that a refusal to enter into dialogue ``can open the door to
violence.''
   He also declared that states that perpetrate or tolerate acts
aimed at endangering the lives of minorities, violate ``the
fundamental law governing the social order.''
   In situations of real injustice, he said it may be the duty of
groups which have emigrated to demand justice for oppressed in their
homelands. But he called for care ``especially when it is difficult
to have objective information.''
   The church marks its World Day of Peace on Jan. 1 but the pope's
message is traditionally issued in advance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
