<1ST_LINE>u i PM-France-Sakharov 1stLd-Writethru a0520 12-09 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Sakharov, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0520,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Physicist Calls For More Steps To Reduce Forces</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Sakharov comments and
material from a0516, Boston-dated PM-Sakharov. Pickup 4th graf pvs,
``Sakharov arrived...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobel laureate Andrei D. Sakharov today called for
more steps to reduce the size of the Soviet military and appealed
for massive help for the victims of the earthquake in the Armenian
republic.
   Sakharov, arriving to attend a celebration marking the 40th
anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, said one
way to cut down the Soviet military would be to limit the length of
service for Soviet draftees.
   Commenting on Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's offer
Wednesday to cut the Red Army by 500,000 men and withdraw thousands
of tanks and troops from Eastern Europe, he said it was a major
decision but only a beginning.
   The human rights activist and nuclear physicist said reductions
in manpower and weapons ``can be done and will change in a major way
the international situation. Gorbachev is going in this direction
and this is very important. I would have liked to see bigger cuts
but what was done is important.''
   Sakharov, 67, spoke at a 90-minute news conference at the Soviet
Embassy.
   He twice sidestepped questions about the political implications
of a meeting he is expected to have with Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa, who left Poland for Paris today to attend the anniversary
celebration.
   Speaking about Wednesday's devastating earthquake in Armenia,
Sakharov said volunteers were needed from all over the world to help
victims. He said he was certain Soviet authorities would welcome all
the help they could get.
   ``All other things have to take second place,'' Sakharov said,
including the ethnic unrest between Armenian and the neighboring
Azerbaijan republic that has forced an estimated 180,000 people to
flee the two republics.
   Sakharov, a founder of the Soviet dissident movement, talked at
length about Gorbachev's political and economic restructuring, known
as ``perestroika,'' saying it ``cannot yet be called irreversible.''
   For the West, he said, the failure of perestroika would be
dangerous. ``There will be a loss of internal stability in the
Soviet Union and therefore of stability in the world because the
pendulum would swing the other way in an expansionist direction,''
Sakharov said.
   He said the West should support perestroika but not
unconditionally.
   Sakharov arrived from Boston, where he had been visiting
relatives. He was to be joined tonight by his wife, Yelena Bonner,
who was en route from Moscow. Mitterrand invited the recent winners
of the Nobel Peace Prize. Walesa won the prize in 1983, Sakharov in
1975.
   Mitterrand and U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
will speak at the celebrations Saturday at the Palais Chaillot on
the Seine River.
</TEXT>
