<1ST_LINE>r w PM-GeographicCutbacks     12-09 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Geographic Cutbacks,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Geographic Facing Financial Crunch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Geographic Society is winding down
its centennial year facing financial problems, with staff reductions
planned and some book publications curtailed.
   The cutbacks were disclosed in a memo to staffers from Gilbert M.
Grosvenor, chairman of the society.
   Grosvenor said he would strive to make the staff reductions
``primarily through attrition and the transfer of regular staff
members.''
   Spokeswoman Barbara Moffett said today reductions are needed in
the wake of a financial report showing a sharp decline in the
society's year-end picture.
   The reductions could affect about 100 of the society's 2,500
workers, according to The Washington Post.
   Two children's book series will be affected by the cutbacks, Ms.
Moffett said..
   Books for World Explorers is being discontinued, she said. A
second series, Books for Young Explorers, will still be published,
but the volumes offered will be reprints of ``classics'' from the
past, she said, with no new one being developed for the time being.
   Grosvenor's memo Thursday noted that the society has employed a
large number of people on special projects in recent years, and
``such personnel will normally be phased out as these activities are
completed.''
   Indications are that the society will complete 1988 about $2
million in the black, compared to a $29 million surplus last year.
   The society, which publishes National Geographic magazine, has
had large expenses this year, including a major effort to improve
geography education, expenses for its birthday celebration and a
costly holographic cover _ a three-dimensional representation
produced with a laser _ on its December magazine.
   In addition, Grosvenor said in his memo that direct mail
promotion seems to have reached a saturation point for society
membership.
   And the nation's demographics are changing, he pointed out. The
decline in the nation's birth rate has reduced the audience for some
society publications aimed at children, for example.
</TEXT>
