<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DaughterAbducted     12-09 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Daughter Abducted,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Incapacitates Social Workers, Abducts Daughter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cancer researcher visiting his 3-year-old
daughter in state custody sprayed a Mace-like substance at four
social workers and abducted the girl, police said.
   Warrants have been issued charging William Edgar Stewart II, 48,
with aggravated battery and interfering with child custody and
accusing his wife, Kimberly Denmark Stewart, 21, with custody
interference, said police Capt. S.A. Brock.
   The child was taken into protective custody after Stewart, a
professor at the University of South Florida, was accused by the
state Health and Rehabilitative Services Department of misconduct
toward her, Brock said.
   HRS spokesman Tony Edwards declined to elaborate on the case
because such records are confidential. He said the girl had been in
state custody for more than a week.
   Social worker Judy Ann Chambers was supervising the couple's
visit Thursday when Mrs. Stewart, the child's stepmother, excused
herself only seconds before a fire alarm sounded, Brock said.
   Employees from an alarm company were working on the system and
activated it as a test. Not realizing the alarm was being tested,
state workers began filing outside.
   When Stewart, his daughter and Ms. Chambers reached a first-floor
landing, the social worker told him he could not leave the building
with the girl, officials said.
   ``Then the father sprayed a substance such as Mace into the face
of the counselor and ran out of the building with the child,'' Brock
said. Three other child care workers standing nearby also were
sprayed. All four were treated and released at a hospital.
   The Stewarts were seen driving off in a car with Georgia license
plates.
</TEXT>
