<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BrennanHospitalized 1stLd-Writethru a0422 12-09 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brennan Hospitalized, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0422,430</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 2 grafs new with Brennan responding to treatment; picks
up
2nd graf pvs, Brennan at 82. Removes pvs graf 7, On Thursday night,
as outdated.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supreme Court Justice William J. Brennan is
responding to treatment for pneumonia and may miss only one court
session, a court spokeswoman said today.
   Kathy Arberg, the spokeswoman, said Brennan ``is continuing to
improve and is resting comfortably.''
   Brennan, at 82 the oldest member of the court, was taken to the
Bethesda Naval Medical Center in suburban Maryland on Thursday after
visiting a doctor at the U.S. Capitol, court spokeswoman Toni House
said.
   ``Justice Brennan was admitted with pneumonia,'' she said. ``He
is being treated with antibiotics, and doctors expect him to respond
very well.''
   Ms. House added, ``His illness is not expected to affect his work
except for the Monday, Dec. 12, session.''
   The court is scheduled to begin a four-week recess after issuing
orders and possibly announcing decisions Monday.
   Ms. House declined to answer other questions concerning the
justice's health or his hospitalization.
   A spokesman for the medical center would confirm that Brennan is
a patient there but declined to offer any information about his
condition.
   A court employee who spoke only on the condition of anonymity
said Brennan left his court office in the early afternoon, suffering
from a fever and the chills.
   Brennan participated in the court's oral arguments Wednesday, and
reportedly has enjoyed good health recently.
   His last hospitalization occurred in August 1987 when he checked
into the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., for tests on his prostate
gland.
   The tests revealed he did not have cancer.
   ``Although the prostate is somewhat enlarged, the condition is
not malignant and no surgery is required,'' Brennan said in a
statement issued by the court at that time.
   In 1979 Brennan had a stroke that left his right hand partially
paralyzed, and a year earlier he was treated for a cancerous growth
on a vocal cord.
   Brennan, appointed to the nation's highest court by President
Dwight D. Eisenhower in 1956, is its oldest and most senior member.
   For three decades the court's leading liberal light, Brennan is
now one of three liberal, octogenarian justices. Thurgood Marshall
and Harry A. Blackmun are 80.
   By comparison, the average age of the court's conservative
justices is about 60.
   Such demographics have fueled speculation about President-elect
Bush's impact over the next four years on a court deeply divided
over such politically explosive issues as abortion and affirmative
action.
   Supreme Court justices are appointed to life terms by the
president. The appointments must win Senate confirmation.
</TEXT>
