<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Court-Brom     12-09 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Court-Brom,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Court Orders 17-Year-Old Tried As Adult In Family Ax Murders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY R. SANDOK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-ager accused of slaying his
parents, brother and sister with an ax must be tried as an adult
because of public safety concerns, the Minnesota Supreme Court ruled
today.
   The Supreme Court justices unanimously affirmed a ruling of the
state Court of Appeals in the case of David Brom, 17, of Rochester.
   The ruling said the state had ``met its burden of proving by
clear and convincing evidence that D.F.B. (Brom) is unamenable to
treatment in the juvenile court system consistent with the public
safety.''
   A lower court judge had ruled that Brom should be tried as a
juvenile.
   Brom is accused of killing his parents, Bernard and Paulette
Brom, both 41; his sister, Diane, 13, and a brother, Ricky, 11. The
bodies were found Feb. 18 in the family's home north of Rochester.
Each had died of multiple blows with an ax, authorities said.
   Brom was 16 at the time of the slayings. He turned 17 on Oct. 3.
   The Court of Appeals concluded that the lower court judge had
misinterpreted the effect of a 1980 amendment to juvenile criminal
justice law. The Appeals Court decided that keeping Brom in the
juvenile court system was inconsistent with the Legislature's intent.
   ``There can be no doubt that the offenses here are heinous and
that the only fair response of the criminal justice system, as a
matter of law, must be referral'' to adult court, the Appeals Court
said.
   Brom was arrested Feb. 19 and has been undergoing treatment at
the Oaks Treatment Center in Austin, Texas, a facility for severely
disturbed children.
   If found guilty in juvenile court, he would have been subject to
state custody until his 19th birthday. A conviction of first-degree
murder in adult court carries a mandatory life sentence, with
eligibility for parole after 17{ years.
</TEXT>
