<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NightclubFire     12-09 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nightclub Fire,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orders Hearings On Beverly Hills Fire Claims Cases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES WOLFE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFORT, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kentucky Court of Appeals today ordered
the state Board of Claims to hold hearings on a group of claims
filed against the state after the 1977 Beverly Hills Supper Club
fire that killed 165 people.
   The board had dismissed the claims without notice in 1987, saying
it had the ``inherent'' power to do so and that it would not have
been liable to the claimants, anyway.
   But the appeals court said in a precedent-setting opinion that
the board and similar administrative agencies, unlike courts, ``have
no `inherent' powers.''
   ``The Board of Claims is entirely a creature of the legislature.
... There is no explicit grant of authority (in Kentucky law) giving
the board the power to take on an adversarial role and dismiss
claims'' on its own motion, the court said in a 2-1 ruling.
   The board was created by the General Assembly to handle damage
claims against state agencies, which under the Kentucky Constitution
cannot be sued for negligence.
   The fire on May 28, 1977, led to years of litigation against
dozens of companies that manufactured materials used in the
construction or furnishing of the club at Southgate, just across the
Ohio River from Cincinnati, Ohio.
   In July 1985, General Electric Co. became the last of 14
defendants in a federal civil suit against aluminum wiring
manufacturers to reach settlements totaling $14 million. Settlements
by other defendants had totaled $30 million by 1984.
   The appeals court upheld Campbell Circuit Court, which earlier
had consolidated the claims by the estates of seven people into a
single case and ordered it back to the board for hearing. The board
appealed that ruling.
   Failure to give the claimants notice of dismissal or to allow
them to respond with legal arguments was a violation of the
constitutional guarantee of due legal process, the appellate panel
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
