<HEAD>Gadhafi Calls For Libyan-Tunisian Unity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi said
Friday he favors closer ties with Tunisia in a five-nation Arab
alliance known as the Maghreb.
   ``Our unity should not necessarily be subjected to uniformity of
political systems,'' said Gadhafi, who began a three-day visit
Thursday.
   ``It is a matter of a constitutional unity in the Maghreb
framework, within which we see a bilateral integration,'' he said in
a speech to the Tunisian Parliament.
   Other countries making up the Maghreb are Algeria, Morocco and
Mauritania.
   Thursday night, Tunisian President Zine el Abidine Ben Ali told
Gadhafi the two countries must ``reconcile the possible and the
desirable'' to strengthen the alliance ``as a prelude to global Arab
unity.''
   Tunisia and Libya re-established diplomatic relations a year ago
after a two-year break, caused by Gadhafi's decision to deport
32,000 Tunisian workers.
