<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--China-Cancer     12-09 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Cancer,0172</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pollution Gives Shanghai Highest Cancer Rate In Nation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air and water pollution has given Shanghai the
highest death rate from cancer in China, a researcher said Friday.
   The annual cancer mortality rate in Shanghai is more than 2 per
thousand males and 1.4 per thousand females, comparable London and
Los Angeles, said Gao Yutang of the Shanghai Tumor Research
Institute.
   The official People's Daily, which on Friday published the
findings of the Tumor Research Institute, said the death rate from
cancer in Shanghai rose more than 230 percent in the past 25 years.
   It blamed pollution for 80 percent of the deaths in the east
coast industrial city and cited a lack of zoning restrictions,
permitting construction of air-polluting factories in residential
areas.
   Gao said heavy smoking is also to blame. About 300 million of
China's 1.08 billion people smoke.
   The government says cancer is the leading cause of death among
urban males and the No. 3 cause among urban women.
</TEXT>
