<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CocaineBust     12-09 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cocaine Bust,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>23 Indicted In $100 Million Cocaine Ring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two brothers led a gang that sold $100
million in cocaine a year and used violence to control the streets
and drive off competing dealers, prosecutors said.
   Robert ``Dread'' Smith, 32, a Jamaican-born alien, was among 23
people named in a 72-count federal indictment unsealed Thursday. If
convicted, he faces a maximum penalty of life imprisonment and a
$108 million fine.
   Smith has been in custody since August on charges that he killed
one man and wounded another in a 1986 street shooting. His trial on
those charges is set for January.
   Smith, his brother, Everton, 29, and other members of the gang
routinely used violence to maintain control over those who sold the
drugs, including crack, and to keep them from reporting their
activities to police, said U.S. Attorney Michael Baylson.
   The defendants, 16 of whom were in custody this morning, were
charged with violating federal drug, racketeering and firearms laws.
   Edward Leary, in charge of the FBI office here, said the acts the
defendants allegedly committed ``are tantamount to those of an urban
terrorist group which has violently sought to satisfy its own greed
by preying upon those addicted to illegal narcotics.''
   ``They had little or no regard for anyone who stood in their
way,'' Leary said. ``They have oppressed children into doing their
bidding and have threatened the fabric of life in this community.''
   Smith's gang allegedly handled an annual average of 2,000 pounds
of cocaine, plus an unknown quantity of marijuana, said Samuel
Billbrough, who heads the Philadelphia office of the federal Drug
Enforcement Administration. A pound of cocaine sells for about
$11,000 wholesale, and the retail price is roughly five times that,
making the gross sales more than $100 million yearly, Billbrough
said.
   All the defendants are charged with conspiracy to manufacture
cocaine base, commonly called crack, and to distribute cocaine,
crack and marijuana.
   The Smiths and two others also are charged with engaging in a
continuing criminal enterprise in violation of the federal ``drug
kingpin'' law, which carries a maximum life sentence.
</TEXT>
