<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Quake Aid, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0566,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Collecting Medications for Quake Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Quake</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 5th graf pvs, Blood packs, with White
House comment.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Red Cross today collected money,
antibiotics and supplies to help victims of the Armenian earthquake
as the Soviet Embassy said it has been overwhelmed with donations
and had set up a bank account for those wishing to help.
   Red Cross spokeswoman Terry Gautier said her organization is
making arrangements with major pharmaceutical firms to supply
antibiotics for shipment to the scene of the disaster.
   In addition, the Red Cross is collecting money to be used in
aiding the quake victims, with Armenian church and ethnic groups in
this country being particularly helpful, she said.
   U.S. officials are also collecting ``blood packs'' for shipment
to the Soviet Union, she said.
   Blood packs are the materials used to collect blood from donors
and separate it into various components, she explained. While the
Soviet Union has sufficient volunteers donating blood, it needs the
equipment to collect it for use in the quake-damaged area.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the U.S.
government stood ready to do whatever it can to help facilitate the
delivery of assistance and materials collected through private means.
   The American Red Cross has activated a toll-free number for
people to call to offer assistance. The number is 1-800-453-9000.
Americans can also make donations to local Red Cross chapters,
marked for the Soviet Armenian Earthquake Relief, or through various
Armenian groups.
   At the Soviet Embassy, meanwhile, spokesman Igor Bulay said:
   ``The phones are ringing constantly. ... There is a stream of
donations. People are walking up to the doors of the embassy with
checks and money orders. Checks are beginning to come in the mail.''
   Bulay said the embassy has opened an account at the Dupont Circle
Branch of the Riggs National Bank, 1913 Massachusetts Ave. NW,
Washington, D.C., 20036.
   The name of the account is ``Relief'' and the account number is
04-08-572-564. Bulay said that as money is received it will be sent
immediately to Armenia and used in the relief efforts.
</TEXT>
