<1ST_LINE>u i PM-WalesaTrip 2ndLd-Writethru a0550 12-09 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Walesa Trip, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0550,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PRECEDE Warsaw</HEAD>
<HEAD>Walesa Makes First Foreign Trip Since Solidarity Banned</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Walesa arriving in Paris,
details. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``But he ...'' CHANGES byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHE CACHERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solididarity leader Lech Walesa today made his first
foreign trip since Poland's martial-law crackdown seven years ago
and told reporters it was time to leave the Stalinist system behind.
   ``After seven years, here I am at the dawn of something new,''
said a smiling Walesa after his arrival at Charles de Gaulle airport.
   Walesa, who was permitted to accept the invitation of President
Francois Mitterrand to join observances of the 40th anniversary of
the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, said he was looking
forward to meeting Soviet physicist Andrei Sakharov, another Nobel
Peace Prize laureate invited by Mitterrand to Saturday's ceremonies.
   ``We both still feel, he and I, the breath of Stalin at our
backs,'' Walesa said, speaking Polish through an interpreter. ``The
Stalin era is over. Now I am waiting for the return to pluralism and
the restoration of rights.''
   Before leaving Warsaw, Walesa told reporters, ``There are several
elements which cause hope that everything's going to be better.''
   But he said problems remained, such the government's monopoly on
trade unions and its handling of social, political and economic
problems.
   ``That is still the breath of Stalin. It was not communism, it
was him. And we have to end it ... by way of evolution and not
revolution.''
   ``I'd like to reach an agreement at last on pluralism and to
finish the Stalinist system for good,'' he said.
   Walesa also was to confer with French trade unionists, the mayor
of Paris and Cardinal Jean-Marie Lustiger, leader of the French
Roman Catholic Church, before returning Monday.
   Walesa, bundled in a thick coat and sporting a front-billed fur
cap, received cheers of ``Bravo Lech!'' when he arrived at Warsaw's
central train station from Gdansk earlier in the day.
   Crowds also gathered around him and historian Bronislaw Geremek
at the airport, with parents holding up children for a better view.
   Geremek, a senior Solidarity adviser, was accompanying Walesa on
the trip.
   In a departure from past practice, the state-controlled media
treated Walesa as a public figure instead of as a private citizen.
   His departure for Paris was listed by the official PAP news
agency as one of its top stories of the day.
   It was the first time since the imposition of martial law in
Poland in December 1981 that Walesa received permission to travel
abroad.
   The issuance of a passport to him Monday coincided with
increasingly positive treatment of Walesa in the official press
since he appeared in a nationwide television debate Nov. 30.
   Walesa was viewed by supporters as having handily won the debate
with official unions' chief Alfred Miodowicz, and the
non-confrontational tone of his remarks drew praise even from
normally hostile government officials.
   The Solidarity leader last left Poland in October 1981, also to
visit France.
   Walesa has led Solidarity since the inception of the first
independent trade union in the Soviet bloc in August 1980.
   Walesa had insisted Geremek, a French medieval scholar who speaks
French fluently, accompany him. Also making the trip with Walesa was
Andrzej Wielowieyski, vice president of the Warsaw Club of Catholic
Intelligentsia.
</TEXT>
