<DOCNO> AP881209-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1334EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Trek     12-09 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Trek,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Right-Wing Groups Celebrate 150th Anniversary of Pioneer Trek</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On horseback and ox-drawn wagons,
Afrikaners paraded into the city Friday to celebrate the 150th
anniversary of the white pioneers' trek into the country's heartland.
   The march, held seven days before the official anniversary, was
organized by right-wing white groups. They object to the upcoming
government-backed ceremony, which has been billed as open to all
races.
   Nearly 1,000 whites, dressed in 19th century pioneer outfits,
arrived in downtown Pretoria to mark the Great Trek, the 1838
journey by Afrikaners away from the British-ruled Cape Colony into
the country's uncharted interior.
   Altogether about 3,000 people attended the parade, with wagons
arriving from several locations across the country.
   The Great Trek is the most momentous event in Afrikaner history.
Stories about hardships on the journey and battles with African
tribesmen have taken on mythical proportions for the Dutch-descended
Afrikaners, who dominate the government.
   ``Today we remember how our ancestors built this country into a
civilized area where it's safe for whites to live,'' said Dann
Combrink, 62.
   Combrink, wearing a leather vest and wide-brimmed hat, was
accompanied by his wife in a period costume that included a bonnet
and a full-length lavender and white dress with lace trim.
   ``This a day Afrikaners should be together,'' said Combrink.
   Organizers said blacks were not welcome at Friday's ceremony or
at an evening gathering at the Voortrekker Monument, a huge granite
structure on a hill overlooking the capital.
   ``The Great Trek marked the coming of our oppression, the
stripping of our rights,'' said a 45-year-old black man who asked to
be identified only as George. ``When I see this, I am very angry,
very bitter.''
   The 100th anniversary commemoration, held in 1938, is regarded as
the catalyst that united the Afrikaners and gave impetus to their
political organizations. Ten years later, the Afrikaner-dominated
National Party came to power and began codifying their apartheid
policies of racial segregation.
   But the two separate trek celebrations illustrate the fracture
between right-wing Afrikaners, who oppose all concessions to the
country's black majority, and President's P.W. Botha's National
Party, which calls for gradual race reforms and limited
power-sharing.
   Friday's ceremony was organized by the Afrikaner Peoples' Guard,
a right-wing cultural group. The contingent that received the
loudest applause was from the neo-Nazi Afrikaner Resistance
Movement, led by the charismatic Eugene TerreBlanche.
   Most members of TerreBlanche's group opted not for the 19th
century attire of their ancestors, but wore khaki outfits with
swastika-like emblems on the shoulders.
   TerreBlanche and his followers received sustained cheers as they
rode around Church Square in the city center, in front of the
courthouse where five black anti-apartheid leaders were sentenced to
prison Thursday on treason and terrorism convictions following a
controversial trial.
   The government-sponsored trek left Cape Town on Aug. 27 for the
870-mile trip to Pretoria. Despite the government's announced
intention of opening the celebrations to all races, few non-whites
have participated.
   The government functions will dominate the next week leading up
to the Day of the Vow, a national holiday, on Dec. 16.
   On that day in 1838, the Afrikaners vowed to make the date
forever holy if they defeated a hostile Zulu tribe. They did so in
the Battle of Blood River, and the day remains the most revered in
Afrikaner history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
