<HEAD>Sikh High Priest Killed by Militants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Suspected Sikh militants ambushed a car
carrying one of the five high priests of their religion and shot him
to death Friday in Punjab state, a news agency reported.
   Balbir Singh was killed in the district of Ropar, north of the
state capital, Chandigarh, the United News of India reported. His
driver and bodyguard were injured, UNI said.
   The five priests had earlier this week readmitted former Punjab
chief minister Surjit Singh Barnala into the Sikh community after
expelling him last year for sending police into the Golden Temple.
   The temple is the holiest Sikh shrine and the priests had said at
the time that Barnala had commited sacrilege.
   Newspapers said Barnala's re-entry into the community was opposed
by Sikh militants.
   Sikh militants have been fighting for an independent homeland in
Punjab since 1982. They have been blamed for at least 2,350 killings
in the state this year.
   Many of the victims have been Sikh moderates opposed to the
separatist campaign. The militants have labeled the moderates as
traitors.
