<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Children'sCrusade     12-09 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Children's Crusade,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Urged To Make Children's Issues Top Priority</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As president, George Bush should declare
children his top priority and commit the country to investing
whatever it takes to ease problems ranging from poverty to abuse, a
children's advocacy group said Friday.
   David Liederman, executive director of the Child Welfare League
of America, said his group is seeking a commitment similar to
President Kennedy's pledge to put a man on the moon. Money for the
space program began flowing immediately, he said.
   ``We understand that there's a (budget) deficit,'' Liederman
said, ``but in the history of the United States, any important
initiative that a president called for, we somehow found the money.''
   The league, a network of more than 500 public and private social
service agencies, is urging Bush to keep campaign promises to expand
Head Start; institute child care tax credits; expand medical
coverage of the poor; and raise spending for homeless aid, school
lunches, immunization programs and nutrition supplements for
pregnant women and infants.
   Liederman said his group also is seeking enactment of at least
some portions of last year's unsuccessful Act for Better Child Care
in order to bolster the supply of day care. ``If you don't have
enough day care, a child care tax credit doesn't work,'' he said.
   The league also is urging Bush to support, and Congress to pass,
comprehensive programs for pregnant adolescents, children and youth
with AIDS, families with no health insurance and unemployed youth,
as well as a higher minimum wage, mandated family leave in the
private sector and expanded supplies of affordable housing.
   Liederman said a good start toward the league's goals might
involve $5 billion in new spending in 1989. ``We are totally
realistic. We're saying let's start,'' he said.
   Asked where that money would come from, Liederman replied, ``The
same place the money comes from for the stealth bomber, for the B-1
bomber, for the Export-Import Bank ... the same place the money
comes from to fund everything that we think is important.''
   Liederman said the league has delivered to Bush a copy of its
plan, called ``The First 100 Days: A Children's Initiative,'' and
has requested a meeting with him.
   ``We like his promises,'' he said. ``We're optimistic. We're
taking President-elect Bush at his word.''
</TEXT>
