<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Rights     12-09 0522</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Rights,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Expresses Support For Human Rights But Questions Remain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China on Friday honored the 40th anniversary of
the United Nations Declaration of Human Rights, although questions
remain about this nation's commitment to such concepts.
   Fei Xiaotong, a well-known sociologist, was quoted by the
official Xinhua News Agency as saying that China actively supports
the development of human rights.
   Fei, speaking at a forum to commemorate the U.N. declaration,
said China's constitution guarantees individual rights, including
freedom of religion and equality before the law.
   He noted, however, that the struggle for human rights should
concentrate not on individual freedoms but on fighting colonialism,
racism and foreign invasion.
   The report was the latest in a series of articles in the official
press stressing China's position that collective rights are more
important than individual liberties.
   A Xinhua report this week said China believes that civil
liberties, rights of minorities and women belong to the ``internal
affairs'' of a country and advised other countries not to meddle in
those questions.
   An article in the Nov. 28 issue of Beijing Review, an official
weekly, soft-pedaled discussion of individual liberties. Human
rights, it said, were a key part in the efforts of Third World
countries to ``establish a new economic order.''
   By pushing such a policy, China can justify both its criticism of
apartheid in South Africa and its rejection of accusations about its
policies in Tibet or its one-party state.
   ``It is no good to force one country's standards on another,''
Friday's Xinhua report said. ``Interference in a country's internal
affairs on the pretext of human rights should be strictly
forbidden.''
   Western human rights groups have persisted in criticizing China's
record.
   In February, the Washington-based group Asia Watch said Chinese
authorities tortured Tibetan activists seeking independence from
China and performed forced abortions on members of minority groups.
   Pro-independence Tibetans have rioted twice in the past two
years, leaving dozens dead in Lhasa, the region's capital.
   The Asia Watch report quoted one Tibetan as saying, ``if one
speaks forcefully, if one gives an account of Tibet as being
independent, they apply cattle prods.''
   Earlier this year, the U.S. Congress also criticized China for
its actions in Tibet.
   An Amnesty International report in April accused China of denying
prisoners access to lawyers or their families. In earlier years, the
London-based group has called for the release of Wei Jingsheng,
China's most prominent dissident, who as a leading member of the
``Democracy Movement'' was jailed in 1979.
   Last week, one of Wei's former associates, Ren Wanding, who spent
four years in jail for his views, renewed his call for free
elections in China.
   Ren, who was freed in 1983, also appealed to the United Nations
to intercede on behalf of his fellow dissidents, like Wei, still
imprisoned.
   The U.N. Declaration on Human Rights was passed in 1948 and
guarantees political, economic and cultural rights as well as the
right of self-determination, sovereignty and territorial
independence.
   China signed the declaration in 1971 when it joined the United
Nations. This year marked the first time China has honored the
document.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
