<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Bush-Judges     12-09 0835</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Judges,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brennan Illness Sparks Speculation Over Bush Appointees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An aging liberal bloc on the Supreme Court,
anchored by ailing Justice William J. Brennan, is prompting renewed
speculation on the impact President-elect Bush will have on the
court's future.
   Brennan, hospitalized Thursday with pneumonia, was reported
Friday to be improving at the Bethesda Naval Medical Center. Court
spokeswoman Toni House said he may miss little time on the bench
since the high court begins a four-week recess Monday.
   Brennan, 82, is the court's oldest justice and senior member in
terms of service.
   He is two years older than the court's two other most consistent
liberals, Justices Thurgood Marshall and Harry A. Blackmun, both 80.
   Aside from Brennan's current bout with pneumonia, the three have
appeared to be in good health and have given no signs they plan to
step down anytime soon.
   Including Justice John Paul Stevens, 68, the average age of the
court's liberal bloc is over 77.
   By contrast, the average age of the five more conservative
members is slightly under 60.
   That group includes three appointees of President Reagan: Sandra
Day O'Connor, 58, named in 1981 as the first woman on the high
court; and Antonin Scalia, 52, and Anthony M. Kennedy, 52, both
named during Reagan's second term.
   In addition, Reagan elevated William H. Rehnquist, 64, to chief
justice to succeed Warren E. Burger.
   The ninth justice, Byron R. White, 71, an appointee of President
Kennedy, votes more often with the conservatives on key issues.
   While Brennan's illness lends new drama to conjecture about the
high court's future, Bush may have a more immediate impact on the
lower federal courts.
   Bush is expected to search out conservatives to fill the existing
41 federal court vacancies _ 32 trial judgeships and nine appeals
court posts. There could be many more for the president to fill over
the next four years.
   Observers doubt that Bush will be as devoted to conservative
ideology as Reagan, who made 375 judicial appointments, filling more
than half the total.
   Guessing Bush's likely Supreme Court appointees is a parlor game
with conflicting clues.
   The president-elect has said he likes ``moderate people with
conservative views.''
   He also pledged during the campaign to pick judges ``who will
interpret the Constitution, not legislate from the bench.''
   ``I will appoint judges who don't reserve all their sympathy for
criminals, who understand that victims have rights, too,'' Bush said.
   As further evidence of Bush's conservative leanings, he supported
Reagan's unsuccessful attempt to place Robert H. Bork on the high
court.
   Bork, opposed for his conservative ideology, was defeated last
year in a bruising political battle in the Democratic-controlled
Senate.
   Associates of Bush are quick to point out that the
president-elect was a close friend of the late Potter Stewart, a
moderate justice with much the same upper-class lineage.
   Asked if Bush was likely to pick someone closer to Stewart than
Bork if there is a Supreme Court vacancy, Bush spokeswoman Sheila
Tate declined to speculate.
   ``That's a pothole over which I will leap,'' she said.
   A Republican strategist who requested anonymity predicted Bush
``will not choose anyone who is anathema to the movement
conservatives'' _ the Republican ideologues who rallied around Bork.
   That strategy may rule out Attorney General Dick Thornburgh, the
former governor of Pennsylvania whose conservative credentials have
been questioned.
   Thornburgh himself said in a recent interview with The Associated
Press that ``judicial restraint'' is a qualification for the bench.
He said he favors picking the best person available.
   Bush also has said he will not impose a litmus test on judicial
appointees. Anti-abortions would like assurances that the next
justice, if given the chance, will vote to overturn the high court's
landmark Roe vs. Wade decision of 1973 that legalized abortion
nationwide.
   Legal experts offer a cross-section of names, including some
moderates, when asked to speculate on likely Bush choices for the
high court.
   The largest group consists of federal judges and includes the
following Reagan appointees to the bench:
   _Patrick E. Higgonbotham, 49, an appeals court judge in Texas
praised for his intelligence. He could face conservative opposition
because of a 1986 ruling that threw out anti-abortion laws.
   _Ralph K. Winter Jr., 52, an appeals court judge in Connecticut.
   _J. Harvie Wilkinson III, 44, an appeals court judge in Virginia.
   _Kenneth W. Starr, 42, a judge on the prestigious and important
federal appeals court in Washington, D.C., and another in the
prominent coterie of youthful conservatives picked by Reagan.
   _Pamela A. Rymer, 47, a federal judge in Los Angeles since 1983.
   Possibilities from outside the judiciary include:
   _James A. Baker, 58, Bush's close friend and choice to be
secretary of state. But GOP insiders doubt Baker is interested in
becoming a justice.
   _Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, 54, one of the nation's most
conservative lawmakers who led the defense of Bork during the Senate
confirmation battle.
   _Carla A. Hills, 54, named by Bush to be U.S. trade
representative.
</TEXT>
