<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Brennan     12-09 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brennan,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Juastice Reported Responding Well to Treatment for Pneumonia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supreme Court Justice William J. Brennan
reportedly responded well to medical treatment Friday, a day after
he was hospitalized with pneumonia.
   Kathy Arberg, a Supreme Court spokeswoman, quoted doctors as
saying that Brennan, 82, was ``continuing to improve and resting
comfortably.''
   His pneumonia was being treated with antibiotics, she said.
   Ms. Arberg said Brennan might return to work early into a
four-week recess the court will begin Monday after issuing orders
and possibly announcing decisions.
   Brennan, the court's oldest and most senior member, was taken by
ambulance to the Bethesda Naval Medical Center in suburban Maryland
on Thursday after visiting a doctor at the U.S. Capitol.
   The justice left his office because he was suffering from a fever
and chills.
   A source close to Brennan who spoke on condition of anonymity
said the justice felt well enough Friday to ask that some of his
court work be delivered to his hospital room.
   Brennan participated in the court's oral arguments Wednesday, and
reportedly has enjoyed good health recently.
   His last hospitalization occurred in August 1987 when he checked
into the Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., for tests on a troublesome
prostate gland. The tests revealed he did not have cancer.
   In 1979 Brennan had a stroke that left his right hand partially
paralyzed, and a year earlier he was treated for a cancerous growth
on a vocal cord.
   Brennan was appointed to the nation's highest court by President
Eisenhower in 1956.
</TEXT>
