<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CarolingHalted     12-09 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Caroling Halted,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Halts Teaching Of Religious Carols After Complaint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elementary school music teacher
has agreed to stop teaching religious Christmas carols because a
Jewish parent complained it violated her child's constitutional
rights, officials said.
   Sandy Miller will not teach carols such as ``Silent Night'' or
``God Rest Ye Merry Gentlemen'' for the rest of the holiday season,
officials of Colorado Springs School District 11 said Thursday.
   School district officials said they will try to determine whether
carols are appropriate for district classrooms, spokesman Paul Kemp
said.
   ``We're asking our attorneys to research it legally, and we'll
take a look at our curriculum adoption policy in the area of music
and see if we are meeting the needs of all children,'' Kemp said.
   Miller and the parent who complained about the carols, Sari
Escovitz, declined to comment.
   The constitutionality of singing religious Christmas carols in
school involves the same First Amendment concerns that have led the
U.S. Supreme Court to bar officially sanctioned school prayers, said
Richard Collins, a professor and specialist in constitutional law at
the University of Colorado at Boulder.
   ``The question is, is this school's involvement in the Christmas
season extensive enough to constitute religious observance?''
Collins said. ``It depends on the coerciveness of the school and the
depth and seriousness of the observance.''
</TEXT>
