<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Pageant     12-09 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Pageant,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White Beauty Pageant Winner Quits Over Racism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white beauty pageant winner
renounced her title because of hostility from blacks, it was
reported Friday.
   Lisiane Braile, 19, told reporters she was booed and physically
threatened after being elected Carnival Princess in Porto Alegre, a
southern city of 1.1 million residents about 950 miles southwest of
Rio.
   ``I renounced for my physical safety, because I was threatened in
anonymous phone calls that I would suffer in the flesh for winning
the title,'' she said in an interview with the Rio newspaper Jornal
do Brasil.
   Miss Braile competed against 28 black and mixed-race women for
the honorary title of Carnival Princess in February's pre-Lenten
festival. Blacks traditionally dominate the annual festivities.
   During the beauty competition, ``several black people asked,
`What's that white girl doing here?''' Miss Braile said. When she
won, the largely black audience booed and insulted her, she said.
   A majority of Brazil's 144 million people are black or
mixed-race, and racism is a crime under the Brazilian constitution.
Although the government tries to promote an image of harmonious race
relations, discrimination _ mostly against blacks _ is still
widespread.
</TEXT>
