<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mongolia-Soviet     12-09 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mongolia-Soviet,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mongolian Official Welcomes Soviet Troop Reduction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ULAN BATOR, Mongolia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Mongolian official on Friday
welcomed Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev's pledge to reduce
Soviet troop strength in this Central Asian country and said the
process already has begun.
   First Deputy Foreign Minister Daramyn Endon said all the Soviet
troops could be pulled out if relations with China continue to
improve.
   ``We don't think there is a need for foreign troops,'' Endon told
a news conference.
   He said Mongolia and its close ally, the Soviet Union, had
decided to cut a large portion of the Soviet garrison in Mongolia in
order to strengthen mutual understanding and trust with other Asian
countries, especially China.
   Gorbachev told the United Nations on Wednesday he planned to
reduce the Soviet army by nearly 10 percent and unilaterally reduce
the Soviet troop presence in East Europe and Mongolia.
   Endon refused to say how many Soviet troops will be withdrawn or
by when. He said military experts have yet to make those decisions.
   ``I can only say that a large part of the Soviet troops will be
withdrawn,'' he said. ``The process has already begun and will
continue until the end.''
   The presence of about 1 million Soviet troops along China's
border, including those inside Mongolia, has been one of the major
obstacles to ending the nearly 30-year-old Chinese-Soviet rift.
   Last year the Soviet Union withdrew one division containing about
12,000 troops from Mongolia, leaving about 50,000 by Western
estimates. They are believed to be confronted by an equal number of
Chinese soldiers on the opposite side of the 2,900-mile-long
Chinese-Mongolian border.
   Endon praised recent improvements in Chinese-Mongolian relations
that have accompanied the warming trend between Beijing and Moscow.
He said there has been much progress toward normalization of
government and party relations. The two countries signed trade and
consular agreements in 1986.
   He said Mongolia's foreign minister will visit China next year
for the first time since the Chinese-Soviet split.
   Endon noted that during the 1950s, when Mongolia and China were
on good terms, Mongolia did not station any troops along its border
with China. He said Mongolia ideally would be able to cut its own
military forces if relations with China continue to improve.
   ``Instead of sending our young men to the army we could use them
in the building of socialism,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
