<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Coupole     12-09 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coupole,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Famed Montparnasse Restaurant Restored to 1920s Splendor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYN AUGUST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   La Coupole, the landmark Left Bank restaurant where
struggling young artists like Chagall and Picasso traded their
paintings for hot meals, reopened Friday after eight months of
renovations restoring its 1920s decor.
   ``La Coupole is more than a restaurant; it's an institution,''
said Jean-Paul Bucher, La Coupole's new owner.
   Bucher, president of the Groupe Flo chain of brasseries known for
good food, fair prices and quick service, said the Coupole
``machine'' still had to be oiled and would get off to a slow start
so as not to disappoint regular customers.
   The menu still features house specialities like lamb curry, steak
tartar and baked Alaska, and there are welcome additions from Flo's
nouvelle cuisine fare. Prices have been held down, Bucher said, and
the lamb curry, served with three tasty chutneys, can be had for $15.
   La Coupole has been a watering hole for artists and
intellectuals, movie stars and politicians since it opened 61 years
ago with Jean Cocteau, Man Ray, Andre Derain and Louis Aragon on
hand for the champagne.
   A decade later, Ernest Hemingway and Willian Faulkner nursed
double scotches there while Henry Miller and Lawrence Durrell played
chess long into the night.
   The post-World War II generation of existentialists made La
Couple their haunt. Until his death in 1980, Jean-Paul Sartre
lunched there daily with Simone De Beauvoir.
   The Coupole's main dining room is a classified historical
monument and renovations of its vintage 1920s decor cost an
estimated $5 million.
   On hand for the inaugural lunch of foie gras, scallops, chicken
fricasee and an orange mousse cake washed down with vintage Medoc
wines was Rene Lafon, 91, the Coupole's original owner.
   ``Entering the restaurant I was very happy to find my Coupole,''
he said.
   The famed 32 pillars, wrapped with original, but mostly unsigned
canvasses painted by artists from the School of Paris _ turned out
to be a Pandora's box.
   Under the cracking plaster, workmen found a type of emerald green
stone that looked like marble. Though it was once the rage of Paris
and still adorns the facade of some of the city's loveliest
buildings, repairs were no easy matter: this man-made stone is no
longer manufactured.
   The paintings themselves had been darkened beyond recognition by
60 years of smoke and cooking grime. They are now more resplendent
than ever, thanks to four well-positioned spotlights on each post.
   ``We can really see the enormous variety of styles and colors
adopted by painters of the School of Paris,'' Marie Lyse de
Castelbajac, head of the restoration team, told The Associated Press.
   She said very few of the paintings are signed, and are thus a
mystery that is unlikely ever to be solved.
   ``One painting has Picasso colors, but its forms are pure
Modigliani, so it's hard to say for sure whose it is,'' she said.
``I guess that will always be part of La Coupole's charm.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
