<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   12-09 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0744</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinians Say Revolt Will Go On</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JABALIYA, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Refugees in this camp where
the Palestinian uprising began a year ago were shut inside their
shacks under military curfew Friday, but they said jailings and
economic hardship wouldn't halt their rebellion.
   ``We are preparing for a long struggle. Palestinians have reached
a point of no return,'' said a medical official in Jabaliya, the
largest and most militant camp in the Gaza Strip.
   Jabaliya's narrow dirt alleys were deserted Friday except for a
few goats picking through garbage piles. The occasional roar of an
army jeep was the only sound breaking the silence. A few residents
peered from the windows of their cement and corrugated tin huts.
   On Dec. 9, 1987, the camp was the site of the first demonstration
in what came to be known as the ``intefadeh,'' or uprising. About
1,000 Palestinians shouting ``Death to the Israelis'' and chanting
Islamic slogans hurled stones at soldiers. Troops opened fire,
killing 17-year-old Hatem Abu Sisi.
   Since then, more than a dozen residents have been killed in
clashes and more than 1,000 treated for gunshot and beating
injuries. The camp's 60,000 refugees have been confined to their
homes for 116 days in the past year, and money is tight.
   Most young men are in jail. ``The next generation has taken their
place,'' said the medical official, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``The stone-throwers are now 13 and 14 years old.''
   Palestinians throughout the occupied territories seem to have
settled in for a long confrontation with Israel while trying at the
same time to maintain some normalcy.
   ``This has become our way of life,'' said a 24-year-old teacher
for handicapped children who would only give his first name, Emad.
   Scores of members of his extended family were gathered in the
lush backyard of his home in Gaza City's middle-class Rimal
district. In the past year, it has become a clan custom to meet
during strikes and curfews to help pass the time, Emad said.
   The uprising has touched even the youngest, Emad said. He pointed
to his nephew, Ahmed, a 2-year-old with curly blond hair who was
hiding shyly behind one of the adults. ``The first word he learned
was soldier, not mother or father,'' Emad said.
   Emad said he had planned to get married on Saturday, but had to
postpone the wedding because of Friday's indefinite curfew which
confined the Gaza Strip's 650,000 residents to their homes.
   At Ahli Arab Hospital, a five-minute drive away, doctors had
settled into their ``strike day'' routine. During strikes called by
the PLO-backed underground leadership, the casualty toll usually
rises, in part due to increased army raids.
   ``In the beginning, we were completely overwhelmed by the number
of casualties,'' said a senior surgeon who refused to be further
identified. He said 4,200 patients had been admitted in the past
year, most with injuries sustained during the uprising.
   Now, all doctors are on duty on strike days. Elective surgery is
postponed and patients with light injuries are sent home to free
beds.
   On Friday, only few clashes were reported in Gaza, and by midday
doctors had only treated four beating victims.
   In the West Bank refugee camp of Balata, four Palestinians were
wounded after Moslem noon prayers, Arab hospital officials said.
   The relative calm was, in part, the result of the curfews and
heavy army presence. Dozens of jeeps patrolled Gaza City's streets,
and foot patrols combed Jabaliya and the nearby Shati camp.
   The low level of violence also indicated that Palestinians are
shifting their emphasis from street confrontations to
nation-building as the uprising enters its second year. The
Palestine National Council declared a Palestinian state during a
Nov. 15 session in Algiers.
   As part of the effort, local popular committees run by pro-PLO
activists organize anti-crime patrols, provide first aid, visit
families of those killed and settle disputes.
   Israel has outlawed the committees, but activists said the groups
continue to function, taking the place of the old leadership of clan
heads and and Israeli-appointed officials.
   ``We will have a state, but we don't expect it quickly,'' said
Sammy, 26, a top activist in the outlawed Shabiba youth movement of
PLO chief Yasser Arafat's Fatah group. ``In the meantime, it's
important to show we are a nation.''
</TEXT>
