<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0427 12-09 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0427,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hooks Says Bush Intends to Name Black to Cabinet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 5 grafs with Bush-Hooks meeting, picking up in
4th graf pvs, Joshua Smith</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The executive director of the NAACP said today
that President-elect Bush told him he intends to appoint a black to
his Cabinet.
   Hooks, a Democrat, spent about 30 minutes with Bush, discussing a
range of issues of concern to blacks, including judicial and Cabinet
appointments. Hooks called the session ``very cordial.''
   Asked if Bush had pledged to name a black to a high-level job,
Hooks said, ``I think I do remember him saying there would be a
black in the Cabinet.'' Hooks then said it was his ``distinct
recollection that he said he intends to do that.''
   Hooks said he suggested to Bush that the president-elect convene
a White House conference on race and poverty after the inauguration
next month.
   On Thursday, Bush met with 60 black Republicans who had
campaigned for his election.
   Joshua Smith, a businessman from Rockville, Md., said the group
expressed concern that a black has yet to be tapped for the Cabinet,
but said the meeting was friction-free.
   ``We have great hopes,'' he said. ``We have confidence he is
going to follow through on his promise.''
   Arthur Fletcher, a Washington businessman and official in the
Nixon and Ford administrations, said, ``There is reason to believe
there could be a black appointed to one'' of the domestic Cabinet
jobs still unfilled.
   Vacancies remaining include those at the departments of Health
and Human Services; Housing and Urban Development; Energy; Interior;
Veterans Affairs, and the newly created drug czar.
   Bush, according to Smith, told the black supporters ``that we
will over the term be pleased. He did not make any specific
commitments as to numbers and individuals.''
   Fletcher said one problem facing Bush is that there are so few
black Republicans qualified for administration jobs.
   ``They would have to look all over the place,'' said Fletcher,
who called the dearth of black Republicans ``a tragedy,'' and called
for stepped-up GOP recruitment of blacks.
   The blacks said they were pleased with the energetic session they
had with Lee Atwater, tapped to be the new Republican National
Committee chairman.
   Since the election, Bush has appointed nine people to
Cabinet-level posts and selected a handful of others for powerful
jobs.
   Among those selected are one woman, Carla Hills, named as the
U.S. trade representative, and one Hispanic, holdover Education
Secretary Lauro Cavazos.
   While blacks have been mentioned for leading jobs, they have not
been given any of them.
   Alan Keyes, a former State Department official who ran
unsuccessfully for the U.S. Senate in Maryland this year, was
thought to have a good chance of becoming U.N. ambassador. The
position was given instead to Thomas Pickering, a career diplomat
who has served as ambassador in El Salvador, Israel, Nigeria and
Jordan.
   Dr. Louis W. Sullivan, president of the Morehouse School of
Medicine in Atlanta, is under consideration for secretary of health
and human services.
   Sullivan said he has told Bush transition aides he was interested
in the No. 1 job at that department but not in the second job.
   Robert Woodson, a black businessman from North Carolina, is in
the running for secretary of housing and urban development. But the
leading prospect appears to be Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y.
   In other transition developments:
   _Rep. John Paul Hammerschmidt, D-Ark., is being pushed for the
job at the veterans department. Rep. Sonny Montgomery, D-Miss.,
chairman of the House Veterans Committee, and Rep. Gerald Solomon,
R-N.Y, wrote Bush in support of Hammerschmidt.
   _A group of Western senators is recommending four people for the
post of interior secretary. The prospects include Richard Richards,
a one-time RNC chairman; Rep. Barbara Vucanovich, R-Nev.; Warren
Morton, former speaker of the Wyoming House, and Rep. John Rhodes of
Arizona.
   _Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, said Bush may be making ``his first serious misstep'' by
prolonging speculation over whether former Sen. John Tower will be
appointed defense secretary. For weeks, there has been speculation
that Tower is the leading contender for the job.
   _Sen. Jake Garn, R-Utah, who flew on the space shuttle, says he
is not interested in running the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration. Among others reortedly in the running are Sally
Ride, the first American woman in space; William Graham, science
adviser to President Reagan, and Frank Borman, former president of
Eastern Airlines and an ex-astronaut.
</TEXT>
