<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ArabLeague     12-09 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arab League,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>League Wants U.N. Observer Membership For PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arab League said Friday it will campaign to
make the Palestine Liberation Organization an observer-member of the
United Nations, putting the organization on a level with Switzerland
and the Vatican.
   ``We are now going to try and get a resolution that would make
the Palestinian state an observer-member of the United Nations,''
Clovis Maksoud, the league's U.S. and U.N. representative, said at a
news conference.
   The session was called primarily to discuss next week's special
U.N. General Assembly meeting in Geneva at which PLO Chairman Yasser
Arafat will speak. Arafat was denied a U.S. visa on grounds he has
been involved in terrorism.
   The league, formed in 1945, comprises 21 Arab states and
``Palestine,'' which it says is represented by the PLO.
   The PLO is currently one of two groups with permanent observer
missions to the United Nations, the other being the South-West
Africa People's Organization. The current status recognizes their
claim to represent peoples.
   The new designation would rank the PLO among ``non-member
states,'' elevating the status of the Palestinian people in
Israeli-occupied territory.
   Maksoud said there would be no point in trying to make the PLO a
full member, because it could not win approval by the United States
in the Security Council. But, he added, ``Maybe this can be a
transition to full membership at a later date.''
   The non-member states are Monaco, North and South Korea, San
Marino, Switzerland and the Vatican.
   Discussing the Israeli raid Friday at Naameh, 50 miles inside
Lebanon, Maksoud called it a ``pre-emptive strike against the peace
option'' and timed to coincide with the first anniversary of the
start of uprisings in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``This is a signal of further oppression yet to come,'' Maksoud
said. ``This is unprovoked violence by Israel. There has been no
provocation. It is an attempt to destabilize Lebanon and to continue
its illegal occupation of the south of Lebanon.''
   Maksoud criticized President Reagan's comment at his news
conference Thursday night that Arafat's statement Wednesday saying
the PLO accepts Israel and rejects terrorism ``in all its forms''
was ambiguous.
   ``We consider that Mr. Arafat's statements have been clear,
unequivocal and categorical,'' he said. ``There isn't any
ambiguity.''
   Maksoud said that ``to include the uprising within the context of
terrorism, as the reaction of the United States seems to include, is
mind-boggling and unacceptable.''
</TEXT>
