<1ST_LINE>r w AM-USAToday-Miscarriages     12-09 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USA Today-Miscarriages,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USA Today Employees Concerned About Miscarriages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials and employees of USA Today are
concerned about an unusually high number of miscarriages among women
working in its newsroom.
   Some employees at the newspaper's suburban Washington
headquarters fear that a reported 14 miscarriages among 100 women
employees over the past 15 months may be partially attributed to
several months of construction work in the offices or to prolonged
exposure to video terminals.
   Editor Peter Prichard said Friday that the company is giving
``close attention'' to the matter.
   Senior Editor Wanda Lloyd, who confirmed only that there have
been ``some miscarriages,'' said: ``Certainly the company is
concerned about anything to do with employees. I'm concerned. I'm
very concerned.''
   But she also said: ``This is an internal matter and a very
personal matter for the women involved. We're still looking into it
and we don't really have any more to say.''
   The Washington Post on Friday reported that 14 miscarriages had
occurred among USA Today employees since September 1987.
   Scientists say about one in seven pregnancies ends in a
miscarriage and that there have been studies of about a dozen
cluster occurrences in the United States and Canada since 1980. A
common thread in the incidences was the use of video terminals in
the offices, although no direct link has been made between their use
and pregnancy problems.
   A USA Today reporter, who asked not to be identified, said the
company brought in experts on video terminals to discuss any danger
they might pose and has been taking an informal survey of employees
to determine the extent of the problem.
   Management also has sent out a memo telling employees not to talk
about the miscarriages, the employee said.
   ``The sheer magnitude of the construction work caused a lot of
concern,'' the reporter said. ``Guys with jackhammers were breaking
up walls right next to your head. You'd walk in to find your
terminal covered with dust. And there were weird smells, very
pungent odors.
   Allen J. Wilcox, an epidemiologist who has studied miscarraiges
for the National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences, said he
had no personal knowledge of the USA Today cases but they appear to
be significant enough to merit study.
   He said, however, it was possible the occurrences were only
coincidence and it is likely no cause will ever be proved. Extensive
epidemiological studies would be required to determine whether there
was any common cause, he said, since a number of factors could have
contributed to each case.
   The Post did not say how many staff members had been pregnant,
but one employee said there were no successful pregnancies among
women working on the two floors that have been undergoing
rennovation since April.
   Gannett Co. Inc., which owns the internationally distributed
newspaper, recently hired a consultant to test materials being
installed during renovation, the Post reported.
   ``There's a lot of concern in the building about the
construction, especially among women who have miscarried,'' said
Peter Johnson, a general assignment reporter interviewed by the
Post. He said the company appeared to be ``genuinely concerned''
about the problem.
   ``Everyone is real frightened,'' a women who had a miscarriage
and who asked not to be identified, was quoted by the Post as
saying. ``You don't know what's going on. It's really an ordeal.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
