<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1526EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OkeechobeePollution     12-09 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Okeechobee Pollution,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>District Endorses Plan To Save Okeechobee, Delays Details</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sweeping plan to stop the pollution of Lake
Okeechobee was endorsed by water directors Friday, but they delayed
adopting details of the regulatory program until February, pending
more hearings.
   The plan envisions strict limits on farm runoff into the lake,
limits that some farmers say could drive them out of business.
   The nine board members of the South Florida Water Management
District voted unamimously to approve a resolution supporting limits
on the overall pollution content of the 700-square-mile lake, the
nation's largest fresh-water lake outside of the Great Lakes system.
   The policy change comes in the wake of increasing phosphorus
pollution over the last two decades that has spawned deadly algae
blooms, wiping out fish and native plant species. One recent reading
found phosphorus levels at a historic high in the nation's largest
fresh-water lake outside of the Great Lakes system.
   Water from the lake flows into the Loxahatchee National Wildlife
Refuge, into Everglades National Park and to water-conservation
areas that recharge the Biscayne aquifer, southeastern Florida's
primary water supply.
   Michael Finley, superintendent of Everglades National Park, said
that the plan could prevent the lake from becoming little more than
a retaining pond for polluted water.
   ``But if it's finessed, delayed and circumvented, then it's going
to be the year 2002, and the nutrient front (phosphorus) will still
be a cancer moving south, and we will have lost more of Florida's
resources,'' Finley said.
   One factor prompting the toughened standards was a federal suit
filed by U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen accusing the district and the
state of failing to protect water quality in the interconnected
water system of the lake, Kissimmee River and Everglades National
Park.
   Lehtinen had said he might consider dropping the suit if the
district adopted the new standards, but spokeswoman Diane Cossin
said Friday that the office would wait until it could examine the
final plan.
   The biggest potential losers in the battle over phosphorus
pollution, which comes principally from fertilizer and cow manure,
are the sugar cane growers and dairy farmers who surround the lake.
   Philip Parsons, representative of the Florida Sugar Cane League,
said the new rules may drive cane growers in a few areas out of
business, although most would be able to survive the runoff limits.
   He complained about the direction of policy, however, saying its
aim seemed to be to force growers and dairy farmers to retain their
runoff on their property.
   ``If you say that to the city of Miami, the city of Miami
wouldn't exist. What are you going to do _ tear down the public
library and build a retaining pond?'' Parsons said.
   Environmentalists, who support the district plan, said the
situation cannot be compared with city sewage disposal.
   ``This is a scarce resource,'' said Joseph Podgor of Friends of
The Everglades. ``You cannot equate Lake Okeechobee to a trash
dump.''
   The district's pollution management plan would require all
lakeside farms to decrease the phosphorus content of their runoff at
least one-fifth by 1991, and they must meet interim goals before
then. Some dairy farms would have to cut phosphorus levels by more
than 80 percent.
   The district was required to submit a draft plan to the state by
December under the state's Surface Water Improvement and Management
Act.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
