<2ND_LINE>AM-Geraldo Cancellation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0647,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Geraldo' Show on Quayle Allegations Canceled</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf, `The show...' to CORRECT to R-N.Y., D-N.Y.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Geraldo Rivera show with former lobbyist Paula
Parkinson talking about a previously reported and denied alleged
incident with Vice President-elect Dan Quayle has been yanked by the
parent company.
   ``After a careful review, the Tribune Entertainment Co. has
determined that the `Geraldo' program titled `Washington
Confidential' will not be broadcast,'' the company said in a
statement Friday.
   ``Tribune is exercising this discretionary right as a matter of
programming judgment. Geraldo Rivera did not agree with this
decision but he understands it.''
   ``I am very angry,'' Rivera was quoted as saying in Friday's
editions of USA Today about the decision Thursday on the show taped
Nov. 3. ``It is censorship and it is appalling to me even when it is
my friends that are doing it.''
   The show featured Parkinson talking about what she had previously
said about Quayle in ``Washingtonian'' magazine, Rivera said. The
show also featured allegations of affairs by former President Nixon
and Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y.
   Rivera told the newspaper the decision had less to do with the
content than other recent shows, especially one ``Geraldo'' show
with Nazi youth in which Rivera's nose was broken and a special on
satanic cults that was panned.
   ``I think they're running scared because of all the Geraldo
bashing,'' Rivera said. ``I think they are reacting to the very
negative critical reaction to us.''
</TEXT>
