<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BicyclistKilled     12-09 0524</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bicyclist Killed,0537</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy Had Past Brush With Drugs, Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old boy who was struck by a car and
killed while riding his bicycle carrying two vials of cocaine lived
a tumultuous life that included a brush with death at age 4 and a
drug entanglement two months ago.
   ``He was a nice boy, full of humor. He was really active, busy,
but he really didn't do anything bad,'' said Barbara Butler, an
instructor at Bethany House Ministries, a church center in Francisco
Martinez's neighborhood.
   The last time Ms. Butler saw Francisco was Nov. 29, the day he
was struck by a car while pedaling his bicycle on a busy, four-lane
road in suburban Ross Township. He died of head injuries Monday at
Allegheny General Hospital in Pittsburgh.
   Francisco was only 4 when his mother, Larita Welch Martinez, then
25, dropped him to safety from the second story of a burning
tenement housing drug addicts and alcoholics in Boston.
   The Rev. Hurshel Langham of Boston, who caught Francisco that day
in January 1983, remembered Francisco as friendly and intelligent.
   ``The thing that amazed me was how he was able to survive in
there with all of the drunks and junkies. I was totally impressed
that he could live in that environment and be so well contented,''
said Langham.
   Ms. Martinez was convicted of arson for allegedly setting the
fire, which killed four people. She was sentenced to life in prison,
and Francisco was sent to live with his grandparents in Pittsburgh.
   Two months ago, police searched the home Francisco lived in with
his grandparents and an aunt and uncle after family members told
police Sept. 2 that the aunt, 20-year-old Renee Welch, was acting as
a drug courier and planned to get drugs in New York, according to
records in Allegheny County Court.
   Ms. Welch would not let officers search her bedroom. After police
left, Francisco went to his aunt's bedroom, but his uncle and
grandparents stopped him as he tried to leave and found 40 bags of
heroin and cocaine in his clothes.
   The aunt, who was charged with multiple drug offenses and
corrupting a minor, is free on bond awaiting trial.
   Meanwhile, Ross Township police Sgt. Frank Zotter said
investigators are looking for links between the vials Francisco was
carrying when he was struck and drug residue found in containers
taken from the aunt's bedroom.
   Tests also showed Francisco had alcohol in his blood when he was
struck. Family attorney Joseph K. Williams III said the boy was
asthmatic and had been taking cough syrup that contains alcohol.
   The boy had been seen riding his bike erratically on the same
highway in the days before he was struck, and police were responding
to a similar report when the fatal accident occurred, Zotter said.
   The teen-age driver was charged with leaving the scene of an
accident.
   The bike seemed to be one of the few constants in Francisco's
life.
   ``On a nice day he'd bring his bike down and park it and play out
back,'' said Sharon Brown, a worker at Bethany House Ministries.
``He loved his bike.''
</TEXT>
