<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1604EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Sununu Bjt   12-09 0907</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sununu, Bjt,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tower Weakened by Appointment Holdup Over Background, Lawmakers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Key lawmakers warned on Friday that the
drawn-out selection process is politically weakening John Tower,
George Bush's expected choice for defense secretary. But Bush's
incoming chief of staff said such delays are unavoidable.
   John Sununu refused to discuss what's behind the delay. However,
Tower's supporters and a transition source who declined to be named
said it was primarily an FBI check believed to be delving into the
former Texas senator's personal life and allegations made by his
ex-wife.
   ``If being thorough in the system creates a problem, then you
have to accept that,'' Sununu said in an interview. ``I can't
imagine anybody who is criticizing us who would suggest to us that
we find a shortcut through a system that ought to be allowed to
cover all the details as efficiently and as effectively as you can.''
   Tower, who was an arms negotiator for President Reagan after
retiring from the Senate, has long been considered the top candidate
for the Pentagon post.
   ``You always wish things could go faster,'' Sununu said. ``And
yet, in today's world, the worst thing you could do is to do things
quickly rather than thoroughly and that applies to all appointments,
not just the Tower one.''
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a backer of Tower and adviser to
President-elect Bush on defense, said, ``They (FBI) are checking
allegations and rumors _ womanizing, drinking involvement in defense
contracts.
   ``They seem to be surfacing all the time,'' McCain said in an
interview. ``All allegations have to be put to rest so there is no
embarrassment at a later date. From their viewpoint I wouldn't do
anything different. It's just sad that it's harming John Tower to
some degree.''
   McCain said Tower's former wife ``obviously has been feeding''
the rumors and ``provding grist for the mill.''
   A source close to Bush, commenting only on condition he not be
named, said, ``I think just that the FBI checks are taking a long
time. John Tower had a messy divorce. And his wife has suggested
17,000 different problems. ... And every single one of those has to
be checked out.''
   Bush said this week he was ``disinclined to believe'' allegations
about Tower.
   Sununu, who will step down soon as governor of New Hampshire,
said on other subjects in the interview:
   _He will not return to New Hampshire in two years to run for
office. ``I want to be chief of staff for eight years with this
president; I want to give him the best eight years a president has
ever had,'' he said. Sununu still has money left over from his
gubernatorial campaign, and said, ``Some day I might come back to
New Hampshire and run for office, governor or senator or whatever.''
   _Direct access to the Oval Office will be guaranteed to the chief
of staff, deputy chief of staff and the national security adviser.
As for Vice President-elect Dan Quayle, Sununu said, ``They (Bush
and Quayle) are going to work out their arrangement, and obviously
whatever the vice president (Bush) decides is the way to work will
be the way we work.''
   On Tower, Sen. McCain expressed concern about the delay, saying,
``The longer it takes, there's bound to be an impact on his stature.
I don't think it's significant now but it could be if it drags on
much longer _ more than a week or two. Then I think it starts
becoming serious.''
   Similarly, Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, said, ``I think anyone
who is allowed to hang out as the designated nominee without any
confirmation from the president-elect is bound to suffer a thousand
wounds.
   ``I think they should move quickly to resolve the position, and
if it's going to be Tower it should be in the very near future, and
if it's not going to be Tower they should say so.''
   Cohen said he, too, understood the nomination was being delayed
by background checks. Moreover, he said Bush's team has been
debating whether the Pentagon chief should be a managerial type or a
policy maker.
   ``I think they have come to the conclusion the secretary should
be the policy maker and that the deputy should be the manager,''
Cohen said.
   ``I have talked to Tower and I think he would like to have a
strong manager as a deputy,'' the senator added. ``He (Tower) is not
going to be dealing with the minutiae of procurement reforms.''
   As for Tower's personal life, Cohen said he has known Tower since
1978.
   ``I don't think John Tower professed to be a saint to anyone but
I don't think that's what we're looking for.'' He said he had never
``witnessed any excess in drinking or anything else'' by Tower.
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, said in a speech, ``If Tower is named defense secretary,
he will come into office in a weakened position. ... For one thing,
with all that twisting in the wind, questions will be raised about
how much confidence the president has in him.''
   McCain said he still expected Tower to get the job. Cohen said,
``Barring any unforeseen disclosures in the FBI investigation that
we have not already heard about, I would expect him to be the
nominee.''
   A top aide to Bush, speaking privately, said, ``I still think
it's a 75 percent bet.''
</TEXT>
