<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ForestRap     12-09 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forest Rap,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservation Group Revives Crocodile Rock, Or Music To Monkey By</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservation group Friday unveiled an attempt
to wrap the message of tropical forest conservation in a rap music
videotape.
   The six-minute videotape made by the U.S. affiliate of the World
Wildlife Fund should be seen by ``5 million to 7 million kids'' next
year in 50,000 schools, said Grace M. Lieberman, member of the fund
staff and co-author of the teacher's manual that accompanies the
tape and other materials.
   Interspersed with shots of exotic animals, birds, plants and
reptiles in the jungles of Peru and Brazil, a group of youngsters
about 10 years old dances through New York City streets and the
Botanic Garden on the Mall in Washington.
   The lyrics reveal the rocky metrics, pulsing beat and sustained
rhyme of typical rap numbers:
   ``The red-eyed frog has suction pads to cling _
   ``They climb vertically, I guess that's their thing.
   ``Howler monkeys, now they got the style,
   ``Their howls can be heard over half a mile
   ``And that's a caiman, waiting a while
   ``For its prey to come, it's related to the crocodile.''
   The teachers' kit was made in cooperation with the Smithsonian
Institution, whose Traveling Exhibition Service is sending a
tropical forest exhibit to 14 cities.
   The fund will give 1,000 copies of the tape and teaching
materials to host institutions in those cities. Others will be asked
to pay $20 per kit or $5 for the tape alone.
   Conservationists say 27 million acres of forest, an area bigger
than Austria, are lost around the world each year through logging
and conversion to farmland, threatening the existence of thousands
of exotic species not even studied yet by scientists, local
environmental damage and exacerbation of the greenhouse effect
warming of the earth.
   ``We surveyed teachers across the country and they told us in a
world of MTV we couldn't use film strips and slide shows'' and hold
students attention, said Ms. Lieberman.
   The idea for the tape came from the rap video idea advanced by
staffer Sally Russell, who produced the tape.
   A grant of $75,000 from Chevron Corp. supported the project.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Lyrics Copyright C 1988 by the World Wildlife
Fund.
</TEXT>
