<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Cannibalism     12-09 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cannibalism,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Captain in Cannibalism Case Will Be Court-Martialed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former captain of a U.S. warship
whose alleged failure to help a boatload of starving Vietnamese
refugees apparently forced them to resort to cannibalism will be
court-martialed, a Navy spokesman said Friday.
   Capt. Alexander G. Balian, 48, of Los Angeles, was relieved of
his duties in August after Vietnamese refugees claimed the USS
Dubuque did not assist them when it met up with their boat in the
South China Sea on June 9.
   United Nations officials said 52 of the refugees later reached
the Philippines but 58 died during the 37-day voyage. Survivors said
two Vietnamese died of starvation but three others were slain and
eaten by fellow passengers.
   U.S. Navy spokesman Lt. Cmdr. Kevin Mukri said Friday that the
commander of U.S. naval forces in the Philippines, Rear Adm. Roger
L. Rich, ordered the court-martial after reviewing findings of an
investigation conducted at the U.S. Subic Bay naval base and in the
Persian Gulf, the Dubuque's destination when it spotted the
Vietnamese boat.
   Mukri said no date had been set for the court-martial, but it
probably would be held at Subic Bay, 50 miles west of Manila.
   The investigation, which corresponds to a civilian grand jury
probe, was completed Oct. 28 and forwarded to Rich on Nov. 7, Mukri
said. It found that the Vietnamese vessel was out of food and water
and with an inoperative engine and sails when it encountered the
Dubuque.
   Balian claimed the boat was seaworthy and that the crew provided
food, water and navigational directions.
   Mukri said the investigation determined that the Dubuque failed
to provide food, water and clothing, even though some of the
refugees were naked, dehydrated, and weakened from their ordeal at
sea.
   He said Balian faced seven charges, including failure to render
assistance to a vessel in distress and failing to determine the
condition of the vessel. He said Balian, who is now in Sasabo,
Japan, could be dismissed from the Navy and imprisoned for two years
on each charge if convicted.
   Balian also was charged with failing to rescue a Vietnamese
refugee who jumped into the water and tried to swim to the port side
of the Dubuque, Mukri said. He said another Vietnamese tried to
climb a rope ladder on the side of the Dubuque, but the crew shook
it and he fell back into the sea.
   The Dubuque also did not report the location of the Vietnamese
vessel by radio so that other ships in the area could render
assistance, Mukri said.
   Quoting the report, Mukri said the Vietnamese vessel left Vietnam
on May 22. By the time it encountered the Dubuque on June 9, there
were 83 men, women and children, including one infant, still alive,
the report said.
   Filipino fishermen later rescued the refugees. They were taken to
the Philippine island of Palawan, where they were cared for by
Filipino and U.N. authorities.
   One of the refugees, 10-year-old Hung Quoc Tran, was reunited
late last month with an aunt and grandmother in El Dorado, Ark.,
about 120 miles south of Little Rock.
</TEXT>
