<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Rights     12-09 0682</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Rights,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sakharov, Walesa Arrive For Human Rights Celebration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet dissident Andrei Sakharov and Polish
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa, each making his first visit abroad
since winning the Nobel Peace Prize, arrived Friday to join a human
rights celebration.
   The two men, who were planning to meet for the first time during
the weekend, were invited by President Francois Mitterrand for
ceremonies marking Saturday's 40th anniversary of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights.
   Mitterrand, U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar and
UNESCO Director General Federico Mayor were scheduled to speak
Saturday at the Palais Chaillot overlooking the Seine that will be
attended by hundreds of dignitaries, human rights activists and
politicians.
   In Oslo, Perez de Cuellar on Friday accepted the 1988 Nobel Peace
Prize check on behalf of the U.N. peacekeeping forces.
   Sakharov, on his way back to Moscow following a four-week visit
to the United States, arrived Friday morning at Charles de Gaulle
Airport and was to be joined by his wife Yelena Bonner on Friday
night for the couple's first trip together outside the Soviet Union.
   Walesa, allowed to leave Poland for the first time since martial
law was declared in 1981, arrived Friday night at the same airport
and told reporters he was looking forward to meeting Sakharov.
   ``We both still feel, he and I, the breath of Stalin at our
backs,'' Walesa said, speaking Polish through an interpreter.
   ``After seven years, here I am at the dawn of something new,'' he
said. ``The Stalin era is over. Now I am waiting for the return to
pluralism and the restoration of rights.''
   At a 90-minute-long news conference at the Soviet Embassy,
Sakharov called for more steps to reduce the size of the Soviet
military. The 67-year-old physicist said one way to do this would be
to limit the length of service for Soviet draftees.
   Commenting on Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's offer
Wednesday at the United Nations to cut the Red Army by 500,000 and
withdraw thousands of tanks and troops from Eastern Europe, he said
it was a major decision but only a beginning.
   He said reductions in manpower and weapons ``can be done and will
change in a major way the international situation. Gorbachev is
going in this direction and this is very important. I would have
liked to see bigger cuts but what was done is important.''
   Sakharov, who helped develop the Soviet hydrogen bomb, previously
was barred from traveling abroad because of his past scientific
work. He was also restricted to the industrial city of Gorky for
seven years because of his outspoken opposition to Soviet
intervention in Afghanistan.
   In 1986, Gorbachev personally called him back to Moscow. Since
then, Sakharov has generally supported Gorbachev's perestroika, or
political and economic restructuring, while speaking out against
some trends, including the growing concentration of power in
Gorbachev's hands.
   He twice sidestepped questions about the political implications
of the meeting he is expected to have with Walesa, who is being
allowed by Polish authorities to make his first trip abroad since
the military crackdown on the independent union seven years ago.
   In an interview published Thursday in the daily Le Monde, Walesa
said he believed authorities granted him the visa because Poland
seeks better relations with the West ``and France can facilitate
this.''
   Walesa, who won the Nobel Prize in 1983, on Thursday told the
French daily Liberation that he was looking forward to meeting
Sakharov, the 1975 prize winner.
   Walesa will confer with French trade unionists, Paris Mayor
Jacques Chirac, actor Yves Montand, Culture Minister Jack Lang and
Cardinal Jean-Marie Lustiger, leader of the French Roman Catholic
Church. Walesa and Sakharov will meet Mitterrand and Premier Michel
Rocard on Saturday.
   The Universal Declaration of Human Rights, adopted without
dissent by the U.N. General Assembly on Dec. 10, 1948, is the basic
document under which member nations pledge to safeguard life and
liberty and abolish torture and slavery.
   The United Nations commemorated the annniversary Thursday by
honoring anti-apartheid activists Nelson and Winnie Mandela and four
other rights advocates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
