<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Gorbachev-East     12-09 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gorbachev-East,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East Europeans Pin Hopes On Gorbachev's Pledge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By INGOMAR SCHWELZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From Communist Party headquarters to street cafes,
East Europeans are giving an enthusiastic response to Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's pledge to withdraw some Soviet
troops from Eastern Europe.
   ``It's great, for us it's a real sign of hope for peace,'' said
one East Berlin teacher as she sat with a group of people around a
table in Egon-Erwin-Kisch Cafe on East Berlin's Unter den Linden
boulevard.
   ``The political significance of Gorbachev's words really cannot
be praised enough,'' said a student. Both asked that their names not
be used.
   In a speech to the United Nations Wednesday, Gorbachev announced
a unilateral reduction of 500,000 soldiers _ 50,000 of them in
Eastern Europe _ including the withdrawal and disbanding of six tank
divisions from Hungary, Czechoslovakia and East Germany by 1991.
   Soviet allies quickly hailed the speech and said the moves were
discussed with the Kremlin in advance.
   East Germany's Communist leader Erich Honecker, who has refused
to follow Gorbachev's economic and political reforms in his own
country, praised the Kremlin leader's pledge.
   East Germany ``welcomes and fully and completely supports the
far-reaching new initiatives and suggestions,'' Honecker said at a
state reception for Yugoslav President Raif Dizdarevic Wednesday.
   Western analysts say the Soviet Union has about 380,000 troops in
East Germany, the largest force in one of its allied countries.
   East Germany's state-run television broadcast Gorbachev's U.N.
speech live and official newspapers carried the full address under
banner headlines.
   Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Varkonyi, who is visiting
Beijing, was quoted by the state news agency MTI as telling a news
conference there:
   ``I can say that together with our Chinese partners we welcomed
this initiative of great significance in the greatest accord.''
   Hungarian Defense Minister Gen. Ferenc Karpati was quoted as
saying the Soviet withdrawal would affect about one-fourth of the
Soviet troops in Hungary, indicating about 12,000 Soviet troops
would leave.
   The official Czechoslovak news agency CTK said Friday the
Communist Party Politburo on Friday welcomed the Soviet initiative
``with high appreciation and full support.''
   An estimated 80,000 Soviet troops in Czechoslovakia came to the
country during the 1968 Soviet-led Warsaw Pact invasion that crushed
the short-lived ``Prague Spring'' of liberal reforms.
   Gen. Kamen Petrov, a member of the Bulgarian army general staff,
described Gorbachev's announced steps as a ``program of the 21st
century.''
   Polish Foreign Minister Tadeusz Olechowski, in a statement issued
by the official PAP news agency said: ``The announced pullbacks will
contribute essentially to easing the threat of military
confrontation on our continent, especially central Europe.''
   Jacek Czaputowicz, co-founder of the unofficial group Freedom and
Peace, said he hoped the move would lead to removal of all Soviet
troops from Poland.
   Jacek Szymanderski, another co-founder of Freedom and Peace, said
the Soviet army is ``the most important Stalinist institution in the
Soviet Union.''
   Gorbachev's action was ``very important, one of the most
important steps in the de-Stalinization of Soviet policy,'' he told
the AP in a telephone interview.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
