<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LIShootings Bjt   12-09 0632</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LI Shootings, Bjt,0649</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Seek Common Thread In Four Shootings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIVERHEAD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frightened eastern Long Island residents
stayed inside behind drawn curtains after four men were shot on four
successive nights, including three injured by shots fired through
their windows, police said Friday. One person was killed.
   The shootings in two Long Island communities have enough in
common to point to one gunman, police say, but they have not figured
out a motive.
   The victims apparently do not know one another, police said, but
they believe the four were not shot at random.
   Residents have begun shutting themselves in after dark, drawing
their curtains and responding to callers with extreme caution,
police said. Officials refused to predict that the sniper would
strike again Friday night, but extra patrols were deployed and
state, county and local police held a meeting to coordinate their
investigation.
   All the shootings have occurred after dark, most around
dinnertime, within a two-mile radius in Flanders and Riverhead. The
victims, all men in their 30s, were shot with either a small-caliber
rifle or a lightweight shotgun.
   ``I don't at this point think we have a random sniper loose in
the streets who is just shooting away at anyone he sees,'' said
Riverhead Police Chief Lawrence Grattan.
   The two villages are about 75 miles east of New York, not far
from the exclusive beach communities called the Hamptons, frequented
in summer by the city's wealthy.
   ``You don't know where he's going to go next,'' said Barbara
Bouchard of Riverhead, a neighbor of one of the victims.
   An anonymous caller believed to have been the gunman contacted
Riverhead police after the first shooting Monday and said, ``death
to drug dealers and crooked cops,'' according to a source involved
in the investigation who spoke on condition of anonymity. A similar
call came after the second shooting on Tuesday, he said.
   But police said none of the victims was known to have dealt drugs.
   ``We think there is a reason for these shootings, a perverted
type of thing,'' the source said.
   The gunman seems to know the area well enough to be a local
resident. Police theorized that he left a car at a distance from the
scene and approached his targets on foot.
   The shootings occurred this way, according to police accounts:
   _ About 6:40 p.m. Monday, Bernard Heaney, 30, of South Jamesport
stepped outside his auto-customizing shop in Flanders to see why his
dog was yelping. The dog had been shot. Other shots rang out and
Heaney fell fatally wounded by a .22-caliber rifle.
   _ On Tuesday at 6:05 p.m., Richard Jensen, 34, a carpenter, was
watching television with his wife and three children at his home in
Riverhead when a shotgun blast came through the window. Jensen had
his hands clasped at the back of his head and the birdshot blew off
the middle finger of each hand. He also suffered scalp wounds. He
was listed in satisfactory condition Friday.
   _ Theodore Squires, 39, a sign painter, was wounded in the
shoulder by a shotgun at his home in Riverhead about 10:50 p.m.
Wednesday. Squires had answered a knock at the door but saw no one.
He closed the door and started to draw the kitchen curtains when a
shotgun blast through a window in the door hit him in the shoulder.
He was hospitalized in serious condition.
   _ About 6:15 p.m. Thursday, Donald Crump, 31, was shot in the jaw
with a light-caliber rifle bullet by someone firing through a window
as he ate his dinner with his mother and nephew in the living room
of his home in Flanders. The slug came out his neck and lodged in a
wall. He was treated for his wound and released.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
