<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoahRobinson     12-09 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noah Robinson,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Set At $1 Million For Robinson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond was set at $1 million Friday for a
man who is charged in a 1986 slaying and is a half-brother of the
Rev. Jesse Jackson.
   Noah Robinson has been in jail without bail since September, when
he was charged in the death of Leroy ``Hambone'' Barber and turned
himself in to authorities. Bail had not been posted by late Friday
afternoon.
   Indictments accuse Robinson, a Greenville native and
self-described millionaire, of hiring a group of El Rukn street gang
members to travel to Greenville and kill Barber, a former employee
in one of Robinson's companies.
   Robinson, 46, also is charged with conspiring to kill a witness
to Barber's killing. Five El Rukn members also are charged.
   Robinson has maintained that he is a victim of a political
conspiracy caused partly by the success of his half-brother.
Robinson and Jackson share the same father, but the former
Democratic presidential hopeful has said he has had no recent
contact with his half-brother.
   Last week, Robinson's lawyers asked that Robinson be granted bail
under a state law that requires defendants be released when two
terms of court had been completed without trial.
   Circuit Judge James Moore said Friday that he agreed with the
argument ``because of the court's concern for a fair trial.''
   Moore's decision marked the end of a three-month legal battle
over the issue of Robinson's right to be granted bail.
   Moore said Robinson would be required to put up $500,000 in the
form of a surety bond plus $500,000 in the form of a personal
recognizance bond. Moore added that Robinson would be required to
remain in Greenville County until his trial, scheduled to begin Jan.
16.
   A personal recognizance bond means a defendant is liable for the
amount of the bond, but he does not have to offer documentation that
he has the money.
   Moore also agreed Friday that the murder charges against Robinson
and the charges involving the attack on the murder witness should be
tried separately, to avoid prejudice.
</TEXT>
