<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0690 12-09 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0690,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NAACP Leader Says Bush Pledges to Name a Black to Cabinet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs with Teeter considering deputy chief of staff
post</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the NAACP said Friday that
President-elect Bush, who has yet to name a black to any high-level
position, has pledged to put a black in his Cabinet.
   Bush, meantime, reiterated his promise to make the Cabinet
representative of women and minorities. ``Stay tuned,'' he told
reporters.
   The vice president continued his string of meetings with various
interest groups. He spent about 30 minutes with Benjamin Hooks of
the NAACP before a session with 13 conservatives, including Edwin
Feulner Jr., president of the Heritage Foundation, and Paul Weyrich
of the Free Congress Foundation.
   Feulner said the conservatives urged Bush to place people of
their philosophical bent in high positions.
   ``In effect what we urged was that he make sure that all parts of
the (conservative) coalition continue to have a stake in his success
once he becomes president,'' he said.
   Bush was also encouraged to make greater use of his veto power to
prevent an ``erosion of power'' from the executive branch.
Conservatives do not want to see Congress attain too much power,
particularly in foreign affairs, Weyrich said.
   Also among the conservatives on Bush's schedule was Robert
Woodson, a black businessman from North Carolina who has been
mentioned as a possible secretary of housing and urban development.
Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y., is thought to have the inside track for that
job.
   Hooks, a Democrat, said his meeting with Bush was ``very
cordial.'' The two discussed personnel appointments in all levels of
government and the judiciary, as well as issues of concern to
blacks, he said.
   Asked whether Bush had made a commitment to place a black in the
Cabinet, Hooks replied: ``To the best of my recollection, I think I
do remember him saying there would be a black in the Cabinet.''
Hooks then said he had a ``distinct recollection that he said he
intends to do that.''
   Bush has named about a dozen people to top jobs in his
administration so far, only one of them female and none of them
black.
   Hooks, a vocal critic of the Reagan administration's civil rights
policies, said he was confident that his group would have better
relations with Bush.
   ``I expect a much better civil rights record from Mr. Bush,'' he
said.
   Hooks said he asked Bush to think about convening a White House
conference on race and poverty next year, an idea he said Bush
promised to consider.
   Meantime, Robert Teeter, co-director of the Bush transition
office, said he still was trying to decide whether to accept the
post of deputy White House chief of staff under John Sununu, but
that he has been assured direct access to Bush if he does take it.
   Teeter, whose polling data and strategy advice helped propel Bush
to victory in November, said he will decide in ``the next few days''
whether to take the job or return to his home in Michigan with his
wife and two children. ``I don't know what I'm going to do yet,'' he
said in a telephone interview.
   In talks with Bush, he said, it has been agreed that he could
fill the dual role of presidential counselor and deputy chief of
staff.
</TEXT>
