<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 2013EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ToxicHome     12-09 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Toxic Home,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sunken Garden Reveals Toxic Wastes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple who was able to move into a house
through a county rent subsidy were packing to leave it Friday, three
months after their garden collapsed into a sinkhole of decaying
automotive batteries and they learned they were living on one of
California's toxic ``superfund'' sites.
   ``I thought we had gone through the toughest part,'' said Patrick
Piazza. ``When we got this place, I thought we were finally on the
right track and we could settle.''
   County officials made a ``bureaucratic mistake'' when they moved
Piazza and his family into the home last March, said Marice Ashe,
director of health education for Contra Costa County.
   ``No one should live there,'' she said.
   She said tests showed that lead levels in the ground around the
property, which has been on the state's toxic cleanup list since
1986, were not seriously high but were ``on the borderline of posing
a health threat'' to the Piazza children. Kevin, 12, Crystal, 4, and
Patrick Jr., 3, have been living in temporary quarters while the
move is arranged.
   The Piazzas spent five years living in a 25-year-old school bus
and a hotel before county housing authorities helped them move into
the $850-a-month house last March. The Piazzas paid $167 of the
monthly total; the county subsidized the rest.
   Piazza said owner John Thomas Sr. warned him there ``was a very
slight contamination in the back behind the fence. But that's at
least 50 feet away and I knew the kids wouldn't be playing back
there.''
   So they relaxed and planted a vegetable garden in the front yard.
   On Sept. 10, Piazza left the water on in the garden overnight. He
awoke to find a hole about three feet deep and six feet wide where
the garden had been, and a sinkhole filled with old automotive
battery parts. It's now about 15 feet wide, Piazza said.
   ``I was so shocked it took a few minutes for me just to get my
thoughts together,'' he said. ``It caused a lot of scared confusion
in our minds because we didn't know what it had done to us or our
kids.''
   ``Here we had been growing vegetables on top of all those things
and eating the crops for more than two months,'' Piazza said.
   Cost of the cleanup is estimated at $1 million.
   California voters approved a state superfund program in November
1984 to raise funds to clean up toxic waste sites, modeled after the
federal superfund program. The Oakley site was reported to county
health authorities in 1985, and was put on the state cleanupt list
the following year, though not at the top.
   The county advised the state health department that the cleanup
could be put off a few years because an elderly couple aware of the
possible contamination problem was living there. Lead is
particularly dangerous for children.
   State health spokeswoman Jill Singleton said then-owner R.D. Cook
agreed to notify the county if property use changed. But deputy
district attorney Jim Sepulveda said Cook failed to notify the
county when he sold the property. Cook said the county knew he had
planned to sell the land.
   According to Singleton, Cook is legally and financially liable
for the cleanup, which could cost up to $1 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
