<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SanctuaryAppeal     12-09 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sanctuary Appeal,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Group Of Sanctuary Workers Appeal Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawyer for eight Arizona sanctuary
workers told a federal appeals court Friday the defendants believed
the Central American aliens they aided were refugees with a right to
live in the United States.
   Attorney Michael Tigar told a three-judge panel of the 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals that a trial judge in Tucson, Ariz.,
improperly barred the sanctuary workers from presenting evidence of
their beliefs concerning the refugees from strife-torn nations.
   A government attorney, urging the court to uphold the convictions
of all eight defendants, said it was clear the workers never
believed they were acting legally and knew that smuggling aliens was
against the law.
   There was no immediate ruling on the appeal. At a news conference
following the court session, one of those convicted, Peggy
Hutchison, vowed that the sanctuary movement would go on regardless
of the outcome of the case.
   ``We have a duty to respond to the violated in our midst,'' she
said.
   The eight, including five clergymen, were convicted on various
charges of conspiracy, transporting and harboring and aiding illegal
entry of aliens in a highly publicized 1986 trial. All received
probation. Several other defendants were acquitted, pleaded guilty
to misdemeanors or won dismissal of charges.
   Donald M. Reno, who prosecuted the case in Tucson, said their
conspiracy was clearly illegal.
   ``In this case, these defendants were methodically smuggling
these aliens into the United States,'' he said. ``Everything they
were doing was surreptitious and clandestine.''
   He said the defendants had falsified documents and urged aliens
to lie to immigration officers when asked about their country of
origin.
   Tigar of the University of Texas Law School at Austin described
for the judges his interpretation of the law governing refugees:
   ``Anyone who is a refugee ... has the right to have that status
recognized regardless of his mode of entry (into the country),'' he
said. ``Refugee status is something you have because of something
that happened to you in your country of origin.''
   He said all of the defendants had offered to prove at trial that
all the people they assisted were eligible for refugee status.
   Reno, however, accused Tigar of arguing ``a legal fiction that
refugees are entitled to reside here.''
   Tigar also argued that the defendants' First Amendment rights
were violated when a government informant secretly recorded church
services and Bible classes where sanctuary was discussed.
   Reno responded that none of that evidence was ever used at the
trial, but said it was proper because the church had been
transformed from ``an appropriate exercise of religion on Sunday to
a criminal enterprise on Monday.''
   Ms. Hutchison said the defendants believed they were acting
legally.
   ``When immigration authorities violate the rights of those
seeking asylum, we have a responsibility to protect those rights,''
she said. ``It is humane, it is moral and it is legal, and we will
continue until the violation stops.''
   Supporters of the defendants presented to reporters a woman now
seeking asylum. Vilma Mendez said she was imprisoned and tortured in
El Salvador for belonging to a union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
