<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Quayle 1stLdWritethru a0613 12-09 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld Writethru, a0613,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Says Gorbachev Pledge Doesn't Warrant Big U.S. Military Cuts</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 10th graf pvs, bgng: `The vice,' with 4 grafs to UPDATE
with Abrams meeting and CORRECT day of week to Friday. Picks up 11th
graf pvs, `Quayle said'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Sununu Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President-elect Dan Quayle said Friday
that Congress shouldn't try to greatly reduce U.S. military spending
in response to a Soviet pledge to cut troop strength.
   ``Let's not forget that the reason that we're making success with
the Soviet Union and the world is because we have been able to
negotiate from a position of strength,'' he said.
   Quayle, who developed a reputation as a hard-liner on defense
issues while in Congress, said that even if Mikhail S. Gorbachev
follows through on a promise to reduce Soviet troops by 500,000, the
Soviets still will ``have a very significant advantage'' in troops
and weapons in Europe.
   ``I hope that the Congress doesn't try to undercut us and to take
away that position of strength,'' he said. ``I hope that the
Congress doesn't respond and say, `Well, we can dramatically cut
defense spending.'''
   Quayle, commenting on a wide range of topics in an interview with
reporters from his home state of Indiana, denied suggestions he has
been swayed by President-elect Bush's transition team in making
staff appointments and other decisions.
   Referring to the appointment of Time correspondent David
Beckwith, who was more closely associated with Bush, to be his press
secretary, Quayle said: ``It was at my initiative. The appointments
I make will be my appointments and I will be making those decisions
on what I think is best for me and the administration.''
   Quayle said he would be ``a very close personal confidential
adviser to the president'' during Bush's term, and also would focus
on his duties as a member of the National Security Council, as
overseer of the administration's space council, as president of the
Senate and as a promoter of education and job training programs.
   Asked why he had left anti-drug efforts off his list of
priorities, since Bush had led Reagan administration programs in
that area, Quayle said his role had not been determined under new
legislation that calls for appointment of a drug czar.
   He steered clear of speculation over whom Indiana Gov. Robert D.
Orr will appoint to fill the Senate seat that Quayle will vacate,
saying, ``He'll make a good choice, a choice I will support.''
   The vice president-elect also met Friday with conservative Eagle
Forum leader Phyllis Schlafly, Bush national security aides Donald
Gregg and Sam Watson and Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams.
   Quayle told reporters outside his house that in the meeting with
Abrams, whom he characterized as an old friend, they discussed
Central America, Abrams' area of specialty at the State Department.
   Quayle declined to specify what direction the Bush administration
will take on the Nicaragua situation and aid to the Contra rebels,
saying ``those will be major issues, and major strategy we'll have
to formulate,'' but that he could not elaborate on it this early.
   Abrams, whose Iran-Contra testimony revealed he had deceived
Congress about the secret operation to assist the Nicaraguan rebels,
told Quayle he definitely was leaving government to return to
private life, the senator said.
   Quayle said the hardest adjustment he's had to make since
becoming Bush's vice president-elect is learning to live with the
tight security detail that tracks his every move.
   The father of three said he misses ``just sort of now being able
to get in the car and drive down to Wendy's drive-in and get a
milkshake with the kids if you want to.''
   ``We consider ourselves a strong, durable family,'' he continued.
``When you get tested, you actually become close and you become
strengthened in many ways, but it is different.''
   Quayle said the criticism and ridicule he received during the
campaign were difficult to deal with, but ``we knew it was unfair
and wrong. We knew in due time things would be adjusted. You don't
like it but it's part of the political system.''
</TEXT>
