<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nobel-Peacekeeping     12-09 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nobel-Peacekeeping,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief Accepts Nobel Check, Chides U.S. For Failing To Pay Dues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY GERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. chief accepted the 1988 Nobel Peace
Prize check Friday on behalf of U.N. peacekeeping forces, but he
said they are threatened because the United States and other
countries won't pay their dues.
   ``I don't know how we're going to cope financially,'' Secretary
General Javier Perez de Cuellar said before receiving the prize
money of $416,000 _ a fraction of the $450 million in dues owed by
U.N. members.
   ``In some ways it's embarrassing because it forces me to say
publicly that the United States still owes the United Nations almost
$350 million,'' said the U.N. chief.
   ``Yesterday I had a meeting with American congressmen who
complimented me on the peacekeeping forces,'' he said. ``I didn't
want to make a joke, but I told them I thought it would be kind of a
posthumous homage to the United Nations. ... We won't have enough
funds, because you are not paying your contribution.''
   Asked when the U.N. would pay its own peacekeeping force bills to
Norway, Denmark, Britain, Canada and other countries that provide
troops, Perez de Cuellar said: ``They are all understanding. They
think we are honest people. But unfortunately, not everyone is
honest with us.''
   Commenting on Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's call for a
U.N. force to monitor a truce as Soviet troops leave Afghanistan, he
said: ``First of all let us see if a cease-fire is possible. ... It
is of course not a very simple question.''
   On Saturday, Perez de Cuellar receives the traditional gold medal
and certificate from the Norwegian Nobel Committee in a ceremony at
Oslo University's Aula Hall.
   The check handover Friday broke with tradition. It is usually
awarded after the ceremony on Dec. 10, the anniversary of the death
of Swedish philanthropist Alfred Nobel, inventor of dynamite.
   But the U.N. chief was flying to Paris immediately after the
ceremony to commemorate the 40th anniversary of the U.N. Human
Rights Convention.
   Perez de Cuellar cited progress on U.N. efforts to end the
Iran-Iraq war and conflicts in Afghanistan, the Western Sahara,
southern Africa and elsewhere.
   ``I have the impression that all of a sudden so many countries
have discovered that the United Nations is really an extremely
useful mechanism for maintaining peace,'' he said.
   The first U.N. peacekeeping operation was in the Middle East in
1948. Since then, half a million men have served in 15 separate
operations, and more than 700 have been killed. Seven missions are
currently in the field.
   In a report this week, Perez de Cuellar predicted the world body
would end next year with a loss of $24.6 million. Only 79 of the 159
members had paid all their dues by Nov. 30, the report said.
   He said Friday that the Soviet Union owed about $100 million, but
he praised the Soviets for seting a payment schedule and sticking
with it.
</TEXT>
