<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FBI-Plane     12-09 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI-Plane,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI Investigating Shooting Down of Private U.S. Plane in Africa</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Locust Planes Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI launched a criminal investigation
Friday into the downing of a U.S. locust-spraying plane over the
Western Sahara in the heart of an area controlled by the Marxist-led
Polisario independence movement.
   Meanwhile, an official of the U.S. Agency for International
Development said his view is that whoever shot the plane down ``make
a mistake. These were not military planes.''
   The FBI is looking for possible violations of federal criminal
laws, including one that deals with destruction of U.S. aircraft
overseas, FBI spokesman Milt Ahlerich said.
   In opening the investigation, the bureau did not specifically
invoke a 1986 anti-terrorism law which makes it a crime to kill U.S.
nationals outside the United States.
   Five Americans aboard the DC-7 were presumed dead when the craft
was shot down Thursday by a surface-to-air missile.
   Jay Morris, deputy administrator of AID, told reporters the
plane, and another craft accompanying it, were in no sense on a
mission for the United States.
   Morris said the planes had been en route from Senegal, where they
had finished work for AID, to Morocco, where they ``were going to
... seek another job'' spraying locusts for AID.
   Ahlerich said the downed aircraft had been under contract to AID,
but that the contract expired Wednesday. Negotiations were under way
to extend the contracts when the aircraft was shot down, Ahlerich
added.
   Asked if the plane crews had been warned of the risk involved in
flying over the area, Morris replied: ``I don't think anyone knew
they were running a risk.''
   ``My own view is that who ever did it made a mistake,'' Morris
said. ``These were not military planes.''
   Madjid Abdullah, the Polisario's North American representative,
told The Associated Press in Washington the front ``will do
everything possible to shed full light on this tragic and
unfortunate incident.''
   Both aircraft were owned by T&G Aviation of Chandler, Ariz., and
were under contract to AID to spray insects, said T&G co-owner
Sergio Tomassoni, who was in the other plane that was hit.
   Morris said the contracts of the five men presumed dead have been
extended to spare their families the expense of transporting the
bodies back to the United States for burial.
   ``We view this as a tragic and deplorable loss of innocent life
in an effort, really, to save life,'' Morris said.
   Morris said the men were part of an international effort to stop
``one of the most massive insect infestations in decades, a plague
really of biblical proportions.''
</TEXT>
