<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras-USCrash     12-09 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-US Crash,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigation Continues Into Chopper Crash; Names of Dead Released</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Army aviation investigations
team arrived in Honduras Friday to look into what caused the crash
of a military helicopter that killed five U.S. servicemen, a U.S.
Embassy spokesman said.
   Embassy spokesman Charles Barclay identified the dead as 1st Lt.
Alan C. Urban, Staff Sgt. John P. McConnell, and Pfcs. Jim D. Bendon
and Douglas J. Kropp, all based at Fort Bragg, N.C.; and Chief
Warrant Officer Randall B. Potter of Fort Stewart, Ga..
   Barclay did not release their hometowns.
   He said rescue workers continued their search for the body of one
of the servicemen, killed Thursday when their CH-47 Chinook
helicopter crashed near the Caribbean port of La Ceiba, 235 miles
north of Tegucigalpa.
   The helicopter was based at Palmerola Air Base, 48 miles north of
Tegucigalpa, the capital. Officials at Palmerola refused comment.
   Barclay said the Chinook had left Palmerola earlier Thursday on a
supply run in joint U.S.-Honduran military maneuvers.
   A team of investigators from the Army Aviation Center in Fort
Rucker, Ala., arrived in Honduras Friday to look into the crash,
Barclay said.
   It was the second fatal crash this year of a twin-rotor Boeing
Chinook. On Feb. 25, an Army Chinook crashed near Chico, Texas,
killing 10 soldiers and seriously burning eight.
   At least 30 American troops in Honduras have been killed or
wounded in accidents or incidents of violence since the United
States began a series of exercises there in 1982.
   About 1,500 American troops are in Honduras, including 1,100
permanently stationed at Palmerola. Others rotate during the year
for training exercises, military construction work and other
projects.
</TEXT>
