<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WorkRelease-Murderers     12-09 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Work Release-Murderers,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two-Thirds Of Inmates On Work Release At Non-Traditional Prison Are
Murderers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JESSUP, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two-thirds of the inmates granted work-release
status at the controversial Patuxent Institution are murderers and
nearly 60 percent are serving life terms, according to prison
statistics.
   The Patuxent Institution, which emphasizes rehabilitation through
psychotherapy, came under criticism last week when convicted rapist
James M. Stavarakas fled while on work-release and allegedly raped a
woman in Hyattsville. He was arrested Sunday.
   Earlier, it was revealed that triple killer Robert Daly Angell
was granted several unsupervised furloughs.
   Citing the criticism and Stavarakas' escape, the Patuxent board
of review voted Dec. 1 to suspend all furloughs and work release
programs indefinitely.
   Lifers turn up more often in Patuxent's work-release and leave
programs than do inmates from the prison's general population,
according to the figures released Thursday by the Department of
Public Safety and Correctional Services. While those serving life
sentences represent about one in five Patuxent inmates, they make up
59 percent of those on work-release and 28 percent of those on
leave, the figures showed.
   The figures also showed that inmates serving life terms at
Patuxent serve only half as much time as do lifers at other Maryland
prisons before they are granted parole.
   The 16 Patuxent lifers paroled from July 1, 1977, to June 30,
1988, served an average of 8.4 years before release. Life inmates at
other Maryland prisons are confined 17 years on average before
parole, saidDr. Norma B. Gluckstern, Patuxent's director.
   Patuxent is unusual because of the wide authority given to prison
officials to grant leaves to inmates, although a 1982 law requires
approval by the governor before an inmate serving for life is
paroled.
   Several state lawmakers have suggested that further restrictions
be placed on the prison's governing board.
   Inmates are sent to Patuxent because correction officials
consider them more likely to be rehabilitated through its program of
psychological and psychiatric counseling.
</TEXT>
