<DOCNO> AP881209-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1938EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-LocustPlanes 1stLd-Writethru a0595 12-09 0883</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Locust Planes, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0595,0904</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Team Having Trouble Reaching Crash Site</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 21 grafs to CLARIFY that plane went down in Western
Sahara, CORRECT spelling of Tommasoni and hometown of Wes Wilson,
UPDATE with Moroccan comment, FBI investigation, widow's comment.
Pick up 18th pvs, ``We lost...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RABAT, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials on Friday tried to determine who
shot down a U.S. locust-spraying plane, and a U.S. team reported
trouble in reaching the wreckage in a remote area used by rebels to
launch attacks.
   The investigators told the U.S. Embassy in Rabat by telephone the
wreckage of the DC-7 lay in the Western Sahara within a 25-mile-wide
strip between Mauritania and the most forward positions along a
2,000-mile defense wall built by Morocco.
   That confirmed earlier U.S. satellite data placing the site in
the heart of an area the Marxist-led Polisario independence movement
in the Western Sahara uses to group its forces. A surface-to-air
missile downed the plane Thursday morning and damaged another plane
that managed to land safely.
   ``At this point, we still don't know who fired the missile,''
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Friday. Asked whether
U.S. officials thought it was a terrorist incident, he said, ``Well,
we don't know yet. A lot depends on something we don't know yet,
which is who did it.''
   U.S. military experts said the site was a few miles east of
Daddar Lahlou, a desert outpost halfway between the Mauritanian
border and the defensive wall Morocco erected to guard the most
valuable part of the phosphate-rich territory. The spot is about 650
miles south of Rabat, the capital of this North African country.
   The plane was chartered by the U.S. Agency for International
Development. Reports said it exploded at an altitude of about 10,000
feet and that the five occupants, all Americans, were presumed to be
dead. The wreckage was scattered over a wide area.
   A second DC-7 chartered by AID to help fight the locust plague in
northern Africa also was hit by a missile, but limped 250 miles and
land safely at Sidi Ifni. It sat at the end of the single runway
Friday, and the Sidi Ifni airport was closed.
   Sergio Tommasoni, 64, co-owner of the Chandler, Ariz., aviation
company that owned both planes, was crew chief of the second plane.
He and the other four men aboard were reported safe in Agadir.
   The American investigators were experiencing ``unusual
difficulties'' in reaching the site, U.S. military experts said.
They did not elaborate.
   The Americans aboard the downed plane were identified as Joel
Blackmer, 46, and Blackmer's son, Frank Kennedy, 21, both of
Phoenix; Ben Rossini, 49, Tempe, Ariz.; Frank Hederman, 47, Cody,
Wyo.; and Wes Wilson of North Platte, Neb.
   In Nebraska, Wilson's widow, Linda Wilson, said she talked with
her husband by telephone on Wednesday night and expected him to be
home by Monday.
   ``They knew there were border disputes, but they evidently didn't
think that had anything to do with them,'' she said in an interview
with KKAR Radio of Omaha.
   It was widely assumed, though not confirmed officially, that both
missiles were fired by a guerrilla unit.
   Polisario fighters in the area usually have Soviet-designed SAM
missiles for defense against Moroccan aircraft. Both DC-7s were
flying at 10,000 to 11,000 feet, generally considered too high for
visual identification.
   An American official said privately it was ``at least possible''
the attackers thought the planes were Moroccan.
   In Washington, State Department officials said the FBI has been
brought into the case to investigate who fired the missile at the
planes and why.
   Madjid Abdullah, the Polisario's North American representative,
told The Associated Press in Washington the front ``will do
everything possible to shed full light on this tragic and
unfortunate incident.''
   He said the Polisario Front has no interest in creating an
incident with the United States and declared that Morocco must
assume responsibility for sending civilian planes over an area with
a ``huge concentration'' of Polisario forces.
   The government of King Hassan II of Morocco issued a statement
Friday denouncing what it called ``this act of barbarism.'' It said
the victims were ``shot down coldly while they were fulfilling a
humanitarian duty.''
   Morocco rarely comments on events in the 14-year-old war with
Polisario, but habitually claims its defensive wall runs flush with
the Mauritanian border.
   Tommasoni described the two-hour trip in the crippled plane to
Sidi Ifni as ``hairy.''
   ``We lost altitude. We were 25 to 30 feet above the ground most
of the way,'' he said by telephone from his hotel room in Agadir.
``We had a load of insecticide aboard and we dumped it and were able
to gain some altitude.''
   The planes left Dakar, capital of Senegal, early Thursday morning
for Agadir to join the battle against locusts.
   Morocco annexed the former Spanish Sahara after Spain withdrew in
1975 and Moroccan positions were attacked soon afterward by
Polisario guerrillas based in Algeria. Fighting has continued
despite Morocco's construction of the wall.
   The United Nations plans to organize a referendum among the
80,000 people who lived in the territory under Spanish rule and
their children. The two sides have not agreed, however, on exactly
who should be allowed to vote or a plan for withdrawing Moroccan
forces.
</TEXT>
