<HEAD>Report Says Authorities Break Spy Ring</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOGNE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal police and Western
intelligence agencies have broken a spy ring that was supplying NATO
secrets to the Soviet Union, a newspaper reported Friday.
   The Cologne Express newspaper called it ``a huge blow against the
Soviet secret service,'' the KGB.
   Detlev Achammer, spokesman for the West Berlin Justice
Department, confirmed that ``three people are being investigated for
suspicion of espionage.''
   He said one was taken into custody for interrogation on Friday,
and that a warrant is out for another. He refused to elaborate.
   The Cologne newspaper said it learned from security sources that
the ``espionage ring had obtained strictly secret electronics of the
Leopard II tank and important high-tech equipment such as
micro-processors.''
   It said some of the equipment has ``already been sent to the
East.''
   According to the newspaper, Western intelligence agencies, the
West German federal police, and police in West Berlin are involved
in the case.
   The newspaper did not give any further details.
   The Cologne Express sent copies of its report to other news
organizations in advance of Saturday's publication.
