<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HitlerParty     12-09 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hitler Party,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nevada Casino Board Accuses Casino Owner Over Hitler Parties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN GRIFFITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of the Imperial Palace casino
faces a possible $400,00 fine and loss of his gaming license over
Adolf Hitler birthday celebrations held at the Las Vegas Strip
resort, state officials said Friday.
   The owner, Ralph Engelstad, threw the parties at his casino last
April and April 1986, according to one count of the state Gaming
Control Board complaint.
   The incidents ``have become public knowledge throughout the
United States and in certain foreign countries and reflect or tend
to reflect on the repute of the state of Nevada and act as a
detriment to its gaming industry,'' the complaint said.
   A second count alleges Engelstad destroyed or concealed evidence
relevant to an unrelated civil action stemming from a 1984 rape case
at the Imperial Palace.
   The complaint seeks a fine of up to $400,000 for the alleged
violations, plus the possible revocation, suspension or restriction
of Engelstad's gaming license.
   No date has been set for a state Gaming Commission hearing on the
board's complaint. During the hearing, commission members will act
as judges and control board members will act as prosecutors.
   There was no immediate comment from Engelstad; he would not take
reporters' calls at his casino Friday and no other spokesman was
immediately available.
   In October, Engelstad issued a public apology for the Hitler
parties, saying they were ``not only stupid, but insensitive.''
   The complaint alleges the two Hitler birthday celebrations were
held around April 20, Hitler's birthday. It alleges they featured
cakes decorated with swastikas, Nazi-era German marching music and
German food.
   Bartenders at the parties wore T-shirts bearing a picture of
Hitler and the message ``Adolf Hitler _ European Tour 1939-45,''
according to the complaint.
   The complaint claimed the celebrations were held in the Imperial
Palace's so-called ``War Room,'' which housed Engelstad's collection
of memorabilia from Germany's Third Reich, including a portrait of
himself in a Nazi uniform.
   The complaint also alleges the Imperial Palace's print shop was
used in August 1986 to print 500 bumper stickers stating ``Hitler
Was Right.''
</TEXT>
