<HEAD>Prodigy to Live With Mother on Temporary Basis, Investigator Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CRUZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twelve-year-old college graduate
Adragon De Mello, who was taken away from his father in September,
will live with his mother on a trial basis beginning this weekend,
representatives of both parents said.
   Adragon, who is believed to be the country's youngest college
graduate, was placed in a foster home after his mother alleged that
the boy and his father had a suicide pact.
   Agustin De Mello, 58, the boy's father, said he will contest the
court's decision. He was arrested in September for investigation of
felony child endangerment although no charges have been filed. He
has denied forming any suicide pact.
   The decision by Santa Cruz County Child Protective Services this
week did not mean that the mother would be given permanent custody,
Robert Bortnick, an investigator who works for the father's
attorney, said Thursday.
   Officials at the agency refused to discuss the case and the boy's
mother, Cathy Gunn, also declined comment. But Gunn's attorney,
Patricia Vorreiter, said Thursday that the boy will move to his
mother's Santa Clara County home on Saturday.
   Adragon graduated from the University of California at Santa Cruz
in June, when he was 11. He earned a degree in mathematics.
