<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 2119EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietAcademician     12-09 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Academician,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Scientists Competing For Use of Controversial Radar,
Official Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet scientists are competing with each other
to develop a research project for the scientific use of a
controversial military radar, the president of the Soviet Academy of
Sciences said Friday.
   Guriy Marchuk, who leads the Soviet academy, said that at least
four scientific uses for the large radar station at Krasnoyarsk have
been proposed to the academy, but no final decision has been made.
   The radar, located in a remote sector of central Siberia, was
turned over to the Soviet academy by Soviet president Mikhail S.
Gorbachev after the Reagan administration claimed that it was a
violation of the anti-ballistic missile treaty between the U.S. and
the Soviet Union.
   The radar is neither on the edge of the Soviet Union nor is it
pointed outward, as is required by the ABM treaty. It is believed by
U.S. experts that the radar was built for the detection and tracking
of ballistic missiles.
   Marchuk, who lectured Friday at the National Academy of Sciences,
was asked what the Soviet academy planned to do with the radar.
   ``We don't know,'' Marchuk replied through an interpreter. ``We
have declared a competition or contest'' to find the best use for
the radar station.
   ``We have at least four projects suggesting what we should do
with it,'' he added. He said the proposals include both space and
atmospheric research.
   Marchuk, speaking to an audience of American researchers, said
that scientists everywhere may participate in the competition.
   ``I invite all of those with ideas to come up with proposals and
send them to us,'' he said.
   In his lecture, Marchuk said the Soviet Union now is applying
democratic principles in selecting the scientific leadership of the
nation.
   He said there are about 520 academic institutions in the USSR and
that they all recently selected new leaders on a ``competitive
basis.''
   ``More than half of the academic institutions now are headed by
young people,'' said Marchuk. ``This is possible only in the
atmosphere of democracy.''
   The academy president said he regarded this as a good development
for Soviet science because ``the best ideas come into the minds of
people under the age of 30. After 30 they just develop their ideas.''
   Marchuk gave the lecture on the opening day of a conference
marking the 30th year of cooperatation and exchange between the
National Academy of Sciences of the United States, and the Academy
of Sciences of the USSR.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
