<DOCNO> AP881209-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 2042EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-S&LClosing     12-09 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-S&L Closing,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Bank Board Commits $1 Billion to Close Denver S&L</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal savings and loan regulators on Friday
pledged $1.05 billion to shut down an insolvent Denver institution
in one of the nation's biggest S&L failures.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which regulates federally
insured S&Ls, created a new institution to receive $1.7 billion in
deposits of the Silverado Banking, Savings and Loan Association,
which was ordered closed by Colorado regulators.
   After the failed institution's assets are liquidated, federal
regulators expect to have spent slightly more than $1 billion.
Silverado joins only a handful of financial institutions that have
cost government insurance funds that much to close or rescue.
   In the largest-ever clean-up of a single insolvent S&L _ the
pending rescue of American Savings and Loan Association of Stockton,
Calif. _ the bank board estimates it will spend $2 billion.
   In the case of Silverado, the bank board's insurance fund, the
Federal Savings and Loan Insurance Corp., is pumping $200 million in
cash to the new, government-owned institution, Mile High Federal
Savings and Loan Association, and pledging another $624 million in a
promissory note.
   Starting Monday, all Silverado depositors with accounts under the
insurance limit of $100,000 will be able to deposit and withdraw
money as usual at the new Mile High.
   The bank board is hiring First Nationwide Bank of San Francisco
to manage Mile High. It appointed a five-member board of directors,
headed by Donald F. Roby of Nevada, Mo., president of Farm Home
Savings Association.
   The current stockholders and manager won't benefit from the
transaction, the bank board said. The institution's president, W.
James Metz, controlled about 90 percent of the stock.
   The bank board attributed the failure to ``substantial
dissipation of assets due to alleged violations of laws, rules and
regulations.'' It said Silverado had swapped some of its preferred
stock for undeveloped land owned by developers.
   Regulators said Silverado was losing money on many of its loans
and that much of its investments were direct interests in risky
commercial real estate ventures, rather than in the traditional S&L
business of home mortgage lending.
   The bank board has closed, merged or otherwise ``resolved'' the
cases of 148 insolvent S&Ls so far this year, a post-Depression
record, spending or pledging to spend about $23 billion. M. Danny
Wall, bank board chairman, said last week that he hoped to have
resolved 200 cases by the end of the year.
   Meanwhile, the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation on Friday
gave preliminary approval to a program to bail out Tracy Collins
Bank and Trust Company of Salt Lake City. Under the program Tracy
will merge with the Continental Bank and Trust Co. in Salt Lake to
create a bank with total assets of approximately $600 million.
   In a separate action, the FDIC also allowed Citicorp Holdings,
Inc. of New York to purchase Caribank, Dania as a national bank
subsidiary. The FDIC had been named receiver for Caribank when
Florida's comptroller closed it Friday.
   About 400 of 3,000 S&Ls are insolvent and estimates of the cost
of the total clean-up range up to $100 billion. The Treasury
Department is working on a plan for President-elect Bush aimed at
directing more money to the resolutions without adding substantially
to the federal budget deficit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
