<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 2131EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Politics     12-09 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Politics,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rocard's Government Survives First Censure Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Socialist Premier Michel Rocard's minority
government survived its first National Assembly censure vote early
Saturday when Communist members refused to back the conservative
opposition.
   Only 258 legislators, all members of rightist or center-right
parties, voted for the censure motion.
   Under the French Constitution, the government is forced to resign
on a censure motion only if an absolute majority _ 286 out of 571 _
votes for it, not just a majority of those voting.
   Only votes in favor are recorded. There are no abstentions or
votes against. Six seats are vacant in the 577-member chamber of
deputies, the lower house.
   Rocard has been widely criticized for his handling of a series of
strikes by public employees, including one that has disrupted
subway, bus and suburban train service for the past two weeks. But
he was in no danger of losing the censure vote.
   ``France is at an impasse,'' Philippe Seguin, speaking for the
conservative Rally for the Republic party, said in the censure
debate. ``A country needs to be led, to know where it's going, how
it's getting there and why it's going there.''
   Rocard told the National Assembly it was a ``motion of spite''
presented because the right was ``embitterred by its defeat'' in
this year's presidential and legislative elections.
   He called the motion ``an operation of political diversion, with
its result known in advance and with no effect on the political or
social climate.''
   The debate began Friday night and lasted past midnight.
   The current chamber of deputies is made up of 273 Socialists, 130
members of the Rally for the Republic, 89 from the center-right
Union for French Democracy, 41 in the Union of the Center, 24
Communists and 14 independents.
   President Francois Mitterrand named Rocard premier last May after
winning re-election to a new seven-year term. In June's legislative
elections, the Socialists fell short of winning a majority in the
chamber, but did well enough to prevent the right from taking
control.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
