<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 2300EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Quake-Americans 1stLd-Writethru a0735 12-09 1076</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quake-Americans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0735,1106</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Americans Organize Relief Efforts For Armenia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 18 grafs to UPDATE with dog team plans; relief
activities launched in Rhode Island, Illinois, Washington, Boston,
California, elsewhere; picks up 8th graf: `In Oregon ...; ADDS 2
grafs with Ohio fund drive.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans are responding to the earthquake in Armenia with offers
of medical supplies, doctors, money, specially trained dogs and
prayers.
   As Soviet officials reported 80,000 people died in the disaster
Wednesday in northwestern Armenia, the American Red Cross collected
money, antibiotics and supplies and groups throughout the United
States began efforts to help the survivors.
   Rhode Island's Gov. Edward DiPrete offered to send his state's
National Guard to Armenia if President Reagan approves. ``It's just
a willingness to help in whatever way possible,'' DiPrete said.
   The Chicago chapter of the Armenian General Benevolent Union,
began accepting relief donations, including two or more ambulances
for the disaster area, said the group's treasurer, Peter Klujian.
   The ambulance contributor, who lives in Florida, ``sent the money
to the manufacturer in East Germany and is having them sent directly
to the earthquake area,'' Klujian said.
   In Washington, an Armenian Diocese Earthquake Fund was set up at
St. Mary's Armenian Church. During a memorial service, its pastor,
the Rev. V. Kalayjian, described the devastation as ``the disaster
that fell on us like a bomb.''
   Boston-based Oxfam America donated $20,000 for temporary shelter
and medical supplies, its first relief effort in an industrialized
nation and in the Soviet Union, officials said.
   Members of the U.S. Disaster Dog Search and Rescue Team headed to
New York and planned to go to Armenia to aid in search efforts,
officials said Friday.
   Team members from Northeast Search and Rescue, New Jersey, and
Dogs East, Virginia, were summoned from their homes across the East
Coast and gathered at JFK International Airport in New York on
Friday.
   Eight dogs, their handlers, equipment and a two-week supply of
dog food were to be flown to the Soviet Union aboard a jet flight
arranged by the State Department, said Judi Kroeger, a spokeswoman
for Allentown, Pa.-based Alpo Petfoods Inc., which sponsors the
units.
   Specific flight times had not been set, but the jet was to fly
first to Washington, D.C.'s Dulles Airport and leave for the Soviet
Union at 2 a.m. to 3 a.m. Saturday, said a worker in the U.S. Agency
for International Aid's Office of Foreign Disaster Assistance, who
asked not to be identified.
   In California, Archbishop Vatche Hovsepian called an emergency
meeting of the largest Armenian community outside the Soviet Union
to raise money and medical supplies for ``our stricken families and
friends in Armenia.''
   Hovsepian, leader of the Armenian Apostolic Church's Western
Diocese, also declared a 40 days' mourning for quake victims.
   In Los Angeles, KSCI-TV scheduled a fund-raising telethon between
midnight Saturday and 6 a.m. Sunday, to be broadcast in English and
Armenian throughout Southern California and in Armenian communities
nationwide, officials said.
   Occidental Petroleum chairman Armand Hammer delivered a message
from his Los Angeles headquarters to the Soviet Embassy in
Washington, D.C., promising the use of a private jet to fly supplies
to the region.
   In Alaska, Gov. Steve Cowper also has offered to send the Soviet
Union teams of trained dogs and searchers to help find survivors
trapped in the earthquake rubble.
   ``The state of Alaska has a history of similar natural disasters.
As a result, we have developed considerable expertise in contending
with the problems associated with earthquakes, avalanches and other
natural catastrophes,'' Cowper said in a letter to Soviet officials
in Washington.
   In Seattle, the Armenian Church of Seattle and the Armenian
Clutural Association here are collecting food, clothing and supplies
for victims of the quake.
   In Oregon, the Portland-based Northwest Medical Teams was
appealing to the public for donations, medical supplies and
volunteers for a possible relief mission to Armenia.
   Ron Post, Northwest Medical Teams president, said he hopes 25
people will go on the mission. The team would include orthopedic
surgeons, neurosurgeons, scrub nurses, orthopedic and
neuro-technicians, an anesthesiologist and support personnel.
   While the U.S. State Department helped the group in its effort to
obtain visas, the organization also began contacting airlines
Thursday to help transport the team and an estimated 80,000 pounds
of medical equipment. The cost of the operation is estimated to be
$250,000, Post said.
   Armenians in Wisconsin banded together with prayers and donations
to help victims of the earthquake that ravaged their homeland.
   The Rev. Tateos Abdalian, pastor at the St. John the Baptist
Armenian Apostolic Church in Greenfield, Wis., said hundreds of
people called with donations of money, clothing and other items. The
church is planning clothing, blood and blanket drives.
   In Cleveland, the 100-member St. Gregory of Narek Armenian Church
said it would accept donations for earthquake victims.
   The Soviet Embassy in Washington said it has been overwhelmed
with telephone calls and by people who are ``walking up to the doors
of the embassy with checks and money orders.''
   New Jersey residents also have opened their hearts and their
pocketbooks to the earthquake victims.
   ``Americans, Armenians, non-Armenians _ the American people are
very generously cooperating with funds,'' said Sonig Vayejian,
associate director of the New Jersey chapter of the Armenian General
Benevolent Union.
   She said the group has 10 phone lines operating 24 hours a day
and was installing an additional five to handle the crush.
   The Rev. Karl Vartan Avakiar of the Armenian Presbyterian Church
in Paramus, N.J., said at least 12 doctors from Hudson and Bergen
counties and several nurses were ready to fly to Armenia with
medical supplies and bedding as soon as they got permission from the
Soviet government.
   The New Jersey Council of Churches, which represents 3,000
churches statewide from 16 denominations, issued an emergency appeal
to its members to take up special collections Sunday for the
earthquake victims.
   ``This is one of the world's most disastrous earthquakes,'' said
the council's executive director, the Rev. Charles W. Rawlings.
``Our brothers and sisters in Armenia are suffering again on a scale
we Americans can barely imagine. They need our help.''
   In Columbus, Ohio, Cincinnati Insurance Cos.' chief executive and
the state insurance director announced a fund-raising drive to raise
at least $500,000 for medical aid to quake victims.
   CEO John Schiff said he would contact the heads of all 283
Ohio-chartered insurance companies to ask for donations, an idea
proposed by state Insurance Director George Fabe.
</TEXT>
