<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1056EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-Ruby'sDinner ADV12   12-09 0881</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Ruby's Dinner, ADV 12,0897</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs, Dec. 12, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Dinner With Miss Ruby and Friends</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY MacVEAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A holiday dinner as sassy and sumptuous as the
one Miss Ruby serves up is a feast indeed.
   The table is set Tuesday on PBS for ``Miss Ruby's Southern
Holiday Dinner,'' and even Yankees will feel right at home with New
York restaurateur Ruth Adams Bronz, aka ``Miss Ruby,'' and her
guests: humorist Roy Blount Jr., entertainer Pearl Bailey, Annie
Potts of ``Designing Women,'' and food writer Craig Claiborne.
   Together they cook, eat and talk about some of the hallmarks of a
Southern Christmas feast _ Smithfield ham, which ``looks funny,
tastes real good,'' says Bronz; red-eye gravy; red snapper stuffed
with crab; turkey and cornbread stuffing; scalloped oysters and
derby pie. It's a delightful hour, for cooks and for eaters.
   Bronz, whose restaurant features a changing menu of regional
American foods, was ``raised in Texas by a Louisiana grandmother''
and so qualifies as a Southern cook. But she acknowledges at the
start that some will disagree with her version of the dishes:
``Every Southerner believes his South is the only true one.''
   Her guests come from Virginia (Bailey), Georgia (Blount),
Kentucky (Potts), and Mississippi (Claiborne), and have a range of
experience in the kitchen. Blount, for instance, mostly puts things
in and takes things out of the oven, tastes the food, and comments
on it: ``This is the prettiest ham. I've seen little children that
weren't as pretty.''
   Over cocktails, Potts and Bronz laugh about fruitcakes and
Yankees, and Claiborne and Blount discuss childhood Christmases,
including Claiborne's memories of breakfasts of quail and ham with
red-eye gravy and grits.
   When Claiborne makes his cornbread stuffing, he notes that it's
``not essential to cook these innards until they're quite
well-done'' because they'll cook in the turkey. But Blount wanders
into the kitchen, takes a handful of stuffing and bites into a raw
giblet, which Claiborne calls ``chicken gizzard sashimi.''
   At one point, Bronz coerces Blount and Potts to pick crab for the
snapper stuffing. As they work on a big pile of blue crabs, they
giggle and reminisce, and Blount, who steals a few bites and gets
caught with crabmeat on the end of his nose, lets on that he's
borrowed Claiborne's apron.
   ``When I used to try to cook things, people used to say, `You
couldn't wear Craig Claiborne's apron.' But I showed them,''' he
says.
   When Bronz was working with producer Robert Kanter and director
Michael Wolkowitz to plan ``Miss Ruby's Southern Holiday Dinner,''
it was decided to try to fit the celebrity guests in with the
cooking, said Bronz.
   That's authentic, Bronz said in a telephone interview, explaining
that her grandmother's generation would make long trips across the
prairie ``for house parties that would last six weeks over the
holidays. And I think that was in my mind in some way. .. . I had a
real vision of these people being in my kitchen.''
   The result is comfortable and welcoming, what Kanter calls a
``comedy-cooking-talk'' show.
   Bronz said she worried a little that the food would be
overwhelmed by all the commotion, but when serious work is under way
in the kitchen, the directions are clear and concise and easy to
follow. Viewers also can send for recipes.
   ``I really think good food is riveting. I don't think people will
wander from that,'' Bronz said. ``And we really set it up so that
when we weren't making food, we were talking about it. Southerners
just love to talk about food, and if they're not talking about food,
they're talking about family. And sometimes they're talking about
food and family.''
   There are dishes for cooks of all abilities. Potts makes her
derby pie in less than 5 minutes, and many people will sympathize
when she zaps the butter too long in a microwave oven and declares,
``It's spitting at me.'' Potts even admits she doesn't make her own
crust for her pie of pecans, chocolate chips, eggs and sugar.
   After filming, the food was donated to a shelter for homeless
people.
   The show is intended as the first of a series on American
regional cooking, including future similar holiday specials.
   Bronz said she is on a ``mission'' to promote American food,
announcing at the start: ``It's Miss Ruby's job to see that great
American food goes public.''
   Wish her well, for then we all can see more of Miss Ruby.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   CHANGING DESKS IN WASHINGTON _ NBC News has made Washington
assignment changes in the wake of the decision by White House
correspondent Chris Wallace to go to ABC. John Cochran, formerly at
the State Department, succeeds Wallace at the White House; also
covering the White House will be Jim Miklaszewski and Sandy Gilmour,
who returns from Moscow next month; Andrea Mitchell, who was at the
White House, becomes chief congressional correspondent; political
correspondent Ken Bode is also on the Congress beat. John Dancy
takes over at State. Lisa Myers will be backup there and also cover
the Bush administration's war on drugs. Tom Pettit gets a newly
created beat, ``poverty and the American underclass.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, Dec. 12</NOTE>
</DOC>
