<1ST_LINE>a w AM-NewstoUse Adv14   12-09 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-News to Use, Adv14,0530</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Dec. 14, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Holiday Decorations, Use Care</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The annual crop of holiday greenery is
sprouting in American homes. Enjoying those decorations also means
using some care to avoid fire and keep children from poisoning
themselves accidentally.
   Some of the most popular plants used for holiday decorations are
poisonous, according to the National Clearinghouse for Poison
Control Centers.
   Holly is popular because of its bright green leaves and red
berries, but the berries can be dangerous if eaten.
   Swallowing the berries can lead to diarrhea, vomiting and
depression of the central nervous system, the Poison Control Center
says.
   Mistletoe berries are another danger, containing chemicals that
can cause abdominal pain, diarrhea, vomiting, high blood pressure
and even collapse of the circulatory system, medical authorities
say. In addition, diarrhea, weakness, low blood pressure and other
problems can occur from eating any part of the yew plant.
   Those lovely red poinsettias can be troublesome too. Health
officials say that if any part of the plant is swallowed it can
cause abdominal discomfort, while the milky sap from the leaves can
cause an irritation or dermatitis in some people.
   Another decoration danger is fire, with Christmas trees and other
greenery a major problem.
   Try to keep the tree as moist as possible, the Consumer Product
Safety Commission urges. After bringing it home cut off a few inches
of the base and place it in water. And keep the tree well watered
when in use.
   Buyers should avoid dry trees, of course. A good test is to pull
on some needles and see if they resist. The harder they are to pull
off, the better.
   If the cut part of the tree is sticky with resin, that's a good
sign.
   Try bouncing the tree on the ground a bit: a shower of falling
needles tells you that it's too dry.
   When going to bed or leaving the house turn off lights on trees
and other decorations, the commission said. And never use candles on
trees or near greens.
   Check all lights for broken bulbs and frayed wires before
installing them, and discard any damaged strings.
   Never use lights on a metallic artificial tree. A faulty string
can cause the entire tree to become charged, potentially causing an
electrocution. This type of tree can be brightened by a spotlight
shining on it.
   Other safety suggestions from the Safety Commission include:
   _Artificial snow sprays can irritate the lungs if inhaled. Read
the directions carefully and follow them.
   _Wear gloves when decorating with spun glass ``angel hair'' to
avoid irritation to eyes and skin.
   _Use plastic ``tinsel'' rather than the leaded kinds which could
be hazardous if ingested.
   _In homes with children be especially careful of using fragile
decorations or items with sharp points or which resemble candy or
food.
   _Before lighting any fire make sure trimmings and wrapping paper
are clear of the area. Do not burn wrappings in the fireplace.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Dec 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881209-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1426EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Trotsky'sGrandson Adv13   12-09 0825</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trotsky's Grandson, Adv13,0851</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, Dec. 13, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Glasnost Has Not Entered House Where Trotsky Was Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The grandson of Leon Trotsky sat in the room
where one of Stalin's assassins killed the old revolutionary with an
ax and pondered how far the new, more enlightened Kremlin would go
toward making amends.
   ``If glasnost wants to have authenticity ... it must recognize
the proper place of Leon Trotsky'' in history, Esteban Volkow
Bronstein said, using the word denoting the more open Soviet
policies of Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The latest sign of change came Dec. 6, when Volkow received
permission to visit his half-sister Alexandra, who is dying of
cancer in Moscow. He has not been to the Soviet Union or seen his
sister in 57 years, and learned only last month that she was alive.
   ``It's all part of Gorbachev's policy,'' Volkow said, and Trotsky
has been emerging slowly from ``the dark cave'' of Soviet history
since glasnost began.
   ``For 50 or 60 years the Russian public has been conditioned to
think of him as almost the devil,'' his grandson said. ``You can't
change black to white in one day.''
   Leon Trotsky, born Lev Davidovich Bronstein in 1879, was among
the most popular leaders of the 1917 Bolshevik revolution _
commander of the Red Army, commissar for war and foreign affairs,
the right hand of Lenin. After losing a power struggle with Josef
Stalin, he became a ``non-person.''
   Stalin exiled him in 1929 and Trotsky's name was stricken from
Soviet history. Photographs and film were doctored to erase his
image. Real and imagined followers were hunted down, and imprisoned
or killed.
   Trotsky's road ended on a summer afternoon in at his desk in the
modest house in Coyoacan, in those days was a quiet village.
Coyoacan is enveloped by the smog of Mexico City now, but in the
house itself little has change since the assassin entered it Aug.
20, 1940, with a mountaineer's ice ax.
   It has no plaques, polished display cases or uniformed guards,
but there is a caretaker to greet visitors. He answers the bell,
shows them through the rooms and hands them the guest book to sign.
   ``There was a terrible solitude, an emptiness here in the
house,'' Volkow said, remembering the years after the assassination.
He was born in the Soviet Union to Trotsky's daughter Zina and now
is 62, a semi-retired chemical engineer.
   Trotsky's house always has attracted a few Soviet visitors, he
said, but more have come in the past year or so.
   ``They are opening windows in Russia,'' Volkow said. ``They are
turning on the light. There is a freshness.''
   Glasnost has not altered Trotsky's official status but his name
sometimes is mentioned publicly and the Soviet Supreme Court
rehabilitated a son, Volkow's step-uncle Sergei Sedov, who died in a
Stalin purge.
   In September, the Communist Party newspaper Pravda called Trotsky
an ``enemy of Stalin'' rather than an enemy of ``socialism'' and the
revolution.
   ``I believe that his heroic struggle, almost alone, against one
of the most terrible, the bloodiest tyrannies in history is the
stage of his life that is going to have the most historical
importance,'' Volkow said.
   A quiet river that ran behind Trotsky's house two generations ago
has become a stream of vehicles belching fumes on a freeway, but in
the shadowed rooms, behind thick walls, time seems congealed.
   ``It's curious. He didn't live here long ...but he impregnated
the house with his presence,'' the grandsom said.
   Beside the reading lamp, the dictaphone waits next to books in
French, German, Russian, Spanish and English on Hitler, capitalism,
Italian fascism, colonialism, British trade unionism.
   The bloodstains on Trotsky's chair have faded but bullet holes
from an earlier assassination attempt still pock the bedroom walls.
   He had the windows shuttered with steel and the gateway bricked
up after the attack May 24, 1940, by Mexican Stalinists with machine
guns.
   Three months later, a Stalinist agent who had insinuated himself
into the Trotsky circle attacked with the ice ax. When Volkow, then
14, entered the room his grandfather lay on the floor, bleeding, his
wife at his side.
   The assassin spent 20 years in prison but his identity never was
confirmed. He was thought to be a Spaniard, Ramon del Rio Mercader,
but also was known as Jacques Mornard and Frank Jackson.
   Volkow said Trotsky treated each day after the May attack as a
bonus: ``Every morning after he got up, he would say `Another day of
life, Natalia. Another day of life.'''
   Natalia Sedov, Trotsky's second wife, lived in the house for more
than 20 years after the assassination. She died in Paris in 1962.
   In the garden, a simple gray stone monument carved with a hammer
and sickle encloses the ashes of Trotsky and Natalia.
   A red flag flutters overhead.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tue AMs, Dec. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881209-0190 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1427EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-LibItalianStyle Adv14   12-09 0929</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lib Italian Style, Adv14,0956</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed Dec. 14 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<HEAD>Italian Women Getting Ahead, Say Men Must Catch Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's hottest anchorwoman hikes her skirt on the
evening news, gets sozzled on champagne from male admirers and,
before signing off, invites men to call her on a special line.
   It happens in a television spoof of television, written and
directed by women, but real life is getting closer. State television
has a woman news reader.
   ``When you feel secure, you can poke fun at yourself,'' said
Serena Dandini, one of three authors of the new weekly show ``TiVu
Delle Ragazze'' (The Girls' Television).
   An increasing number of prime time newscasts feature women, and
Italian women are becoming prominent in many other fields once
closed to them.
   Women drive Rome's orange-colored buses in bumper-to-bumper
traffic ever more frequently directed by female traffic officers.
   Policewomen wave automatic rifles out the windows of squad cars
as they escort ministers and dignitaries. Until 1981, the national
police force assigned women only to cases involving prostitution or
children.
   Sunday afternoon soccer, that ultimate male bastion, now has a
woman as one of the play-by-play radio commentators. The games are
not televised live.
   When the first woman justice was named to the Supreme Court in
September, she was asked what it meant to enter a world previously
reserved for men.
   ``It signifies that women are present, that they're doing their
job,'' Maria Gabriella Luccioli said. She began her judicial career
in 1963, when women were permitted to become magistrates.
   Marisa Occhionero, a Rome University sociologist who has done
studies for the government on the future of women, said the movement
into top positions is increasing and remains merely a ``question of
time.''
   ``Professors at universities ... engineers, businesswomen,
architects,'' she enumerated. ``They're not content to stay in civil
service jobs. The woman is changing. She has changed. It's the man
who hasn't changed.''
   Women in fields ranging from politics to banking echoed her
comment in interviews. They reported tremendous gains at work but
much less success in persuading men to help mind the house and
children.
   A survey of city families with both spouses working found the men
put in an average of 3-5 hours a week at such chores as home repairs
and cleaning the car while women did 33-35 hours of housework.
   Carole Beebe Tarantelli, an American who serves in the
Parliament, said changing sex roles are difficult for an Italian man
``whose mother would respond to every whim.''
   Newly married Italian men often are dismayed to discover that
their wives, working or not, will not iron their underwear like
their mothers did.
   ``The Italian woman's (struggle) is especially hard'' because of
the importance placed on the family and the concept of the mother as
its pillar, Ms. Occhionero said.
   It often is difficult to run an Italian family, given the
structure of Italian society, especially for working mothers.
   Mrs. Tarantelli, a mother, noted that public schools don't have
team sports or other extracurricular activities. That means
babysitters for children who finish classes at 1 p.m., five or six
hours before parents finish work.
   Stores close three hours for lunch and only a few stay open past
8 p.m. In the Tuscan hilltown of Arezzo, complaints by factory
workers that the only day care center shut down before the factory
did prompted the town to open another with more suitable hours.
   Gioia Longo, a cultural anthropologist who founded a hotline for
abused women, said a survey she did of 700 teen-agers in an Adriatic
resort town indicated girls see no limits on possible achievement
but boys are confused about their changing roles.
   Ms. Occhionero said stereotypical Latin males ``are afraid of
these women. They want to protect them but don't understand to what
point, (and) they are threatened.''
   Stefania Zappanico, a journalist in her 20s, says many women
don't help their cause.
   ``Italian women are still different from northern European or
American women,'' said Ms. Zappanico, who has spent time in Britain
and the United States. ``They're not mentally independent. Even
women who work think they have to depend on men. They don't value
independence that much in itself.''
   In a nationwide study of women's lot in the 1870s, the first
years of a unified Italy, an official in Bari said ``an ass, an ox,
a sheep are always worth more than a wife to the peasant, and the
wife obeys her husband like a slave.''
   A simple rendezvous could get a wife convicted of adultery a
brief generation ago but a husband could be prosecuted only if he
brought his lover to live in the house. A 1969 Supreme Court
decision led to adultery being abolished as a crime for either sex.
   Birth control pills were legalized in the early 1970s and
abortion in 1978.
   Children of an Italian man who marries a foreigner always have
qualified for citizenship automatically, but those of a woman in the
same situation did not qualify until 1984.
   Dictator Benito Mussolini thought a woman's place was home making
babies, but some historians feel his policy of getting women out of
the workplace helped them in the long run because many enrolled in
universities when they could not get jobs.
   As more and more Italian women enter politics, their issues are
certain to get more attention. Ms. Occhionero said women are ``ever
more present'' in the field but still scarce ``in proportion to
their effort.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Dec. 14</NOTE>
</DOC>
