<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1348EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s a BC-Gorby'sApple Adv11   12-09 1016</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Gorby's Apple, Adv11,1037</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Dec. 11, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reporter's Notebook: Gorby Bites the Big Apple</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HUGH A. MULLIGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On his suddenly shortened visit, Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev achieved every out-of-towner's dream of making
it big in the Big Apple. He saw his name in lights on Broadway.
   As his 45-car motorcade moved through Times Square at the height
of rush hour, one of those huge news headline display signs flashed
``Welcome, Gorbachev.''
   The chairman of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet got the
friendly message.
   At the corner of 5lst and Broadway, the tank-like Zil limousine
came to a halt, a smiling Gorbachev stepped out and began pressing
the flesh as the crowd chanted ``Gorby! Gorby!''
   His startled security detail, led by bomb squad vans and a legion
of motorcycles, executed an illegal U-turn that further confounded
cross-town traffic already immobilized by ``Gorby-lock.''
   Here are other scenes from a reporter's notebook on the brief
visit of the statesman-tourist from Moscow:
   _ Something like 180,000 commuters heeded Mayor Ed Koch's warning
against coming to town during Gorbachev's visit. The number of
vehicles entering Manhattan by bridge and tunnel dropped 20 percent,
bringing about a new Christmas miracle on 34th Street in the
vicinity of Macy's department store, where a police inspector
observed that traffic was ``no more chaotic than normal.'' The
motorcade's l6-minute dash from the United Nations to South Ferry
was the envy of New York taxi drivers and should qualify as a modern
record in daylight hours. New York's traffic commissars were
serious. They even posted parking meters with signs in Russian:
``Don't Even Think of Parking.''
   _ When the curtains were drawn, the squat, highly polished,
somewhat antiquated Soviet black limousines flown in with Gorbachev
looked as if they had strayed off course from a Mafia funeral along
Mulberry Street. Cabbies, however, had high praise for the Russians
behind the wheel. ``Being wheel man in a motorcade is real
tsuriss,'' said taxi driver Moishe Abramson of Bay Ridge, Brooklyn,
using the Yiddish word for tension and trouble. ``Gorby's visit
buried the old joke we had around the U.N. about a Russian motorcade
being a 10-car pile-up with flags.''
   _ On the ``Tonight Show'' Johnny Carson had a topical gag about
Gorbachev's promised half-million cut in Soviet troop strength:
``Soon the Russians will be down to just one obsolete tank, driven
by Mike Dukakis.''
   _ Coast Guard Capt. Michael Garwin estimated he had made ``6,400
crossings'' on the five-minute Governors Island ferry run before
being grabbed by news anchors Tom Brokaw and Peter Jennings for
prime-time interviews. And with Gorbachev aboard, this was the first
time police frog men in their wet suits had inspected the hull of
the ferry T. Samuel Coursen minutes before lines were cast off.
   _ Two Transit Authority cops amused the crowd outside the New
York Stock Exchange by harmonizing on ``Shultz and Shevardnadze,''
to the tune of ``Some Enchanted Evening,'' while waiting for the
motorcade to roll by the cathedral of capitalism.
   _ Raisa Gorbachev, the style-conscious Soviet first lady who
calls designer Givenchy by his first name of Hubert, helped bury the
cartoon caricature of frumpy Soviet women in galoshes and babushkas.
In a visit to Estee Lauder's Fifth Avenue beauty salon, she was
sprayed with a fragrance called ``White Linen'' by the cosmetic
queen herself, who plans to open a branch soon on Moscow's Gorky
Street. Raisa also made a brief stop outside Bloomigdale's, the
upscale market version of Moscow's Gum department store, but didn't
have time to flash her American Express card.
   According to rumors spread by refuseniks, she never leaves her
dacha without it.
   Some Christmas shoppers like Faye Bernardi of Ozone Park, N.Y.,
thought they detected the ``look of longing in her eyes that we
women get when afflicted with that shop-until-you drop syndrome.''
Or maybe it was the look a Muscovite gets when peering into the
windows of a Beryozka shop, where luxury goods can be bought only
with foreign currency.
   _ Nearly 60 students protesting on behalf of Soviet Jews were
arrested on the final night of Gorbachev's visit, but the number of
demonstrators fell far below what police had anticipated. Among a
variety of ethnic and political dissenters was a small group of
animals lovers fuming against Raisa's broadtail Persian taupe
topcoat and Russian lynx fur hat with signs proclaiming ``minx
stinx.''
   _ The visit, of course, was a media carnival. One of the more
ingenious sideshows featured a Canadian actor, a Gorbachev
look-alike, who conned super capitalist Donald Trump into a hoax
interview after the real Soviet leader had turned down an invitation
to visit his $19 million apartment in Trump Tower.
   _ A yogurt emporium in the alley behind the stock exchange
dressed up its luncheon menu with a message in the Cyrillic
alphabet. Translated it read: ``Have a nice glasnost.''
   _ With Mikhail Gorbachev, Ronald Reagan and George Bush gazing
meaningfully at the Statue of Liberty from Liberty Point, Governors
Island had its most memorable historical happening since Wouter Van
Twiller, the second Dutch governor of the New Netherlands, purchased
the 173-acre tract from local Indians for two axe heads and a
fistful of nails and named it Nutten Island.
   On a sparkling day, the tiny island with its sudden promise of
long sought world peace almost seemed the inspiration for the
closing paragraphs of F. Scott Fitzgerald's ``The Great Gatsby'':
   ``The old island that flowered once for Dutch sailor's eyes _ a
fresh, green breast of the New World. Its vanished trees had once
pandered in whispers to the last and greatest of all human dreams.
For a transitory enchanted moment man must have held his breath in
the presence of this continent, compelled into an aesthetic
contemplation he neither understood nor desired, face to face for
the last time in history with something commensurate to his capacity
for wonder.''
   Around the Big Apple, the Great Gorby made a substantive
contribution to man's capacity for wonder.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Dec. 11</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
