<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former director of the New York Federal
Reserve Bank has been charged with leaking confidential interest
rate information to a securities brokerage.
   Prosecutors said Thursday's indictment was the first insider
trading case involving government securities.
   Robert A. Rough received $47,000 in interest-deferred loans from
the now defunct Bevill, Bresler & Schulman investment firm in
exchange for the information, the indictment charged.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business Week's former broadcast editor has
pleaded guilty to mail fraud in an insider trading scheme, admitting
he illegally used advance material from the magazine to buy and sell
securities.
   Seymour G. ``Rudy'' Ruderman on Thursday admitted making $15,000
between January 1986 and last July in securities trades, using
not-yet-published information from upcoming issues of the nation's
biggest business weekly.
   The editor waived indictment and pleaded guilty to two counts of
mail fraud before U.S. District Judge Robert Ward. He faces a
maximum penalty of five years in prison and $250,000 in fines on
each count.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bankers will reap more than $700 million in fees
for their participation in history's largest deal, according to
government documents filed in the wake of the $24.53 billion buyout
of RJR Nabisco Inc.
   Documents filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission
suggest investment and commercial bankers would get as much as
$711.88 million in fees for arranging financing for Kohlberg's $109
cash-and-securities offer for each share of RJR stock.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All three measures of the nation's money supply
rose in late November, the Federal Reserve Board reported.
   The Fed said Thursday the narrowest measure of the money supply,
M1, rose $3.1 billion to a seasonally adjusted $787.8 billion in the
week ended Nov. 28 from $784.7 billion the previous week.
   The central bank said a broader measure known as M2 rose $3.7
billion to a seasonally adjusted $3,061.9 billion from $3,058.2
billion.
   An even broader measure, M3, increased $1.9 billion to a
seasonally adjusted $3,896.7 billion from $3,894.8 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1988 Christmas shopping season is off to a
modestly good start, although retailers in some parts of the country
report warmer weather has put a damper on their holiday spirits.
   ``We're doing fine _ right on target,'' Miraed Smith, a
spokeswoman at Bloomingdale's flagship store in Manhattan, said
Thursday.
   Securities analysts who track the industry said the first two
weeks of the season have been good, and they are optimistic
retailers will have moderately strong increases from the dismal
performance of Christmas 1987.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   TW Services Inc. has again recommended that its
shareholders reject a $1.14 billion takeover offer from Coniston
Partners, calling the bid for the food services company too low.
   TW Services also urged shareholders Thursday to withdraw any
shares already tendered in the bid, which Coniston has amended to
$29 a share in cash for the 81 percent of the company it does not
already own.
   The tender offer is scheduled to expire next Tuesday.
</TEXT>
