<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Their top salesman was missing, but Soviet
entrepreneurs went ahead with the opening of an unprecedented trade
show intended to usher in a new era of Soviet-U.S. commerce.
   As fashion models showed off the latest trends from Moscow
Thursday to the beat of American pop music, Soviet executives showed
off their wares, including furs, tractors, vodka, books, toys, cars,
guns and caviar.
   Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev had been scheduled to open the
trade fair. But his appearance was scrubbed when he decided to
return to Moscow early because of a catastrophic earthquake in
Soviet Armenia.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. corporations paid one-fourth of their
earnings in federal income taxes last year, up 15 percent since
income tax laws were overhauled in 1986, private analysts say.
   Three-fourths of 1,000 corporations surveyed by Tax Analysts, a
research and publishing organization, paid higher taxes in 1987 than
in 1986. As a group, they contributed about $7 billion more to the
federal treasury.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota unveiled a new luxury auto
nameplate, rolling out two new models designed to lure yuppies
graduating from economy imports and compete with top-drawer European
sports sedans.
   The cars, introduced Thursday, are part of the Lexus line, which
will be a division of Toyota Motor Sales U.S.A. Inc., the American
arm of Japan's Toyota Motor Corp.
   In the manner of Honda's Acura, Toyota will try to establish a
separate, upscale identity for Lexus in part through design, price
and advertising, and in part by selling them through a separate
dealer network.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Research and development spending by industry,
government, universities and non-profit organizations will increase
4.6 percent next year, but inflation will account for most of the
rise, a magazine says.
   Research & Development magazine projects in its January issue
that $130.8 billion will spent on research next year, compared to an
estimated $125 billion for 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If federal bureacrats have their way, 3{ tons of
edible roasted beef will be destroyed because it might be too chewy
to live up to the ``choice'' grade given by a meat processor.
   There are no provisions in U.S. Department of Agriculture rules
to let the meat go to a charity, even in the spirit of the holiday
season, according to government attorneys.
   In a civil lawsuit filed Tuesday under the name ``U.S. v. 7,007
Pounds of Cooked Roast Beef,'' the USDA seeks the forfeiture of the
504 roasts, prepared at Max Bauer Meat Packers, a wholesale
distributor supplying other South Florida distributors and markets.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market lost ground Thursday as the Gorbachev-inspired
rally faded, pushing the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials down
11.92 points to 2,141.71.
   The dollar retreated against other major currencies.
   Bond prices were narrowly mixed in quiet trading.
   Copper futures prices soared to record highs, energy futures fell
sharply, precious-metals futures slipped, livestock and meat prices
dipped, and grains and soybeans rose.
