<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     12-09 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mostly Lower After Flirting With $16 Level</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Technical factors and concerns about production
have sent crude oil futures sharply lower.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the January contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, settled
30 cents lower Thursday at $15.44 a barrel, after rising 28 cents on
Wednesday. Other contract months also declined.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange Thursday,
the January contract for wholesale home heating oil closed 0.81 cent
lower at 48.08 cents a gallon. The contract had risen 0.29 cent
Wednesday.
   But January unleaded gasoline, which lost 0.59 cent on Wednesday,
settled at 43.93 cents a gallon, up 0.17 cent from Wednesday's
session.
   Peter Beutel, an energy analyst with Elders Futures Inc., said
prices started out strong, with the January contract for West Texas
Intermediate trading as high as $15.97 a barrel. But when the
contract failed to pierce the psychologically important $16-a-barrel
level, a selloff began, he said.
   ``As the price approached the $16 level they (traders) found
themselves asking themselves whether the market was bullish enough
to merit that price,'' Beutel explained. ``They came to the
realization that it was not as strong fundamentally.''
   Beutel said recent reports of higher-than-expected oil production
have concerned many traders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881209-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 0037EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Soviet-Business Bjt   12-09 0921</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Business, Bjt,0949</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`The Russians Are Coming' Is History: They've Been Here for Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail Gorbachev's peacemaking New York visit
and the opening of a glitzy Soviet trade show underscored the
importance the Kremlin leader attaches to developing business and
commercial ties in the West.
   But perhaps unknown to many Westerners, the Communist superpower
has long been dabbling in overseas ventures that range from currency
speculation in London to fish canning in North America.
   While Gorbachev may reduce the Soviet military, as he pledged in
a speech at the United Nations, experts on the Soviet bloc said they
believe his broader reforms likely will make the Soviets much more
aggressive in foreign investing, exporting and competing for
customers in an increasingly global economy.
   ``They're beginning to talk about more direct investment abroad,
focused on firms that might help them market their own products,''
said Edward Hewitt, a Soviet economics expert at the Brookings
Institution, a Washington research organization. ``I wouldn't be at
all surprised if they come in and buy out some small European or
U.S. firms in the next few years.''
   The Soviets have not acquired any significant Western companies
yet, but the number of foreign firms owned wholly or partly by the
Soviets has risen sharply from about a dozen in the early 1960s to
more than 120 now, said Carl McMillan, a Soviet expert at Carleton
University in Ottawa.
   McMillan, who has compiled a list of Soviet bloc-owned companies
in the West for the past 10 years, said many of these ventures
reflect a growing sophistication about investing abroad.
   ``There are different ways in which they do it,'' he said. ``They
have assets, portfolios and direct investments. They're in a wide
range of business areas: banks, insurance, engineering, shipping and
commercial companies.''
   The Soviet investment presence abroad remains minuscule by
Western standards, however, considering that just one U.S. or
Japanese conglomerate might have 120 foreign subsidiaries. Still,
the Soviets appear to be catching on.
   ``As they participate in the world economy, they've found this is
the way everybody else plays the game,'' McMillan said.
   In Scandinavia, for example, the Soviets have established a chain
of government-owned service stations to sell one of their biggest
exports, petroleum.
   On this side of the world, the Soviets have stakes in two North
American fishing and fish-processing concerns, Cansov Marine
Products Ltd. in Nova Scotia and Marine Resources Co. International
in Seattle.
   As one of the largest producers of agricultural machinery and
equipment, the Soviets have long been in the business of selling
tractors. In 1972, they formed Belarus Equipment of Canada Ltd., a
Toronto-based marketer of Soviet farm vehicles. A U.S. branch was
formed five years later, with offices in New York and Milwaukee.
   ``I would say this sort of trend will continue, and under
Gorbachev it will be more dynamic,'' said McMillan. ``I don't think
`The Russians Are Coming' thing really fits. They've been around for
awhile.''
   The Soviets also are veteran participants in the world's
speculative foreign-exchange markets, trading largely through two
government-owned banks, Moscow Norodny in London and the Eurobank in
Paris. Each is believed to have about $5 billion in assets.
   Because the ruble is not a convertible currency, the Soviets must
use Western money in order to pay for goods imported from
non-communist trading parters. As with other currency speculators,
the Soviets like to move their holdings into the currency that is
worth the most at any given time.
   They are said to favor the Swiss franc, although they also have
deposits and trading accounts denominated in dollars, British
pounds, West German marks and Japanese yen.
   ``They used to be into wild speculation, but they're more careful
now,'' said Jan Vanous, a Soviet expert at Planecon, a
Washington-based consulting and information concern that studies the
centrally planned economies of the Soviet bloc.
   A few years ago, for example, Soviet traders attempted to push
down the value of the Swiss franc by dumping $50 million worth of
francs in 20 separate orders throughout Europe, assuming dealers
would not be able to communicate fast enough about who was selling.
The Soviets were wrong, losing money and respect.
   ``It really caused a lot of bad blood,'' Vanous said. ``You do
this to someone in the foreign-exchange market, and the next time
they deal with you they're extra careful.''
   Some traders have privately accused the Soviets of eavesdropping
on international telephone lines for advance word on central bank
coordination and intervention, which often moves a currency sharply.
   The Moscow Norodny bank, for example, is believed to have once
made huge profits on marks it bought just before the mark soared in
value after the West German Bundesbank made a surprise policy shift.
   That change resulted from a telephone conversation hours earlier
between aides from the Bundesbank and the Federal Reserve in
Washington, and according to one widely circulated story the Soviets
learned about it through a wiretap.
   On the other hand, the Soviets can show remarkable naivete about
economic trends that hurt their currency holdings. They were active
buyers of dollars just before the currency tumbled because of a
coordination agreement by the leading Western democracies and the
collapse of oil prices a few years ago.
   ``Generally they are savvy in the short run, but they don't do
too well in the long run,'' said Vanous. ``They are miserable in
making forecasts. They don't have the trained people, the
information, and keep making judgments based on their own behavior.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
