<1ST_LINE>a f BC-TickerTalk Adv12   12-09 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ticker Talk, Adv 12,0619</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 12</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Dec. 12</NOTE>
<HEAD>Hunting For Gold in Wall Street's Scrap Heap</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prime time is at hand for a special brand of
holiday shopping that has become a tradition of sorts on Wall Street.
   Stock analysts and traders are busily combing the markets for
issues trading at or near their lowest levels of the year.
   The idea is to buy these stocks while they are artificially
depressed by yearend sell orders _ from individual investors looking
for tax writeoffs and from institutions clearing the losers out of
their portfolios before they make yearend reports to clients.
   Once the pressure of this selling is removed with the arrival of
the new year, the reasoning goes, these stocks stand a good chance
of rebounding, even if the financial affairs of the companies
involved don't change much.
   In his annual Stock Trader's Almanac, investment adviser Yale
Hirsch describes the list of stocks trading at new 52-week lows
around Dec. 15 as a menu for ``the only free lunch on Wall Street.''
   For most of the time in the past 15 years, according to Hirsch's
research, the New York Stock Exchange issues at new lows on Dec. 15
outperformed the NYSE composite index through the following Feb. 15.
   Last winter, for example, the 23 new lows posted an aggregate
gain of 13.2 percent over the two-month period, compared to a 6.8
percent rise for the NYSE index.
   Occasionally, however, the ``free lunch'' is more famine than
feast. The four new lows at mid-December 1985, which included three
energy-related issues, suffered an overall loss of 22.5 percent by
the next Feb. 15 as oil prices nosedived.
   In addition, small investors armed with limited capital face
problems turning this historical trend into a workable trading
strategy.
   Brokerage commissions take their considerable toll. And if a
trader doesn't have enough money to buy a diversified package of the
stocks at new lows, which ones to pick?
   The December bargain hunt does dovetail nicely with a phenomenon
known as the ``January effect'' that has been widely analyzed in
academic studies and at least one book.
   This research has documented a tendency for stocks, especially
those of smaller companies, to show unusual strength in the first
few weeks of the year.
   The only trouble with the January effect, analysts say, is the
very recognition it has received. Once market patterns become well
known, they often quickly change as traders try to capitalize on
them.
   Thus the suspicion among a good many Wall Streeters that the
January effect will soon be negated, or at least moved into December.
   Whether or not they prove to be ``bargains,'' many of the lists
of depressed stocks being published these days contain a surprising
number of big names.
   For example, at Oppenheimer & Co., analysts Norman Weinger and
Michael Metz ran a computer screen of stocks with market values of
at least $50 million, priced at no more than 10 percent above their
52-week lows, and carrying price-earnings multiples of no more than
10.
   The names that turned up included Digital Equipment, Xerox, Texas
Instruments, NCR and several technology issues that once ranked as
leading glamour stocks.
   Blue-chip industrial companies? How about DuPont, Goodyear and
Weyerhaueser, for starters.
   ``No investment decision is warranted on the basis of these
figures alone,'' Weinger and Metz cautioned. For a further
observation, they added: ``It is interesting to note how many stocks
are still down sharply'' in the aftermath of the October 1987 crash.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Dec 12</NOTE>
