<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Drexel     12-09 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Drexel,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Say Another Drexel Trader Turns State's Evidence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. bond trader has
agreed to cooperate with federal prosecutors probing the Wall Street
firm for possible securities fraud, the second employee to turn
state's evidence this week.
   Sources familiar with the Drexel case, who spoke on condition
they not be identified, confirmed a report Friday that Terren Pizer,
who worked on the bond trading desk at the firm's Beverly Hills
office, agreed late Wednesday to provide evidence in exchange for
immunity from prosecution.
   Pizer sat near Michael Milken, Drexel's high-yield bond financier
and a key target of the federal investigation that has lasted more
than two years, an outgrowth of the Ivan Boesky insider trading
scandal.
   Drexel, Milken and two other employees have been accused by the
Securities and Exchange Commission of conspiring with Boesky to
commit frauds that range from trading on inside information to stock
manipulation. Now imprisoned, Boesky has been the government's key
source of evidence in the case.
   A Manhattan federal grand jury has been investigating the firm on
similar grounds and has been expected to indict Drexel, Milken and
the others for months. The defendants have maintained their
innocence, although Drexel has been negotiating with prosecutors
about a possible settlement.
   The Wall Street Journal reported Friday that Pizer's cooperation
reflected a tougher negotiating stance by the government and
intensified pressure on Drexel to capitulate in order to avoid a
possibly devastating indictment that would include charges of
racketeering, which carry enormous fines.
   But it was unclear what, if any, incriminating material Pizer
could provide.
   Spokesmen for Drexel and Milken declined to comment on the
development. Aides to Manhattan U.S. attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani
also declined to comment in accordance with their policy of silence
on pending investigations.
   Pizer's agreement came one day after another key figure in the
investigation, Milken aide Cary Maultasch, struck a plea bargain
with prosecutors. But the effect of Maultasch's cooperation also
remains unclear.
</TEXT>
