<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Salomon-Charge     12-09 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Salomon-Charge,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salomon Inc. To Take $150 Million Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salomon Inc. said it plans to shift $1.1 billion
from a Swiss subsidiary to its U.S. operations and take a $150
million tax charge against fourth-quarter earnings.
   The announcement Thursday marks a major restructuting of
Salomon's $3.6 billion capital and triggered some speculation that
the investment banking firm may be preparing a stock buyback or
major acquisition.
   Robert Salomon, a managing director, said the move would reduce
the capital of the Swiss unit to $600 million from $1.7 billion. He
said $750 million would be repatriated immediately and $350 million
at a later date.
   The company said it is taking the charge against earnings because
it had not set aside money to pay taxes on the additional income.
   Salomon said returning the foreign earnings to the United States
would give the company greater flexibility
   He said the move also would allow Salomon to use certain foreign
tax credits that expire at year's end. Foreign tax credits typically
allow firms to repatriate foreign earnings at a lower U.S. tax rate.
   Salomon's Zug, Switzerland, unit, the commercial financial
division, was established six years ago for tax purposes by Philipp
Brothers, a commodities firm that merged with Salomon.
</TEXT>
