<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Lorimar-Warner     12-09 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Lorimar-Warner,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Warners Loses Appeal in Lorimar Acquisition Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state appeals court has upheld a lower court
ruling that blocked Warner Communications Inc.'s proposed $1.2
billion acquisition of Lorimar Telepictures Inc.
   However, Warner said it expected to complete the deal next month.
   The Appellate Division of State Supreme Court on Thursday
affirmed a decision that the merger violated a 1984 agreement
between Warner and its largest stockholder, Christ-Craft Industries
Inc., a broadcasting and manufacturing company.
   At issue in the case are Lorimar's televison stations.
Chris-Craft claimed in a suit filed in July that because Lorimar
owned six stations, the merger violated a 4-year-old pact
prohibiting Warner from owning any TV station so long as it owned 25
percent or more of Chris-Craft's BHC Inc. broadcasting subsidiary.
   Warner acquired a 42.5 percent stake in BHC in 1984 in exchange
for Chris- Craft getting 23 percent of Warner's voting stock.
   The appeals court upheld a a ruling that said Warner could not
acquire any Lorimar stock until the TV stations were sold or it
reduced its stake in BHC.
   But Warner said it was moving ahead despite the setback. ``We
have been working on alternatives and it is our intent to consummate
the transaction in January,'' the company said in a statement.
   Since the Chris-Craft suit was filed, Lorimar completed the sale
of television stations in Odessa, Texas; Springfield, Mo.; and
Redding, Calif., to a partnership that includes a former Lorimar
executive.
   It also reached an agreement in principle to sell a fourth
station in Pittsburgh, but two independent stations in Puerto Rico
remain on the auction block.
   Warner contends the proposed merger would not violate the
agreement with Chris-Craft because Warner planned to set up an
independent trust, pending approval from the Federal Communications
Commission, to run the remaining stations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
