<DOCNO> AP881209-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1124EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-US-EECHormones     12-09 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-EEC Hormones,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Official Says Hormone Ban Will Go Into Effect</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Trade Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community said Friday that
a ban on the imports of hormone-treated meat from the United States
will go into effect next month.
   The ban, implementation of which was postponed for one year at
the request of the United States, could provoke a trade war with
Washington.
   EEC spokesman Nicolas Wegter also said the 12-nation EEC only
would agree to international arbitration of the dispute with the
United States if consumer-related arguments as well as scientific
ones are taken into account.
   The ban legislated by the EEC, which goes into effect Jan. 1,
would affect $170 million of U.S. meat exports. This does not
include about $72 million of horsemeat, which is not treated with
hormones.
   EEC and U.S. negotiators were expected to have an opportunity to
discuss possible solutions to the dispute when they met here this
week for a ministerial conference of the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade.
   But a U.S.-EEC clash over support for farmers prevented the
discussion from taking place. The matter will also not be taken up
at a bilateral meeting of ministers taking place in Brussels Friday
because the U.S. and EEC agriculture negotiators had to stay in
Montreal longer than expected and did not get to Belgium in time.
   ``We don't care what the Americans want for their consumers,''
said Wegter. ``Our legislation goes into effect and we will apply
it.''
   A European Parliament investigation of reports that European
farmers violate the legislation and treat their animals with
hormones will not affect implementation of the ban, he said.
   The council of the GATT, which oversees implementation of the
1947 treaty regulating world trade, is scheduled to meet Dec. 20 to
consider a U.S. request for establishing an arbitration pnel.
   Wegter said the EEC would only accept the arbitration panel if it
``doesn't rely just on scientific arguments but also on
consumer-related and other arguments.'' He said most EEC members
already had legislated bans on hormone-treated meat, ``and they
think it's good for their consumers.''
   The United States insists that hormones used on animals do not
leave residues that are harmful to humans. Some European scientists
have concurred, while others have argued that the hormones can cause
cancer.
   The United States could retaliate against the meat ban with one
of its own against European meat exports, which consist mostly of
high quality items like Danish ham.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
