<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade on pre-weekend profit-taking and
disappointment over the Agriculture Department's rejection of
China's bid for a large wheat shipment.
   The Chinese bid Wednesday for 400,000 of the 1 million metric
tons of U.S. wheat that exporters recently were authorized to sell
them at subsidized prices under the USDA's Export Enhancement
Program. The markets learned early today that the USDA had rejected
China's initial tender.
   ``But I am told they will rebid, so I don't think we'll lose very
much ground,'' said Dale Gustafson, a grain-market analyst with
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   Soybean prices were pressured by conflicting reports about the
amount of overnight rainfall in the South American soybean belt, he
said.
   Corn prices were mixed, with support stemming from strong cash
markets and a positive export outlook.
