<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1251EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-TradeTalks-Japan 1stLd-Writethru   12-09 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade Talks-Japan, 1st Ld-Writethru,0502</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with European official saying Japan was silent on
agriculture talks, edits throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assochated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter
declared himself satisfied with Japan's role in internatonal trade
talks here and said he would reject a petition by American farmers
to demand access to the Japanese rice market.
   But a spokesman for the 12-nation European Economic Community,
Nicolas Wegter, said Friday that ``the Japanese didn't say one word
the entire week about agriculture.''
   Yeutter had told reporters that the Japanese delegation to the
ministeral meeting of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
``performed superbly.'' ``They handled themselves skillfully,'' he
added. ``It was a first class performance.''
   Japan, the world's largest net importer of agricultural products,
sat in on six days of talks between the EEC, the United States and
the world's leading farm exporters.
   ``I didn't hear the translators translate one word from Japanese
into agriculture,'' Wegter told reporters.
   The divergence of views reflected attempts by the EEC and the
United States to curry Japan's favor in their battle over
agricultural subsidies.
   Yeutter, asked whether he would accept a petition by the U.S.
Rice Millers Association, responded, ``I will not.''
   Several weeks ago Yeutter rejected a petition by the American
rice producers' group which called on the U.S. government to
investigate whether Japan is employing unfair trade practices in
refusing to open its rice market to imports.
   In turning down the petition, Yeutter said he hoped the rice
question would be resolved in Montreal and if not the farmers could
resubmit their appeal.
   Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party, concerned with the
veiled threat of U.S. pressure, sent a delegation to Montreal to
make sure the foreign ministry negotiators did not cave in to
demands on the rice issue.
   But much to Japan's relief, the subject was virtually not
mentioned during the six days of talks, which were dominated by the
U.S.-EEC clash on farm supports.
   The United States is seeking farm subsidy elimination, while the
EEC is only willing to cut down the supports. The talks ended in
stalemate.
   Japan said it did not take sides in the clash.
   ``Our position is that there is no point in making decisions
until they settle,'' said Mutsuyoshi Nishimura, Japan's director of
foreign press relations.
   Nishimura said that whatever the outcome, Japan's prime concern
is the protection of its rice market against foreign imports.
   The administration appears content to allow the rice issue to
rest as long as Japan leaves it on the table for future negotiations.
   Japanese rice is about four times more expensive than U.S. rice,
but Japan is insistent on complete self-reliance in production of
the staple crop.
   The Rice Millers were demanding a quota of up to 2.5 percent of
the Japanese market the first year, which would rise to 10 percent
in the fourth year.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>END</HEAD>
