<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ComputerExtortion     12-09 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Computer Extortion,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Men Accused Of Computer Extortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men have been charged with attempted
extortion in a series of death threat letters sent to prominent
Antelope Valley citizens.
   Although the two unemployed aerospace workers are suspected of
sending 265 computer-printed threats, they were charged with only 10
specific acts to simplify the case, Deputy District Attorney Steve
Cooley said Thursday.
   ``Many of the letters were identical,'' said Cooley, but he noted
that the text of each letter was ``customized'' to include personal
information about the intended victims.
   Roman Stephan Makuch, 27, and Richard Mathew Faroni, 26, were
arrested in Las Vegas on Thanksgiving Day and waived extradition.
   Letters attached to the complaint began with an obscenity and a
death threat. The writers then demanded specific amounts of cash as
high as $600,000 with instructions for its delivery. They also gave
gruesome details of how victims would be killed, and threatened harm
to children, spouses and relatives of the letter recipients, Cooley
said.
   Those targeted by the letter writers, he said, were all
``substantial people'' including a former city manager of Lancaster,
lawyers, bank vice presidents, doctors, dentists, accountants and
real estate agents.
   None of them paid any money, he said.
   The letters, received Nov. 2-3, told some recipients to take a
citizens band radio to Las Vegas and tune in a specific channel for
instructions on where to deliver money.
   Cooley said a search of a Las Vegas apartment occupied by Makuch
and Faroni and a nearby storage facility turned up computer,
printers and computer discs, a handgun and several CB radios.
   He said acquaintances said about the pair: ``They could be
characterized as being a couple of oddballs, misfits.''
   Cooley added, ``there is some indication there may be other
people involved.''
   Makuch and Faroni were unemployed but had worked previously on
the assembly line at Rockwell International's Palmdale plant on the
B-1B bomber project, Cooley said.
   Both were charged with conspiracy to commit extortion, attempted
extortion and sending threatening letters for extortion purposes. If
convicted, Cooley said they could draw maximum sentences of six
years in prison.
</TEXT>
