<HEAD>No. 2 Man Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The second-ranking executive at Beecham
Products USA, maker of Aqua-Fresh toothpaste, Sucrets lozenges,
Geritol vitamins and Williams Lectric Shave lotion, resigned in a
move that could influence where the headquarters will be located.
   The exit of Robert M. Lancaster as executive vice president for
sales and marketing followed a proposed corporate realignment that
eliminates his position.
   The British parent, Beecham Group PLC, intends to merge Beecham
USA with its other U.S. subsidiary, Norcliff-Thayer of Tarrytown,
N.Y., maker of Tums antacids and Oxy acne medications.
   Lancaster, a 15-year veteran of the company, favored keeping
Beecham USA in Pittsburgh, where 400 employees oversee
administration, sales, marketing, research and customer services.
   Lancaster's boss, President Charles Pergola, wanted the issue to
be decided by a study that also is determining the best way to carry
out the merger.
   ``Having been through the changes we've been through, it isn't
unusual for people in this position to have philosophical
disagreements,'' Maurice L. Kelley, vice president for sales and
marketing, said Thursday.
   Lancaster joined the company as national accounts manager while
it was part of Merck & Co. Merck sold the business to Beecham in
1977.
   Beecham undertook the study in September shortly after Pergola
became Beecham USA's third president in three years.
   The company spent $10 million two years ago constructing a
95,000-square-foot headquarters building outside Pittsburgh in
Kennedy Township.
</TEXT>
