<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished lower on London's Stock
Exchange Friday, but above their worst levels, lifted by a strong
trend on Wall Street and the start of a new trading account.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 7.6
points, or 0.4 percent, lower at 1,750.3, well above the day's low
of 20 points off. However the market never recovered to its best
level of 3.6 points up.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed 7.7 points lower at
1,429.4.
   Volume was a moderate 637.1 million shares up from 543.8 million
shares a day earlier.
   Dealers said the market remained preoccupied through most of the
trading session by the prospects for higher interest rates
worldwide, focusing on Friday on unconfirmed rumors that West German
interest rates may be increased next week.
   The interest rate worries about Germany added to the market's
longstanding concern about the effect on British corporate
profitability of recent British base lending rate increases.
   But toward the close, a strong trend on Wall Street, and the 3:30
p.m. start of a new trading account lifted the market from its lows
toward the close.
   The exchange divides trading into two-week and three-week periods
for accounting purposes.
   The Financial Times 500-share index fell 6.24 points to 981.56 at
the close.
