<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1425EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Spain-Railroads     12-09 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Railroads,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spain Approves Railway System Overhaul</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spain on Friday adopted Europe's standard
width for railroad tracks, a step that will allow trains to roll
directly into western Europe for the first time since track was laid
133 years ago.
   The move clears the way for completion of high-speed train links
with Europe by 1992, when Spain hosts the Summer Olympics and
celebrates the 500th anniversary of Christopher Columbus' discovery
of the New World.
   The government next week is expected to award a major contract to
build Spain's first high-speed train system. French, West German and
Japanese firms are bidding for the deal.
   The first phase of the changeover to the narrower European tracks
would permit construction of a high-speed line from Port Bou on
Spain's northern border with France to Barcelona, Madrid and Seville.
   By the turn of the century, the 5.5-foot-wide Spanish and
Portuguese tracks would be replaced with 4.7-foot-wide track used in
10 other European Economic Community nations.
   Transport Minister Jose Barrionuevo said the France-to-Seville
line should be ready by the opening of Seville's World Expo in
spring 1992 to commemorate the Columbus anniversary and the 1992
Barcelona Summer Olympics.
   The government also ordered the state rail company, RENFE, to
study replacing the rest of the country's 7,887 miles of rail track
by 2001.
   It is widely believed that Spanish railways were given a narrower
gauge than the rest of Europe when first built in 1855 to make a
military invasion of the Iberian peninsula more difficult.
   Engineers maintained that a wider gauge was necessary to
accommodate locomotives that carried trains across Spain's
mountainous terrain.
   Now, wheels on railway cars from Spain and Portugal must be
changed or modified at the Spanish-French border.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
