<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Finish Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower while most corn and oat futures advanced slightly in subdued
trading Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Analysts attributed the declines to profit-taking and positioning
ahead of the weekend.
   They said wheat also fell on disappointment that the Agriculture
Department had rejected China's bid for 400,000 metric tons of U.S.
wheat at subsidized prices.
   Soybeans came under additional pressure from mixed forecasts for
the weekend weather in the South American soybean belt, analysts
said.
   ``Two (private) forecasters were predicting rain and another one
said it wasn't going to rain so they've got some confusion going in
the beans,'' said Jerry Gidel, an analyst with the G.H. Miller
futures trading division of LIT America Inc. in Chicago.
   Corn futures were buoyed by expectations for increased export
sales, analysts said.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 4\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.27 a bushel; corn was 2
cents lower to 2} cents higher with December at $2.59{; oats were 2
cents to 3} cents higher with December at $2.05} a bushel; soybeans
were 3 cents lower to 1{ cents higher with January at $7.73 a bushel.
