<NOTE>$adv 11</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 10-11</NOTE>
<HEAD>Is the Yield Curve Changing Course?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the world of credit, ``short'' is most
definitely in fashion these days, at least from an investor's
standpoint.
   Yields on some bills and notes, particularly in the Treasury
market, have nearly equaled or surpassed those on longer maturing
bonds more so now than at any other time this year. That makes it
far more sensible to hold onto the shorter securities.
   Usually it's the other way around. Long-term rates often are
significantly higher to compensate investors for their increased
risk.
   For instance, it's more likely that someone will renege on a
30-year debt than on one lasting three months. There's also
increased risk of higher interest rates, which depress a bond's
price, and higher inflation, which reduce its real value.
   But now the so-called yield curve, which illustrates the
difference between short- and long-term interest rates, appears to
be changing. Normally in an upward, or ``J'' position, the curve,
which has been flat for most of the year, looks close to inverting.
   By midday Friday, the yield on the Treasury's bellwether 30-year
bond stood at 8.96 percent, lower than the yields of all other bonds
and notes of lesser maturities. The 20-year bond was yielding 9.02
percent; the 10-year, 9.01 percent; the four-year, 9.00 percent; and
the two-year, 8.99 percent.
   Treasury bill yields remained a bit lower, however. A quick
measure of the curve is the relationship between the three-month
bill and the 30-year bond. By Friday afternoon the long bond was
0.79 percentage points higher than the bill. The gap, though, was
closing in on the one-year bill, which was yielding 8.90 percent.
   When the yield curve is in a positive, upward steep the long bond
is usually between 1{- to 2 percentage points higher in yield.
   The yield curve theoretically should reflect the expectations of
borrowers and investors. One that ascends steeply indicates that the
markets expect interest rates and inflation to rise; it also
portrays ``easy'' money.
   The last time the curve inverted was around 1981. The stock
market fell into a slump as a result and the nation headed into a
recession.
   Market watchers aren't sure what the current movement of rates
means.
   Jay Goldinger, a principal at the Beverly Hills, Calif.,
investment banking firm Capital Insight Inc., said he expects the
yield curve to continue to invert but that the economy shouldn't
suffer as a result.
   ``What it (the inversion) really means is inflation expectations
in this country continue to be reduced as the Fed has done a good
job of tightening'' credit, Goldinger said.
   ``This is nothing unusual. We have an inverted yield curve in
England and in Australia,'' he explained. ``The central banks of
this world really pay attention in focusing in on inflation fears.''
   Marshall B. Front, an economist at the Chicago investment firm
Stein Roe & Farnham, predicted that rates might be heading lower
soon because the economy is showing signs of slowing down.
   While short-term rates certainly are attractive now _ not just in
Treasuries, but in things like certificates of deposits or money
market accounts _ Front says he's gradually sinking his money into
longer-maturing securities.
   ``Our own guess is that we're fairly close to a peak in
short-term rates. We could see a decline in rates before the end of
the first quarter,'' Front said.
   If that happens, then bond prices will head higher.
   ``We don't think we'll have a repeat of the last few cycles where
you had a sharply inverted yield curve,'' Front said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 10-11</NOTE>
</DOC>
