<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Plessey,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GEC and Siemens To Delay Formal Offer For Plessey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. PLC and Siemens AG said Friday
they would delay their 1.7 billion-pound, or $3.1 billion, joint bid
for the British electronics firm Plessey Co. PLC pending a high
court hearing late next week.
   Plessey on Thursday obtained a preliminary injunction from the
High Court blocking the offer before a full court hearing on whether
the bid infringes on the anti-competition provisions of the Treaty
of Rome.
   Plessey said the injunction was dropped by the court on Friday
after GEC and Siemens pledged not to pursue their bid before the
full hearing. The matter is now likely to come before the court next
Thursday and Friday, Plessey said.
   GEC, a British company, which is not related to the U.S. company
of the same name, said it intends to contest Plessey's arguments.
   Siemens is a West German concern.
   Plessey argued that the GEC-Siemens bid is anti-competitive and
illegal and allegedly contravenes the anti-trust provisions of the
Treaty of Rome, the European Community's founding charter.
   The EC commission is also investigating the bid, but has not yet
announced its decision.
</TEXT>
