<DOCNO> AP881209-0230 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1618EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-UnbundledStocks     12-09 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unbundled Stocks,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Security Aimed at Unbundling Stock Value</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-New Security</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a capsule description of an unbundled
stock unit, a new type of security developed by Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc.
   Four major companies _ American Express Co., Sara Lee Corp.,
Pfizer Inc. and Dow Chemical Co. _ have announced plans, subject to
federal review, to exchange up to $5.6 billion of their stock for
unbundled stock units.
   The new securities consist of:
   _A 30-year bond that pays interest equal to the current stock
dividend and carrying a face value payable in 2019 higher than the
current stock price.
   Under the preliminary proposal, for instance, American Express's
bond would pay 84 cents a year in interest and have a face value of
$75. American Express stock was trading at $26.87{ the last trading
day before the proposal.
   _A share of preferred stock that will entitle the holder to any
dividends declared by the company in excess of the current dividend.
For American Express, that would be anything above 84 cents a year.
The preferred share could also be redeemed in 2019 for a nominal
price expected to be $2.
   _A stock appreciation certificate that will give the holder the
right to purchase for cash a share of the company's stock in 2019
for the principal amount of the bond plus the preferred share. In
the American Express example, that would be $77.
   It is expected that, subject to appropriate approvals, the
unbundled stock unit, each of its parts and a security that combines
the preferred share and the stock appreciation certificate would be
traded on the New York Stock Exchange, just as the company's stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
