<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TradeTalks Bjt   12-09 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade Talks, Bjt,0686</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Talks End With Only Tentative Gains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World trade talks ended inconclusively Friday,
with tentative gains in many areas but no sign of compromise on the
critical issue of farm supports.
   ``I suppose we could say it's a semi-success,'' said John
Crosbie, minister of international trade for host Canada.
   Trade ministers agreed to postpone final action until the first
week in April, hoping a way will be found in the meantime to break a
deadlock between the United States and European Economic Community
over agriculture.
   Top officials from 103 nations _ including 90 trade ministers _
came to Montreal to prod along the four-year Uruguay Round of
free-trade talks under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   This is the most ambitious round of free-trade talks since
formation of the GATT after World War II, and negotiators are
discovering deep sensitivities over agriculture, which had been
largely exempted from scrutiny until now.
   The four-month delay in the so-called midterm review of the
Uruguay Round meant that progress was frozen in 11 areas of
tentative agreement, including important ones such as freeing trade
in services and monitoring nations' trade policies.
   Arthur Dunkel, the director general of the GATT, will seek to
bridge differences over the next four months in the four remaining
areas: agriculture, protection of intellectual property, textile
tariffs and quotas, and escape clauses from GATT rules.
   Dunkel expressed optimism that he could persuade the American and
European negotiators to yield by appealing to their guilty
consciences over the impasse on agriculture.
   ``When people have bad conscience it's a good start to make a
deal,'' he said in a news conference.
   The farm deadlock had threatened to derail the entire
negotiations because some nations that depend on farm exports had
warned they would withhold approval of the other agreements unless
they got some progress on agriculture.
   The nations that demanded progress in all areas included
Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Colombia and Uruguay, Hungary and New
Zealand.
   The United States demanded a commitment by all nations to the
eventual elimination of trade-distorting farm subsidies and
barriers, while the EEC said it was willing to cut but not eliminate
such programs.
   The United States said it would not discuss short-term measures
until it got a commitment on the long-term goal, while the EEC said
it would not discuss a long-term goal until short-term measures had
been agreed upon.
   These were some of the tentative accords reached in Montreal,
subject to approval in April:
   _ Import tariffs on most goods would be cut by at least the 30
percent achieved in the last GATT round, which ended in 1979. The
significance of tariff cuts has diminished somewhat along with the
rise in non-tariff barriers.
   _ Trade in services would be liberalized, although developing
nations would be allowed to give their service industries some kind
of extra protection. Sectors to be covered would be decided by May
1989.
   _ To speed up settlement of disputes, all GATT reports on
disputes would have to be completed within 15 months unless the
parties agreed to an extension.
   _ The United States would be permitted to take trade retaliation
outside the GATT rules even if a GATT proceeding on its complaint
was under way.
   _ The legality of countries' trade policies would be reviewed
every two years for the United States, Canada, Japan and EEC
countries; every four years for 16 other countries; and as needed
for all other GATT members.
   _ The GATT's director general would be instructed to seek closer
ties to the World Bank and International Monetary Fund and report
back by September 1989.
   _ Developed countries would lower barriers to imports of tropical
products such as coffee, bananas and rubber from developing nations.
   The EEC said Friday it would go ahead with its concessions on
tropical products and eliminate tariffs on imports from some of the
world's poorest countries without waiting for the April meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
