<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Eastern-Continental     12-09 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern-Continental,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eastern Denies Sales Operation Split Intended To Ease Sale Of
Carrier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines on Friday denied speculation that a
move to break up the sales force it shares with Continential
Airlines is intended to do anything but sell more tickets.
   ``It has absolutely nothing to do with anything except better
customer service and selling our core markets to the public,'' said
Cori Zywotow, Eastern manager of corporate communications marketing.
   But labor officials said there may be other reasons for the move
to separate the two carriers' sales forces, which were combined
after Texas Air Corp. bought both airlines.
   ``It may indicate the company is being readied for sale,'' said
J.B. Stokes, a spokesman for Eastern's Air Line Pilots Association.
   Texas Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo has insisted the money-losing
airline is not for sale. But speculation increased after real estate
magnate Donald Trump negotiated to buy Eastern's most profitable
division, the Northeast shuttle linking Washington, New York and
Boston, for $365 million cash.
   Eastern lost about $234 million in the first nine months of the
year and has laid off about 3,500 employees in recent months.
   Other union officials speculated that the sales change may be an
attempt by Texas Air to keep Miami-based Eastern and Houston-based
Continental from being declared one carrier for labor representation
purposes. The National Mediation Board has been addressing that
matter in hearings since last summer.
   Eastern-Continental Sales was formed when the operations were put
together to improve efficiency. Its representatives called on travel
agents, promoting group packages, charters and special fares offered
by the two carriers.
   ``This was one of the things where we had great consternation
when we did it,'' Joseph Leonard, Eastern's executive vice president
and chief operating officer, said Thursday. ``We have felt, and the
sales people have told us this, that it's very difficult to sell two
products.''
   Lorenzo says the carriers are independent and he has no plans to
merge them. He turned the chairmanship of Continental over to D.
Joseph Corr, former president of Trans World Airlines, earlier this
week.
   The present sales team will be split in half, Leonard said. Each
will be based at its carrier's headquarters.
   Eastern salespeople will report to Stan Brown, vice president of
passenger sales. Brown will report to Eastern vice president of
marketing George Brennan.
   ``It's really going back and concentrating our energies on
Eastern and emphasizing our sales programs and distinctive
features,'' Zywotow said. ``And we're expecting that with a
dedicated sales force that we can concentrate on our tradtional core
markets'' along the East Coast, Latin America and the Caribbean.
</TEXT>
