<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Miyazawa     12-09 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Miyazawa,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Finance Minister Biggest Casualty Yet of Insider Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa resigned Friday,
the highest-ranking government official to quit in the aftermath of
an insider trading scandal, while critics intensified demands for a
full-scale probe of the share purchases by politicians.
   Miyazawa said he was resigning as finance minister and deputy
premier to take responsibility for conflicting statements in
Parliament regarding his involvement in questionable purchases of
stock of the real estate firm Recruit-Cosmos Co.
   ``My explanations weren't sufficient and I am taking
responsibility,'' Miyazawa told reporters after he informed Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita he was quitting.
   He also said he hoped his resignation would facilitate passage of
a major tax reform package through the Parliament.
   ``Accomplishing tax reform is my mission,'' Miyazawa said. ``It
doesn't matter what happens to me.''
   Takeshita, who is expected to announce a Cabinet shuffle in the
next few weeks, told reporters later that he would assume the
finance portfolio. He refused to comment, however, on how long he
would hold that reponsibility.
   More than a dozen leading politicians, including Takeshita and
former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, have been linked to the
stock profiteering deal devised by businessman Hiromasa Ezoe,
founder of the information conglomerate Recruit Co.
   Ezoe reportedly offered certain individuals the opportunity to
purchase bargain-priced shares in Recruit-Cosmos, a Recruit
affiliate, prior to their over-the-counter listing in October 1986.
Shortly after the shares were offered for public trading, their
value rose sharply and earned large profits for holders, many of
whom were also provided with interest-free financing to buy the
shares.
   Opposition leaders spearheading a probe of the stock deal _
dubbed Recruit-gate as a parallel to the U.S. Watergate scandal _
have charged that politicians were offered the lucrative shares in
return for political favor.
   Miyazawa himself came under fire after delivering several
conflicting reports regarding his former secretary's role in the
incident.
   He initially testified to a parliamentary committee investigating
the scandal that a third party, a friend of his former secretary,
purchased 10,000 Recruit-Cosmos shares and only borrowed the name of
``Miyazawa.''
   He later admitted his ex-secretary actually paid 30 million yen,
or about $246,000, for the shares in September 1986 and sold them
for 52.7 million yen or $431,000 less than a month later after they
were listed without the finance minister's knowledge.
   Miyazawa also insisted the stock purchase was not financed by a
Recruit-linked financial institution but refused to show bank
documents to back up his argument.
   Miyazawa is the largest casualty to date in the five-month-old
scandal that has shaken public confidence in Takeshita government.
   Public support for Takeshita's government dropped to 18 percent
from 30 percent when he assumed office a year ago, according to a
survey released Friday by the mass-circulation newspaper Mainichi
Shimbun.
   The leading opposition Japan Socialist Party and other critics
said Miyazawa's resignation was overdue but renewed demands for a
stepped-up investigation of the scandal.
   The Asahi Shimbun, a leading liberal daily, said it was time for
Takeshita to heed the opinion polls and ``listen to the voice of the
people'' who want the Recruit affair cleared up.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881209-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1955EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Hunts-Settlement     12-09 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hunts-Settlement,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Puts Commission Action Against Hunts On Hold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. Bankruptcy Court judge has approved a
request to forestall action by the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission against two of the Hunt brothers of Dallas while they
work out Chapter 11 reorganization settlements.
   ``We had an order (that) enjoined the Commodity Futures Trading
Commission from proceedings until other matters are resolved,'' said
Judge Harold Abramson of his 36-page opinion handed down Thursday in
the cases of William Herbert Hunt and Nelson Bunker Hunt.
   The CFTC complaint claims the two Dallas businessmen, who filed
for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection in September, and others
manipulated the price of silver futures between fall 1979 and March
1980.
   Silver prices collapsed to $10 an ounce on March 27, 1980, after
previously hitting a high of $52 an ounce.
   Tom Whitaker, vice president of Hunt Energy and a spokesman for
the brothers, said the Hunts are pleased with Abramson's decision.
   ``Our ongoing intent is still intact _ that is to get all these
proceedings into one forum,'' he said.
   Whitaker estimated it could be 12 to 14 months before the
bankruptcy court matters are resolved. Attorneys for the Hunts filed
statements of financial affairs and schedules of assets and
liabilities in U.S. Bankruptcy Court last month.
   Now creditors have until mid-January to file claims with the
court, Whitaker said.
   Angela G. Tese, a New York bankruptcy attorney whose firm Cole &
Deitz has been observing the Hunt case, said Abramson's decision
means damages and claims against the brothers take precedence over
fines and penalties that might be imposed.
   ``The decision of the bankruptcy court judge is not an unusual
one at all,'' Ms. Tese said. ``It's in keeping with the spirit of
the bankruptcy code.''
   She said the decision apparently does not mean the CFTC will drop
its civil complaint against the Hunts. ``It's possible that they
will proceed at some later date,'' she said.
   The CFTC general counsel, who is handling the case, did not
immediately return telephone calls to The Associated Press on Friday.
   In September, administrative law Judge Arthur L. Shipe ruled that
the Hunts' personal bankruptcy court filings did not automatically
block the government's case against the brothers.
   The CFTC's complaint is the biggest market manipulation case ever
filed by the commission. If the Hunts lose, they could face fines of
$100,000 for each violation of federal commodity laws and be
premanently banned from trading in all futures markets.
   Whitaker also said Abramson's ruling also means the CFTC cannot
press its case until appeals are heard involving the Hunts' lawsuit
with the Peruvian company Minpeco.
   William Herbert Hunt, Nelson Bunker Hunt and their brother, Lamar
Hunt, and others were ordered by a federal court jury in New York to
pay Minpeco, the Peruvian governments' silver mining company, $134.6
million. The company had lost millions of dollars in the silver
price squeeze.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881209-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1723EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-09 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Ends Lower in Choppy European Trading, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mixed against the major foreign
currencies Friday as investors turned their sights toward trade
deficit figures to be released next week.
   Gold prices were also mixed. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a late bid of $422.50 for a troy ounce of gold, up from
$421.30 late Thursday, but the metal declined in overseas trading.
   Dollar trading was lackluster as investors squared their
positions in advance of the weekend and Wednesday's scheduled
release of balance of trade figures for October.
   Jack Barbanel, a market analyst for Gruntal & Co., predicted the
dollar would remain stable until the report is released.
   Overseas, dealers said the dollar was pressured lower by strength
in the West German mark. They said the mark rose amid speculation
that the Bundesbank would raise its Lombard rate by a half
percentage point to 5.5 percent.
   The Lombard rate is the interest the central bank charges
commercial banks for supplemental borrowings in which securities are
used as collateral.
   In Frankfurt, the dollar slipped to 1.7330 marks from 1.7420 late
Thursday. In New York, it fell to 1.73525 marks from 1.73865.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.59 yen to a closing 122.43 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 122.30 yen, and in New York, the dollar rose
to 122.49 yen from 122.30 late Thursday.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.8490 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.8510 Thursday. In New
York, the pound was worth $1.8495, compared with late Thursday's
$1.85505.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's prices, included: 1.4620 Swiss francs, down from 1.4633;
5.9290 French francs, down from 5.9350; 1,282.75 Italian lire, down
from 1,283.00; and 1.19665 Canadian dollars, up from 1.19275.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.4605 Swiss francs, down from 1.4665; 5.9240
French francs, down from 5.9450; 1.9560 Dutch guilders, down from
1.9645; 1,280.25 Italian lire, down from 1,285.00; 1.1970 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1933.
   Gold closed at $422.90 a troy ounce on the Commodity Exchange in
New York, up from 421.30 late Thursday.
   But gold fell earlier in London to a late bid price of $420.75 a
troy ounce, compared with $423.50 late Thursday, and in Zurich, it
closed at a bid $420.30, compared with $423 bid late Thursday.
   In Hong Kong, gold fell $1.24 to close at a bid $423.64.
   Silver bullion prices held steady on the London market where the
metal was trading at a late bid price of $6.16 a troy ounce,
unchanged from Thursday.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, silver rose to $6.175 a
troy ounce from late Thursday's $6.128.
</TEXT>
