<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-09 0785</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0810</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugar Futures Hit New 4-Month High On Brazil Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Sugar futures prices soared to four-month highs Friday on New
York's Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange on expectations of reduced
availabilty of sugar from Brazil, analysts said.
   On other markets, coffee, cattle, pork, energy and
precious-metals futures all gained; grains and soybeans were mixed;
and stock-index futures retreated.
   Sugar for delivery in March settled .55 cent higher at 11.86
cents a pound, the highest daily settlement since Aug. 5, on rumors
that the Brazilian Alcohol and Sugar Institute was preparing to
announce a diversion of substantially more sugar cane from
sugar-making to alcohol production.
   Brazil has embraced the use of gasohol _ an automobile fuel made
from gasoline and alcohol _ like no other country. A recent OPEC
agreement to limit crude-oil production has pushed oil and gasoline
prices higher, which in turn has led to speculation that Brazil will
renew its efforts to encourage gasohol use, analysts said.
   If the government-run Alcohol and Sugar Institute does indeed
announce a greater diversion of sugar cane to alcohol production
scheduled for release on Monday, ``obviously that would mean less
sugar would be available for exporting purposes,'' said Arthur
Stevenson, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New
York.
   Sugar prices had fallen earlier in the week on speculation that
Brazil would soon emerge as a large-volume seller of sugar on the
world market.
   ``This has really turned that situation upside down,'' Stevenson
said.
   Brazilian concerns also fueled a strong rally in the coffee
market. It's been a dry spring so far in Brazil, the world's largest
coffee producer, and fears of drought damage to the 1988-89
Brazilian coffee crop have begun to surface.
   Meanwhile, the weather in Columbia, the No. 2 coffee producer,
has been extremely wet, hampering the harvest of the 1987-88 coffee
crop, said Sandra Kaul, an analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
in New York.
   Coffee settled .29 cent to 1.60 cent higher with March at $1.2727
a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures posted strong gains on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange on bullish signals from the cash markets,
including the first signs of a significant drop in hog slaughters
since early 1987.
   Hog kills for the day totaled 337,000 compared to 339,000 a year
ago, and kills for the week totaled 1.881 million vs. 1.879 million
a year ago.
   The current figures were closer to year-ago figures than the
market has seen in more than a year, and the weekly total was about
3 percent below the previous week, said Tom O'Hare, an analyst in
New York with Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Pork futures traders have been expecting a slowdown in slaughters
for some time, he said, adding: ``anyone with bullish aspirations
had to be licking their lips today.''
   Live cattle settled .95 cent to 1.10 cents higher with December
at 71.82 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .60 cent to 1.08 cents
higher with January at 83 cents a pound; live hogs were .10 cent to
1.13 cents higher with December at 41.60 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .85 cent to 1.23 cents higher with February at 43.25
cents a pound.
   Oil futures finished on a strong note at the New York Mercantile
Exchange on feelings the market is bound to rise if members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries stick by their new
crude-oil production quotas.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 33 cents to 40 cents
higher with January at $15.84 a barrel; heating oil was 1.42 cents
to 1.80 cents higher with January at 49.50 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .53 cent to 1.19 cents higher with January at 44.46
cents a gallon.
   Precious-metals futures followed the oil market higher on New
York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold settled 90 cents to $1.10 higher with February at $427.60 a
troy ounce; silver was 4.2 cents to 4.7 cents higher with March at
$6.305 a troy ounce.
   Wheat and soybean futures prices finished mostly lower while most
corn and oat futures advanced slightly in subdued trading on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents to 4 cents lower with December at $4.27 a
bushel; corn was 2 cents lower to 2} cents higher with December at
$2.59{ a bushel; oats were 2 cents to 3} cents higher with December
at $2.05} a bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents lower to 1 cent higher
with January at $7.73{ a bushel.
   Stock-index futures finished slightly lower on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the
Standard & Poor's 500 index settled .25 point lower at 280.45. Each
point is worth $500.
</TEXT>
