<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CoalProjects     12-09 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Coal Projects,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minnesota Dropped For Clean Coal Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department said Friday it has ended
negotiations with the state of Minnesota aimed at financing one of
the department's ``clean coal'' demonstration projects.
   Instead, the department will begin negotiations with sponsors of
other potential projects in West Virginia, Pennsylvania and Montana.
   Minnesota's Department of Natural Resources had proposed to join
U.S. Steel Corp. in an advanced ironmaking project near Mountain
Iron, Minn., using raw coal in a low-pollution system.
   Most iron production requires the conversion of coal into coke.
   The department said the state had been unable after a year of
trying to win financial backing for its share in the project. The
``clean coal'' program requires local sponsors to put up at least
half the cost of a project.
   The decision to end negotiations does not mean there were any
technical flaws or that the state had been unresponsive, just that
``financial support was not available to allow the project to
proceed in a timely manner.''
   The decision will free about $25 million to $30 million in
federal funds and the department said it would open negotiations
with Combustion Engineering Inc. to extend an existing coal-cleaning
project sponsored by the Electric Power Research Institute at Homer
City, Pa.; with United Coal Co. of Bristol, Va., to demonstrate the
recovery of low-sulfur coal particles from a mine waste disposal
pond at Logan County, W. Va.; and with Western Energy Co. to upgrade
western coals by reducing moisture and sulfur content at Colstrip,
Mont.
   The clean coal program is aimed at financing $5 billion worth of
projects over five years, at least half the money to come from
non-federal sources.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
