<1ST_LINE>r f BC-TheMirage     12-09 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-The Mirage,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Golden Nugget Chief Names New Hotel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Golden Nugget Inc. Chairman Steve Wynn said
Friday he liked the name ``The Mirage'' so much, he paid $500,000 to
use it for his new $585 million resort on the Las Vegas Strip.
   Wynn's announcement ended speculation that the new resort on the
Las Vegas Strip would carry the same name as his hotel-casino in the
downtown's Glitter Gulch.
   Wynn said he and others at the resort knew they had to have a new
name for the new property, or the downtown Golden Nugget would
become know as ``the old one'' and the Strip resort ``the new one.''
   ``It didn't seem fair that this property would be called `the old
one,''' Wynn said.
   The downtown casino dates to 1946, but renovations, a new tower
and luxury suites have pushed the value to $200 million, Wynn said.
   The gaming chief said he settled on the name ``The Mirage''
because of the South Pacific theme, then had to wrestle with the
problem of two other Las Vegas motels that carry the same name.
   Wynn said he went to the owners of the Mirage Motel and La
Mirage, and paid them $250,000 each to change their name as of July
1.
   Wynn said the new property will open early next December. He said
he planned to be a major player in bringing boxing matches to Las
Vegas, joining Hilton and neighboring Caesars Palace as a major
promoter of the events.
   ``We're going to be the third player in the game,'' Wynn said.
   Wynn said he had no intention of selling his downtown property.
   ``It has broken every profit record this year,'' Wynn said.
``It's one of the most successful entities in America.''
   ``Anything's for sale,'' he added, qualifying his statement. ``I
didn't think I'd ever sell Atlantic City, then they came along and
offered me $440 million.''
   Wynn sold his Golden Nugget hotel and casino in Atlantic City to
Bally Corp. in 1987.
   Earlier this summer the Golden Nugget purchased the Nevada Club
in Laughlin, Nev. Wynn plans to build an 1,100-room hotel there.
</TEXT>
