<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 1831EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Bonds     12-09 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bonds,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices ended mixed in slow trading Friday,
reflecting what credit-market strategists called uncertainty over
the direction of interest rates.
   The Treasury's 30-year bond rose about [ point or $1.25 per
$1,000 in face amount, and its yield eased to 8.95 percent from 8.96
percent Thursday.
   One noteworthy development was a rise in rates on short-term
Treasury notes to yield more than that of 30-year bonds, an unusual
shift that last occurred prior to the 1981-82 recession. But the
significance of the so-called inverted yield curve remains unclear.
   Bond strategists said the market was influenced largely by
confusion over whether or when the Federal Reserve will move to
tighten credit conditions in order to pre-empt inflationary pressure
and keep the dollar stable.
   They said the confusion may be clarified somewhat next Wednesday,
when the Commerce Department is scheduled to release the
market-sensitive monthly trade deficit figures for October. A large
imbalance could hurt the dollar's value and force the Fed to raise
interest rates.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
governments fell [ point, intermediate maturities fell \ point and
long-term issues rose [ point, the Telerate Inc., financial
information service reported.
   The movement of a point equals a change of $10 in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Daily Treasury Bond Index, which measures
price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with maturities
of a year or longer, fell 1.45 to 1,135.57.
   In corporate trading, industrials and utilities also fell.
Moody's Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price
movements on 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or
longer, lost 1.00 to 295.10.
   Prices strengthened slightly in the tax-exempt market. The Bond
Buyer index of 40 actively traded municipal bonds was up 7-32 point
at 90 as of 3 p.m. EST. The average yield to maturity was 7.90
percent, down from 7.92 percent Thursday.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 8.14 percent as the
discount fell 8 basis points to 7.88 percent. Yields on six-month
bills rose to 8.67 percent as the discount rose 4 basis points to
8.21 percent. Yields on one-year bills rose to 8.92 percent as the
discount rose 5 basis points to 8.28 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, which is paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, traded at 8{ percent, unchanged from late Thursday.
</TEXT>
