<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AccountingTax     12-09 0123</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Accounting Tax,0127</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Accounting Standards Board Delays Statement 96</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Financial Accounting Standards Board
has voted to delay the effective date of its Statement 96,
``Accounting for Income Taxes,'' until fiscal years starting after
Dec. 15, 1989.
   FASB project manager Robert Wilkens said the board voted to delay
the effective date of Statement 96 to allow more time for companies
and their auditors to understand how to apply the statement.
   The board also voted that a new accounting statement, which will
be issued later this month, will apply only to companies that have
not yet adopted Statement 96. Companies that have already adopted
Statement 96 are not permitted to revert to previously applied
accounting principles, the board ruled.
</TEXT>
