<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 2056EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SoftwareMerger     12-09 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Software Merger,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Independents Join Forces</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two major computer software companies, Duquesne
Systems Inc. of Pittsburgh and Morino Inc. of Vienna, Va., said
Friday they will merge into one of the industry's largest
independent companies.
   ``Our merger represents the first true merger in our industry,
one which brings together two companies with comparable histories,
successes and operating philosophies,'' they said in a joint
statement.
   Both serve the growing market for programs for larger IBM and
compatible mainframe computers.
   Mario M. Morino, chairman of the Virginia company, will become
chairman of the new concern, and Duquesne Chairman Glen F. Chatfield
will become chief executive.
   The combined firm, for which a name was not announced, will be
valued at about $400 million, with 600 employees generating annual
sales of about $100 million. The new company will have cash of
nearly $60 million and no debt.
   ``We'll be attractively positioned for both internal development
and external expansion,'' the two chairmen said.
   Duquesne and Morino will maintain their present headquarters.
They proposed merging no later than March 31 in a stock swap,
pending approval of their boards and shareholders.
   Duquesne Systems was founded in 1970 and over the last five years
has grown at a rate of 60 percent compounded annually, with 1988
revenue of $50.3 million.
   Morino began developing software for other vendors in 1973 and by
June 30, 1988, had reached $44.7 million in revenue.
</TEXT>
