<FILEID>AP-NR-12-09-88 2132EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     12-09 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rebound</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a volatile week, oil futures prices
finished on a strong note.
   ``The market closed at one of its highest levels in a long
time,'' said Richard Redoglia, a trader with Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the January contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, settled
40 cents higher Friday at $15.84 cents a barrel, after falling 30
cents on Thursday during a technical selloff. The contract had been
up and down throughout the week.
   Other contract months also gained ground Friday.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange, the
January contract for wholesale home heating oil closed 1.42 cents
higher at 49.50 cents a gallon. The contract had fallen 0.81 cent on
Thursday.
   Traders said seasonal demand was responsible for the sharp price
increase.
   January unleaded gasoline, which gained 0.17 cent in the previous
session, settled at 44.46 cents a gallon, up 0.53 cent.
   Redoglia said there was ``no real news, no real fundamental
reason'' for Friday's rally.
   ``Except there's a feeling the market can work higher if OPEC
sticks to its quotas,'' he said.
   In late November, the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries reached a production agreement aimed at propping up
sagging worldwide oil prices.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
